{"title_page": "American Express", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Amex||AMEX (disambiguation){{!}}AMEX}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = American Express Company<!--exact legal name as specified in its charter-->\n| logo = American Express logo (2018).svg\n| logo_size = 150px\n| type = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as = {{NYSE|AXP}}<br />[[DJIA|DJIA component]]<br />[[S&P 100|S&P 100 component]]<br />[[S&P 500|S&P 500 component]]\n| predecessor = {{nowrap|Livingston, Fargo & Company}}<br />{{nowrap|Wells, Butterfield & Company}}<br />{{nowrap|Wells & Company}}\n| industry = [[Bank]]ing<br />{{nowrap|[[Financial services]]}}\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|1850|3|18}}, in [[Buffalo, New York]], U.S.\n| location = [[200 Vesey Street]]\n| location_city = [[New York City|New York City, New York]]\n| location_country = United States\n| key_people = {{nowrap|[[Stephen Squeri|Stephen J. Squeri]]}}<br />{{nowrap|{{small|([[Chairman#Public corporations|Chairman]] & [[CEO]])}}}}<br />{{nowrap|Jeffrey C. Campbell}}<br />{{nowrap|{{small|([[Vice president#In business|Executive VP]] & [[CFO]])}}}}\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| products = {{nowrap|[[Charge card]]s}}<br />{{nowrap|[[Credit card]]s}}<br />{{nowrap|[[Traveler's cheque]]s}}<br />{{nowrap|[[Corporate banking]]}}\n| services = [[Financial services|Finance]]<br />[[Insurance]]<br />[[Travel]]\n| revenue = {{increase}} {{US$|43.556 billion|link=yes}} {{small|(2019)<ref name=\"10-K\">{{cite web|url=https://last10k.com/sec-filings/axp#link_fullReport |title=American Express Company 2018 Annual Report (Form 10-K) |date=February 2019 |publisher=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]] |website=last10k.com}}</ref>}}\n| operating_income = {{increase}} {{US$|8.164 billion}} {{small|(2018)<ref name=\"10-K\" />}}\n| net_income = {{increase}} {{US$|6.921 billion}} {{small|(2018)<ref name=\"10-K\" />}}\n| assets = {{increase}} {{US$|188.602 billion}} {{small|(2018)<ref name=\"10-K\" />}}\n| equity = {{increase}} {{US$|22.290 billion}} {{small|(2018)<ref name=\"10-K\" />}}\n| num_employees = 59,000 {{small|(December 2018)<ref name=\"10-K\" />}}\n| homepage = {{URL|https://www.americanexpress.com/}}\n| footnotes = <ref name=PZG>Peter Z. Grossman. ''American Express: The Unofficial History of the People Who Built the Great Financial Empire''. New York: Crown Publishers, 1987. (reprint: Beard Books 2006; {{ISBN|1-58798-283-8}}; Chapter 2.)</ref><ref name=NML>Noel M. Loomis, Wells Fargo. New York: Clarkson N. Potter, Inc., 1968</ref><ref name=\"10-K 2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/4962/000000496220000030/axp-20191231.htm|title=US SEC: Form 10-K American Express Company|publisher=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]]|accessdate=February 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215171453/https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/4962/000000496220000030/axp-20191231.htm|archive-date=February 15, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''American Express Company''', also known as '''Amex''', is an American [[multinational corporation|multinational]] [[financial services]] corporation headquartered at [[200 Vesey Street]] in [[New York City]]. The company was founded in 1850 and is one of the 30 components of the [[Dow Jones Industrial Average]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://money.cnn.com/data/markets/dow/?iid=C_MT_Index | title=Dow Jones Industrial Average | work=[[CNN Business|CNN Money]] | accessdate=October 20, 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014230313/http://money.cnn.com/data/markets/dow/?iid=C_MT_Index | archive-date=October 14, 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref> The company is best known for its [[charge card]], [[credit card]], and [[traveler's cheque]] businesses.\n\nIn 2016, credit cards using the American Express network accounted for 22.9% of the total dollar volume of credit card transactions in the United States.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://wallethub.com/edu/market-share-by-credit-card-network/25531/ | title=Market Share by Credit Card Network | first=Alina | last=Comoreanu | website=Wallet Hub | date=March 7, 2017 | access-date=April 8, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170408171736/https://wallethub.com/edu/market-share-by-credit-card-network/25531/ | archive-date=April 8, 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref> {{as of|2019|December|31|df=US}}, the company had 114.4{{nbsp}}million cards in force, including 54.7{{nbsp}}million cards in force in the United States, each with an average annual spending of $19,972.<ref name=\"10-K 2019\"/>\n\nIn 2017, ''[[Forbes]]'' named American Express as the 23rd most valuable brand in the world (and the highest within financial services), estimating the brand to be worth US$24.5{{nbsp}}billion.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/powerful-brands/list/#tab:rank_industry:Financial%20Services |title=Forbes 2017 Rankings - The World's Most Valuable Brands |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180308010404/https://www.forbes.com/powerful-brands/list/#tab:rank_industry:Financial%20Services |archive-date=March 8, 2018}}</ref> In 2020, ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' magazine ranked American Express at number 9 on their Fortune List of the Top 100 Companies to Work For in 2020 based on an employee survey of satisfaction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/best-companies-to-work-for-based-on-employee-satisfaction-fortune-2020-2|title=The 25 best companies to work for, based on employee satisfaction|publisher=[[Business Insider]]|author=Jessica Snouwaert|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe company's [[logo]], adopted in 1958, is a [[gladiator]] or [[centurion]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.companylogos.ws/americanexpresslogo.html |title= American Express Logo Review |year= 2008 |publisher= Company Logos |accessdate= June 25, 2011 |quote= The initial trademark of 1958 described the gladiator in the American Express logo as a gladiator on a shield whereas the current American Express website lists the logo character as a Gladiator Head Design. However, there are many who believe that the gladiator is a centurion ... |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100920014842/http://companylogos.ws/americanexpresslogo.html |archive-date= September 20, 2010 |url-status= dead }}</ref> whose image appears on the company's [[traveler's cheque]]s, [[charge card]]s and [[credit card]]s.\n\n=pyae=Early history==\n[[File:American Express Shipping Receipt 1853.jpg|thumb|right|285px|American Express Co. early shipping [[receipt]]s (1853, 1869)]]\n[[File:American Express Company 1865.JPG|thumb|Share of the American Express Company, issued 13. October 1865; signed by William G. Fargo as Secretary and Henry Wells as President]]\nIn 1850, American Express was started as an [[express mail]] business in [[Buffalo, New York]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Recognizing Responsibility: American Express Company 2007/2008 Corporate Citizenship Report|url=http://about.americanexpress.com/csr/docs/cresp.pdf|publisher=American Express Co.|accessdate=2012-07-25|page=8|quote=In 1850, three men\u2014Henry Wells, William G. Fargo and John Butterfield\u2014founded an express company in Buffalo, New York, to forward freight and valuables across the united States.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111116062825/http://about.americanexpress.com/csr/docs/cresp.pdf|archive-date=November 16, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> It was founded as a joint stock corporation by the merger of the express companies owned by [[Henry Wells]] (Wells & Company), [[William G. Fargo]] (Livingston, Fargo & Company), and [[John Warren Butterfield]] (Wells, Butterfield & Company, the successor earlier in 1850 of Butterfield, Wasson & Company).<ref name=PZG/><ref name=NML/> Wells and Fargo also started [[History of Wells Fargo|Wells Fargo & Co.]]<!-- Link should be to \"History of Wells Fargo\" article as it relates to the original Wells, Fargo & Company founded in 1852 by two of Amex's founders (and ultimately acquired by Amex). \"Wells Fargo & Co.\" redirects to the \"Wells Fargo\" article, which is *only* about the post-1998 bank (its holding company uses that name); other than common historical roots in the 1852 Wells, Fargo & Company, there is NO connection between Amex and modern-day Wells Fargo. --> in 1852 when Butterfield and other directors objected to the proposal that American Express extend its operations to California.\n\nAmerican Express initially established its headquarters in a building at the intersection of Jay Street and [[Hudson Street (Manhattan)|Hudson Street]] in what was later called the [[Tribeca]] section of Manhattan. For years it enjoyed a virtual monopoly on the movement of express shipments (goods, securities, currency, etc.) throughout New York State. In 1874, American Express moved its headquarters to 65 Broadway in what was becoming the [[Financial District, Manhattan|Financial District]] of Manhattan, a location it was to retain through two buildings.<ref name=\"Citycyclopedia\">Kenneth T. Jackson. ''The Encyclopedia of New York City''. The New York Historical Society: [[Yale University Press]], 1995. P. 23.</ref>\n\n===American Express buildings===\nIn 1854, the American Express Co. purchased a lot on Vesey Street in New York City as the site for its stables. The company's first New York headquarters was an 1858 marble Italianate palazzo at 55\u201361 [[Hudson Street (Manhattan)|Hudson Street]], which had a busy freight depot on the ground story with a spur line from the [[Hudson River Railroad]]. A stable was constructed in 1867, five blocks north at 4\u20138 Hubert Street.\n\nThe company prospered sufficiently that headquarters were moved in 1874 from the wholesale shipping district to the budding Financial District, and into rented offices in two five-story brownstone commercial buildings at 63 and 65 Broadway that were owned by the Harmony family.<ref name=\"LANDMARKS\">New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission; [http://www.nyc.gov/html/lpc/downloads/pdf/reports/amerexpress.pdf December 12, 1995, Designation List 269; LP-1932] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020225802/http://www.nyc.gov/html/lpc/downloads/pdf/reports/amerexpress.pdf |date=October 20, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1880, American Express built a new warehouse behind the Broadway Building at 46 Trinity Place. The designer is unknown, but it has a fa\u00e7ade of brick arches that are reminiscent of pre-skyscraper New York. American Express has long been out of this building, but it still bears a [[terracotta]] seal with the American Express Eagle.<ref>White, Norval & Willensky, Elliot; ''[[American Institute of Architects|AIA]] Guide to New York City'', 4th Edition; New York Chapter, American Institute of Architects; Crown Publishers/Random House. 2000. {{ISBN|0-8129-3106-8}}; {{ISBN|0-8129-3107-6}}. p.23.</ref> In 1890\u201391 the company constructed a new ten-story building by [[Edward H. Kendall]] on the site of its former headquarters on [[Hudson Street (Manhattan)|Hudson Street]].\n\nBy 1903, the company had assets of some $28&nbsp;million, second only to the [[Citibank|National City Bank of New York]] among [[financial institution]]s in the city. To reflect this, the company purchased the Broadway buildings and site.<ref name=\"LANDMARKS\" />\n[[File:American Express Company Building 65 Broadway entrance.jpg|thumb|250x250px|The [[65 Broadway|American Express Company Building]] at 65 Broadway \u2013 the former headquarters of the American Express Company]]\n\nAt the end of the Wells-Fargo reign in 1914, an aggressive new president, George Chadbourne Taylor (1868\u20131923), who had worked his way up through the company over the previous thirty years, decided to build a new headquarters. The old buildings, dubbed by [[the New York Times]] as \"among the ancient landmarks\" of lower Broadway, were inadequate for such a rapidly expanding concern.\n\nAfter some delays due to the First World War, the 21-story [[Neoclassicism|neo-classical]] [[65 Broadway|American Express Co. Building]] was constructed in 1916\u201317 to the design of James L. Aspinwall, of the firm of Renwick, Aspinwall & Tucker, the successor to the architectural practice of the eminent [[James Renwick, Jr.]]. The building consolidated the two lots of the former buildings with a single address: [[65 Broadway]]. This building was part of the \"Express Row\" section of lower Broadway at the time. The building completed the continuous masonry wall of its block-front and assisted in transforming Broadway into the \"canyon\" of neo-classical masonry office towers familiar to this day.<ref name=\"AIA22\">{{cite AIA5|page=22}}</ref> American Express sold this building in 1975, but retained travel services there. The building was also the headquarters over the years of other prominent firms, including investment bankers [[J. & W. Seligman & Co.|J.& W. Seligman & Co]]. (1940\u201374), the [[American Bureau of Shipping]], a maritime concern (1977\u201386), and later J.J. Kenny, and [[Standard & Poor's]], the latter of which renamed the building for itself.<ref name=\"LANDMARKS\" /><ref name=\"AIA22\" />\n\n===Nationwide expansion===\nAmerican Express extended its reach nationwide by arranging affiliations with other express companies (including [[History of Wells Fargo|Wells Fargo]]<!-- Link should be to \"History of Wells Fargo\" article as it relates to the original Wells, Fargo & Company founded in 1852 by two of Amex's founders (and ultimately acquired by Amex). The \"Wells Fargo\" article is *only* about the post-1998 bank; other than common historical roots in the 1852 Wells, Fargo & Company, there is NO connection between Amex and modern-day Wells Fargo. --> \u2013 the replacement for the two former companies that merged to form American Express), railroads, and steamship companies.<ref name=\"Citycyclopedia\" />\n\n===Financial services===\nIn 1857, American Express started its expansion in the area of financial services by launching a [[money order]] business<ref name=\"Citycyclopedia\" /> to compete with the [[United States Post Office]]'s money orders.\n\n[[File:Amer express dog 1890.jpg|thumb|right|200px|The American Express logo in 1890 depicting a watchdog lying on top of a shipping trunk to symbolise trust and security]]\nSometime between 1888 and 1890, [[J. C. Fargo]] took a trip to Europe and returned frustrated and infuriated. Despite the fact that he was president of American Express and that he carried with him traditional [[letter of credit|letters of credit]], he found it difficult to obtain cash anywhere except in major cities. Fargo went to [[Marcellus Flemming Berry]] and asked him to create a better solution than the letter of credit. Berry introduced the American Express [[traveler's cheque|Traveler's Cheque]] which was launched in 1891 in denominations of $10, $20, $50, and $100.<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,866900-7,00.html Host With The Most] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100616020709/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,866900-7,00.html |date=June 16, 2010 }}, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', April 9, 1956 issue</ref>\n\nTraveler's cheques established American Express as a truly international company. In 1914, at the onset of [[World War I]], American Express in Europe was among the few companies to honor the letters of credit (issued by various banks) held by Americans in Europe, because other financial institutions refused to assist these stranded travelers.\n\nThe British government appointed American Express its official agent at the beginning of World War I.  They were to deliver letters, money and relief parcels to British prisoners of war.  Their employees went into camps to cash drafts for both British and French prisoners and arranged for them to receive money from home.\n\nBy the end of the war they were delivering 150 tonnes of parcels per day to prisoners in six countries.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Barham|first1=Peter|title=The impact of the Great War in 1916.|journal=Great Eastern Journal|date=January 2016|issue=165|page=14}}</ref>\n\n===Loss of railroad express business===\nAmerican Express became one of the monopolies that [[Theodore Roosevelt|President Theodore Roosevelt]] had the [[Interstate Commerce Commission]] (ICC) investigated during his administration. The interest of the ICC was drawn to its strict control of the railroad express business. However, the solution did not come immediately to hand.<ref name=\"Citycyclopedia\" /> The solution to this problem came as a coincidence to other problems during World War I.\n\nDuring the winter of 1917, the United States suffered a severe coal shortage and on December 26 [[President of the United States|President]] [[Woodrow Wilson]] commandeered the railroads on behalf of the United States government to move [[United States Armed Forces|federal troops]], their supplies, and coal. Treasury Secretary [[William Gibbs McAdoo]] was assigned the task of consolidating the railway lines for the [[war effort]]. All contracts between express companies and railroads were nullified and McAdoo proposed that all existing express companies be consolidated into a single company to serve the country's needs. This ended American Express's express business, and removed them from the ICC's interest. The result was that a new company called the [[Railway Express Agency|American Railway Express Agency]] formed in July 1918. The new entity took custody of all the pooled equipment and property of existing express companies (the largest share of which, 40%, came from American Express, who had owned the rights to the express business over {{convert|71280|mi|km}} of railroad lines, and had 10,000 offices, with over 30,000 employees).\n\n===Investment banking===\nDuring the 1980s, American Express embarked on an effort to become a financial services supercompany and made a number of acquisitions to create an investment banking arm. In mid-1981 it purchased [[Sanford I. Weill]]'s [[Shearson Loeb Rhoades]], the second largest securities firm in the United States to form [[Shearson/American Express]].\n\n[[File:Shearson Lehman Logo.png|170px|Shearson Lehman logo|thumb|right]]\n\nAfter the purchase of Shearson, Weill was given the position of president of American Express in 1983. Weill grew increasingly unhappy with responsibilities within American Express and his conflicts with American Express' CEO [[James D. Robinson III]]. Weill soon realized that he was not positioned to be named CEO and left in August 1985. In 1984, American Express acquired the [[investment banking]] and trading firm [[Lehman Brothers|Lehman Brothers Kuhn Loeb]], and added it to the Shearson family, creating Shearson Lehman/American Express.  It was Lehman's CEO and former trader [[Lewis Glucksman]] who would next lead Shearson Lehman/American Express.\n\nIn 1984, Shearson/American Express purchased the 90-year-old [[Investors Diversified Services]], bringing with it a fleet of financial advisors and investment products. In 1988, Shearson Lehman acquired the brokerage firm [[E.F. Hutton & Co.]]. E.F. Hutton was merged with the investment banking business and the investment banking arm was renamed [[Shearson Lehman Hutton, Inc.]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/12/03/business/shearson-reported-to-acquire-hutton-in-a-1-billion-deal.html |title=Shearson Reported To Acquire Hutton In a $1 Billion Deal |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 3, 1987 |first=Robert J. |last=Cole |access-date=February 5, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161110012931/http://www.nytimes.com/1987/12/03/business/shearson-reported-to-acquire-hutton-in-a-1-billion-deal.html |archive-date=November 10, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nHowever, when [[Harvey Golub]] became CEO of American Express in 1993, American Express decided to get out of the investment banking business and negotiated the sale of Shearson's retail brokerage and [[Investment management|asset management]] business to [[Primerica]]. The Shearson business was merged with Primerica's [[Smith Barney]] to create [[Smith Barney Shearson]]. Ultimately, the Shearson name was dropped in 1994.<ref name=shearsondropped>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/11/10/business/shearson-name-may-disappear.html |title=Shearson Name may Disappear |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=November 10, 1993 |agency=Bloomberg News |access-date=February 5, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161110013647/http://www.nytimes.com/1993/11/10/business/shearson-name-may-disappear.html |archive-date=November 10, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, American Express spun off of the remaining investment banking and institutional businesses as [[Lehman Brothers|Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc]].{{citation needed|date=August 2019}} After almost fifteen years of independence, Lehman Brothers [[Bankruptcy of Lehman Brothers|filed for bankruptcy protection in 2008]] as part of the [[financial crisis of 2007\u201308]].\n\n==Recent history==\n{{unreferenced section|date=September 2019}}\nFormer CEO [[Kenneth Chenault]] took over leadership of American Express in 2001, from [[Harvey Golub]], CEO from 1993 to 2001. Prior to that, the company was headed by [[James D. Robinson III]] from 1977 to 1993, [[Howard L. Clark Sr.]] from 1960 to 1977, and [[Ralph Reed (American Express)|Ralph Reed]] from 1944 to 1960. Current CEO: Stephen Joseph Squeri since February 1, 2018.{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n===Charge card services===\n[[File:World Financial Center.jpg|left|thumb|200px|[[American Express Tower]] (tallest, left) in New York City]]\nAmerican Express executives discussed the possibility of launching a travel [[charge card]] as early as 1946, but it was not until [[Diners Club]] launched a card in March 1950, that American Express began to seriously consider the possibility. At the end of 1957, American Express CEO [[Ralph Reed (American Express)|Ralph Reed]] decided to get into the card business, and by the launch date of October 1, 1958, public interest had become so significant that 250,000 cards were issued prior to the official launch date. The card was launched with an annual fee of $6, $1 higher than Diners Club, to be seen as a premium product. The first cards were made of paper, with the account number and cardmember's name typed. In 1959, American Express began issuing embossed [[ISO/IEC 7810]] plastic cards, an industry first.<ref name=ourstory>{{cite web|website=American Express|url=https://secure.cmax.americanexpress.com/Internet/GlobalCareers/Staffing/Shared/Files/our_story_3.pdf|title=Our Story|access-date=September 8, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303203130/https://secure.cmax.americanexpress.com/Internet/GlobalCareers/Staffing/Shared/Files/our_story_3.pdf|archive-date=March 3, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1966, American Express introduced the Gold Card.<ref name=ourstory/> In 1984, the company launched the Platinum Card, clearly defining different [[market segment]]s within its own business, a practice that has proliferated across a broad array of industries.<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://about.americanexpress.com/news/pr/2011/pct.aspx | title=American Express Platinum Card Packs on the Perks for International Travelers | publisher=American Express | date=April 5, 2011 | access-date=April 12, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170520201642/http://about.americanexpress.com/news/pr/2011/pct.aspx | archive-date=May 20, 2017 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> The Platinum Card was billed as super-exclusive and had a $250 annual fee ({{as of|September 2019|lc=yes}}, the fee is $550<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanexpress.com/us/credit-cards/card/platinum/|website=American Express|title=The Platinum Card|access-date=December 1, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016202121/https://www.americanexpress.com/us/credit-cards/card/platinum/|archive-date=October 16, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>). It was offered by invitation only to American Express customers with at least two years of tenure, significant spending, and excellent payment history; {{as of|2019|lc=yes}}, it is open to applicants on request. In 1987, American Express introduced the Optima card, its first credit card product that did not have to be paid in full at the end of the month.\n\nAmerican Express formed a venture with [[Warner Communications]] in 1979, called [[Warner-Amex Satellite Entertainment]], which created MTV, [[Nickelodeon]], and [[The Movie Channel]]. The partnership lasted only until 1984. The properties were sold to [[Viacom (1971\u20132005)|Viacom]] soon after.\n\nIn April 1992, American Express spun off its former subsidiary, [[First Data Corp.]], in an [[initial public offering]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstdata.com/en_us/about-first-data/media/first-data-history.html|website=First Data|title=First Data History|access-date=April 12, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170317144814/https://www.firstdata.com/en_us/about-first-data/media/first-data-history.html|archive-date=March 17, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, the Optima True Grace card was introduced. The card was unique in that it offered a [[grace period]] on all purchases whether a balance was carried on the card or not (as opposed to traditional revolving credit cards which charge interest on new purchases if so much as $1 was carried over).<ref>{{cite web | url=https://articles.latimes.com/1994-09-07/business/fi-35691_1_grace-period | title=American Express Launches New Credit Card | first=Kathy M. | last=Kristof | newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] | date=September 7, 1994 | access-date=April 12, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170413073208/http://articles.latimes.com/1994-09-07/business/fi-35691_1_grace-period | archive-date=April 13, 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref> The card was discontinued a few years later; the now discontinued{{when|date=August 2019}} One from American Express card offered a similar feature called \"Interest Protection\".\n\n===\"Boston Fee Party\"===\nFrom the early 1980s until the early 1990s, American Express was known for cutting its [[interchange fee]] (also known as a \"discount rate\") to merchants and restaurants if they accepted only American Express and no other credit or charge cards. This prompted competitors such as [[Visa Inc.|Visa]] and [[Mastercard]] to cry foul for a while as the tactics \"locked\" restaurants into American Express. Capitalizing on this elitist image, American Express frequently mentioned such exclusive partnerships in its advertising.<ref>{{cite video|publisher=[[YouTube]]|title=American Express Super Bowl XXV ad feat. Dana Carvey & Jon Lovitz - Travelling (1991)|date=April 16, 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XeSnqSfRkgE|access-date=September 28, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323090235/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XeSnqSfRkgE|archive-date=March 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAside from some holdouts including [[Neiman Marcus]] (which continued exclusivity until 2011), the practice largely ended in 1991. A group of restaurants in [[Boston]] stopped accepting American Express while accepting and encouraging the use of Visa and Mastercard, including some that were exclusive to American Express. The rationale was due to far lower fees as compared with American Express' fees at the time (which were about 4% for each transaction versus around 1.2% at the time for Visa and Mastercard). The revolt, known as the \"Boston Fee Party\" (alluding to the [[Boston Tea Party]]), spread to over 250 restaurants across the United States, including restaurants in other cities such as [[New York City]], [[Chicago]], and [[Los Angeles]]. Visa offered to pay the Fee Party's legal bills, and [[Discover Card]] was able to increase their acceptance among Boston restaurants by 375%. Kenneth Chenault, then head of Travel Related Services prior to becoming American Express CEO, cut fees to bring these restaurants back into the fold.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.bloomberg.com/features/2015-how-amex-lost-costco/| title=How Bad Will It Get for American Express?| last1=Leonard| first1=Devin| last2=Dexheimer| first2=Elizabeth| publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]]| date=October 15, 2015| access-date=March 5, 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170413071646/https://www.bloomberg.com/features/2015-how-amex-lost-costco/| archive-date=April 13, 2017| url-status=live}}</ref> American Express then shifted its focus from exclusivity to broadening acceptance, adding mainstream merchants like [[Walmart]] to the American Express network.\n\n===Conversion to bank holding company===\nOn November 10, 2008, during the [[financial crisis of 2007\u20132008]], the company won [[Federal Reserve System]] approval to convert to a [[bank holding company]], making it eligible for government help under the [[Troubled Asset Relief Program]].<ref name=\"American-Express-Dec-2008-8-K\">{{cite web| url=http://pdf.secdatabase.com/2714/0001104659-08-078273.pdf| title=American Express, Form 8-K, Current Report, Filing Date Dec 23, 2008| publisher=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission|Securities and Exchange Commission]]| accessdate=January 6, 2013| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512070738/http://pdf.secdatabase.com/2714/0001104659-08-078273.pdf| archive-date=May 12, 2013| url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"lanman\">{{cite news |title=American Express Gets Fed Approval to Convert to Bank |network=[[NPR]] |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=96844962 |air-date=November 11, 2008 |series=[[Morning Edition]] |first=Ari |last=Shapiro |author-link=Ari Shapiro |accessdate=February 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205130124/https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=96844962 |archive-date=February 5, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> At that time, American Express had total consolidated assets of about $127{{nbsp}}billion.<ref name=\"lanman\"/> In June 2009, $3.39{{nbsp}}billion in TARP funds were repaid plus $74.4{{nbsp}}million in dividend payments. In July 2009, the company ended its obligations under TARP by buying back $340{{nbsp}}million in Treasury warrants.<ref name=\"American-Express-Jul-2009-8-K\">{{cite web| url=http://edgar.secdatabase.com/2182/496209000030/filing-main.htm| title=American Express, Form 8-K, Current Report, Filing Date Jul 29, 2009| publisher=Securities and Exchange Commission| accessdate=January 6, 2013| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512074543/http://edgar.secdatabase.com/2182/496209000030/filing-main.htm| archive-date=May 12, 2013| url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=AmEx Gets Out of TARP; Pays $340M for Warrants| url=http://wallstreetpit.com/8963-amex-gets-out-of-tarp-pays-340m-for-warrants| publisher=wallstreetpit.com| date=July 29, 2009| accessdate=August 21, 2009| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100205135530/http://wallstreetpit.com/8963-amex-gets-out-of-tarp-pays-340m-for-warrants| archive-date=February 5, 2010| url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=AmEx gets out of TARP| url=http://money.cnn.com/2009/07/29/news/economy/american_express_tarp.reut/index.htm| website=[[CNN Business|CNN Money]]| date=July 29, 2009| accessdate=August 21, 2009| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514205159/http://money.cnn.com/2009/07/29/news/economy/american_express_tarp.reut/index.htm| archive-date=May 14, 2011| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Charging order controversy in the UK===\nIn November 2010, the UK division of American Express was cautioned by the [[Office of Fair Trading]] for the use of controversial [[charging order]]s against those in debt.<ref>{{cite web| title=OFT Warns Credit Card Providers Off 'Charging Orders'| url=http://www.choose.net/money/guide/news/oft-warns-against-charging-orders.html| publisher=Choose| date=November 10, 2010| access-date=January 26, 2012| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302053525/http://www.choose.net/money/guide/news/oft-warns-against-charging-orders.html| archive-date=March 2, 2012| url-status=live}}</ref> The regulator said that the company was one of four companies who were encouraging customers to turn their unsecured credit card debts into a form of secured debt.\n\n===CFPB enforcement action===\nIn October 2012, The [[Consumer Financial Protection Bureau]] (CFPB) announced an enforcement action with orders requiring three American Express subsidiaries to refund an estimated $85{{nbsp}}million to approximately 250,000 customers for illegal card practices between 2003 and 2012. Allegations included that American Express made misleading statements regarding signup bonuses, charged unlawful late fees, discriminated against applicants due to age, and failed to report consumer complaints to regulators.<ref>{{cite press release| url=https://www.consumerfinance.gov/about-us/newsroom/cfpb-orders-american-express-to-pay-85-million-refund-to-consumers-harmed-by-illegal-credit-card-practices/| title=CFPB Orders American Express to Pay $85 Million Refund to Consumers Harmed by Illegal Credit Card Practices| publisher=[[Consumer Financial Protection Bureau]] (CFPB)| date=October 1, 2012| access-date=April 12, 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170413074426/https://www.consumerfinance.gov/about-us/newsroom/cfpb-orders-american-express-to-pay-85-million-refund-to-consumers-harmed-by-illegal-credit-card-practices/| archive-date=April 13, 2017| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Costco exclusivity arrangement (2004\u20132016)===\nBeginning in 2004, [[Costco]] issued co-branded American Express cards which also doubled as a membership card. Costco ended this arrangement in 2016, in the United States and in 2015, in Canada. The cards did not have annual fees and offered cash back in form of in-store rebates on certain tiers of purchases. The TrueEarnings cards issued by Costco in the United States were an extension of an exclusive credit card network deal between Costco and American Express dating from 1999. Costco was the last major U.S. merchant that accepted American Express cards exclusively. In November 2011, [[Neiman Marcus]], which gave similar general-purpose card exclusivity to American Express since 1987, began accepting Visa and [[Mastercard]].{{citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\nCostco's Canadian stores ended its exclusive deal with American Express in January 2015, in favor of one with [[Capital One]] and Mastercard.<ref>{{cite news| last1=Schecter| first1=Barbara| last2=Leong| first2=Melissa| title=Costco to stop accepting American Express cards in Canada, switches to Capital One and Mastercard| url=http://business.financialpost.com/news/retail-marketing/costco-canada-american-express| accessdate=October 29, 2017| work=[[Financial Post]]| date=September 18, 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103213312/http://business.financialpost.com/news/retail-marketing/costco-canada-american-express| archive-date=January 3, 2018| url-status=live}}</ref> Capital One did not buy accounts and balances from American Express, which required Costco Canada members to apply for the new cards instead of automatically qualifying.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/capital-one-said-to-replace-amex-as-costcos-canada-card-issuer/article20665637/| title=Costco Canada switches to MasterCard from AmEx| first=Marina| last=Strauss| newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]]| date=September 18, 2014| access-date=August 24, 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516160940/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/capital-one-said-to-replace-amex-as-costcos-canada-card-issuer/article20665637/| archive-date=May 16, 2017| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn February 12, 2015, it was announced that the partnership between American Express and Costco in the United States would dissolve March 31, 2016, which was later extended to June 19, 2016. By March 2, 2015, Costco announced that [[Citigroup]] would become the exclusive issuer of Costco's credit cards and that [[Visa Inc.]] would replace American Express as the exclusive credit card network accepted at Costco's stores in the United States. The Costco deal with Visa began on June 20, 2016, and in addition to the new Citi card, Costco accepted all other Visa cards.<ref>{{cite news| newspaper=[[San Antonio Express-News]]| url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/business/national/article/What-to-expect-from-Costco-s-new-deal-with-Visa-6119462.php| title=What to Expect From Costco's New Deal With Visa| access-date=January 22, 2016| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201221834/http://www.mysanantonio.com/business/national/article/What-to-expect-from-Costco-s-new-deal-with-Visa-6119462.php| archive-date=February 1, 2016| url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Los Angeles Times\">{{cite news| url=https://latimes.com/business/la-fi-costco-visa-20150302-story.html| title=Costco names Citi, Visa as new credit card partners after AmEx deal ends| work=[[Los Angeles Times]]| date=March 2, 2015| accessdate=July 1, 2015| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150703133135/http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-costco-visa-20150302-story.html| archive-date=July 3, 2015| url-status=live}}</ref> All TrueEarnings card accounts and balances held by American Express were sold to Citigroup, and new Costco Anywhere Visa cards were sent to Costco members prior to the switch date. Concurrent with the switch to Visa, Costco no longer accepted American Express in stores, at Costco.com, or through Costco Travel.\n\nThe Costco partnership represented 8%, or $80{{nbsp}}billion, of American Express' billed business and about 20%, or about $14{{nbsp}}billion, of its interest-bearing credit portfolio, according to Richard Shane of JPMorgan Chase & Co.<ref name=\"Los Angeles Times\"/> The impact of losing the Costco card accounts was significant; in the first quarter without Costco cards, company profit dropped 10% and revenue dropped 5% compared to the previous year.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.bizjournals.com/seattle/news/2016/10/21/costco-american-express-citigroup-credit-card.html| title=The Costco effect: How American Express is faring after losing co-branded credit cards| first=Coral| last=Garnick| newspaper=Puget Sound Business Journal| date=October 21, 2016| access-date=March 15, 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316204246/http://www.bizjournals.com/seattle/news/2016/10/21/costco-american-express-citigroup-credit-card.html| archive-date=March 16, 2017| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Centurion Lounges ===\nAmerican Express has a network of Centurion Lounges at major airports to cater to their Platinum and Centurion card holders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.creditcards.com/credit-card-news/centurion-lounges-guide.php|title=Guide to Centurion lounges|date=2019-02-27|website=CreditCards.com|access-date=2019-08-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190804223536/https://www.creditcards.com/credit-card-news/centurion-lounges-guide.php|archive-date=August 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Free services include concierge, food and alcohol, wifi, etc. The first lounge opened in 2013, at [[Las Vegas McCarran Airport|McCarran Airport]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rewardexpert.com/blog/american-express-centurion-lounge/|title=The Oasis at the Airport: American Express Centurion Lounge|date=2015-01-05|website=The Source for Maximizing Award Travel|access-date=2019-08-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190804230346/https://www.rewardexpert.com/blog/american-express-centurion-lounge/|archive-date=August 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2019 American Express acquired lounge app LoungeBuddy <ref>{{cite news |last1=Liddington-Cox |first1=Alexander |title=Aussie entrepreneur's airline lounge app is snapped up by American Express |url=https://www.businessinsider.com.au/american-express-snaps-up-aussie-entrepreneurs-airline-lounge-app-2019-3 |accessdate=3 November 2019 |work=Business Insider Australia |publisher=Pedestrian Group |date=14 March 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191103234616/https://www.businessinsider.com.au/american-express-snaps-up-aussie-entrepreneurs-airline-lounge-app-2019-3 |archive-date=November 3, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Finances ==\nFor the fiscal year 2017, American Express reported earnings of US$2.634{{nbsp}}billion, with an annual revenue of US$35.583{{nbsp}}billion, an increase of 5.2% over the previous fiscal cycle. Its shares traded at over $83 per share, and its market capitalization was valued at over US$86.5{{nbsp}}billion in October 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.macrotrends.net/stocks/charts/AXP/american-express/revenue|title=American Express Revenue 2006-2018 {{!}} AXP|website=www.macrotrends.net|access-date=2018-10-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181030170433/https://www.macrotrends.net/stocks/charts/AXP/american-express/revenue|archive-date=October 30, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> American Express ranked {{No.|86}} in the 2018 [[Fortune 500]] list of the largest United States corporations by total revenue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fortune.com/fortune500/list/|title=Fortune 500 Companies 2018: Who Made the List|website=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]|access-date=2018-11-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181110190356/http://fortune.com/fortune500/list/|archive-date=November 10, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable float-left\" style=\"text-align: right;\"\n!Year\n!Revenue<br />in mil. USD$\n!Net income<br />in mil. USD$\n!Total Assets<br />in mil. USD$\n!Price per Share<br />in USD$\n!Employees\n|-\n|2005\n|24,404\n|3,734\n|113,960\n|39.22\n|\n|-\n|2006\n|27,692\n|3,707\n|128,329\n|44.74\n|\n|-\n|2007\n|31,540\n|3,986\n|149,743\n|49.21\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|31,920\n|2,684\n|126,074\n|31.91\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|26,543\n| 2,130\n|125,145\n|23.49\n|\n|-\n|2010\n|30,005\n| 4,006\n|146,689\n|36.98\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|32,282\n|4,877\n|153,337\n|42.84\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|33,781\n|4,433\n|153,140\n|51.29\n|\n|-\n|2013\n|34,828\n|5,312\n|153,375\n|67.63\n|62,000\n|-\n|2014\n|35,895\n|5,839\n|159,103\n|84.25\n|54,000\n|-\n|2015\n|34,441\n| 5,063\n|161,184\n|74.06\n|54,800\n|-\n|2016\n|33,823\n|5,285\n|158,893\n|61.68\n|56,400\n|-\n|2017\n|35,583\n|2,634\n|181,159\n|83.28\n|55,000\n|}\n\n==Card products==\n{{As of|2019|12|31}}, the company had 114.4 million cards in force, including 54.7{{nbsp}}million cards in force in the United States, each with an average annual spending of $19,972.<ref name=\"10-K 2019\"/> These include consumer, small business and corporate cards issued by American Express themselves and cards issued by its Global Service Network partners that run on its network (such as Commonwealth Bank, Westpac and NAB in Australia and Lloyds Bank and Barclays Bank in the UK). On March 1, 2017, Australia's fourth largest bank ANZ announced that it was no longer issuing American Express cards, with the support phased out entirely by August 5, 2017.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.ausbt.com.au/anz-stops-issuing-american-express-credit-cards| title=ANZ stops issuing American Express credit cards| work=Australian Business Traveller| first=Chris| last=Chamberlin| date=March 1, 2017| accessdate=February 4, 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205184349/https://www.ausbt.com.au/anz-stops-issuing-american-express-credit-cards| archive-date=February 5, 2018| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAmerican Express is the fourth largest general-purpose card network on a global basis based on purchase volume, behind China UnionPay, Visa and MasterCard.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://ir.americanexpress.com/Cache/1001233963.PDF?O=PDF&T=&Y=&D=&FID=1001233963&iid=102700| publisher=American express| title=American Express Company Annual Report, 2017| accessdate=March 13, 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180407031203/http://ir.americanexpress.com/Cache/1001233963.PDF?O=PDF&T=&Y=&D=&FID=1001233963&iid=102700| archive-date=April 7, 2018| url-status=live}}</ref> It is the 4th largest card network in the world, based on the number of cards it has in circulation.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.cardhub.com/edu/credit-card-companies/| title=List of Credit Card Companies & Networks: Differences, Contact Info & More| work=Card Hub| accessdate=September 21, 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808053813/http://www.cardhub.com/edu/credit-card-companies/| archive-date=August 8, 2014| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAmerican Express is one of the partner banks to both [[Google]] and [[Apple Inc.|Apple]]'s mobile wallet systems ([[Google Pay]] and [[Apple Pay]], respectively) meaning that cardholders can use their American Express-issued cards to pay at establishments where [[Near field communication|NFC]] payments are accepted. American Express offers various [[Contactless smart card|contactless credit cards]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Contactless | publisher=American Express | url=https://www.americanexpress.com/us/credit-cards/features-benefits/contactless/index.html | access-date=August 22, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190822224502/https://www.americanexpress.com/us/credit-cards/features-benefits/contactless/index.html | archive-date=August 22, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=What Are Contactless Credit Cards? And How Do I Get One? | publisher=Credit Card Insider | date=November 29, 2018 | url=https://www.creditcardinsider.com/blog/what-are-contactless-credit-cards-and-how-do-i-get-one/ | access-date=August 22, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190822224501/https://www.creditcardinsider.com/blog/what-are-contactless-credit-cards-and-how-do-i-get-one/ | archive-date=August 22, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Consumer cards===\n[[File:HK West Kln Waterfront Promenade Hong Kong Wine & Dine Festival Nov-2012 booths American Express sponsor view ICC.JPG|thumb|260px|An advertisement for the American Express Platinum Credit Card in Hong Kong]]\n{{See also|Centurion Card|Accolades Card}}\nAmerican Express is best known for its Green, Gold, and Platinum charge cards.  The Gold Card has recently{{when?|date=September 2019}} been converted to a credit card for UK residents but remains a charge card in the U.S.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thriftypoints.com/american-express-preferred-rewards-gold-card/|title=Amex Gold Card - American Express Preferred Rewards Gold Card Review UK|date=2019-03-05|website=Thrifty Points|access-date=2019-04-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190421143905/https://thriftypoints.com/american-express-preferred-rewards-gold-card/|archive-date=April 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1958, American Express issued its first [[charge card]], which required payment at the end of every month.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/clairetsosie/2016/08/29/what-the-first-credit-cards-were-like/| title=What The First Credit Cards Were Like| first=Claire| last=Tsosie| journal=[[Forbes]]| date=August 29, 2016| access-date=April 9, 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170410133053/https://www.forbes.com/sites/clairetsosie/2016/08/29/what-the-first-credit-cards-were-like/| archive-date=April 10, 2017| url-status=live}}</ref> In 1966, the company issued its first gold card, in an effort to cater to the upper echelon of business travel.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/27/business/american-express-turns-to-its-core-customers-the-affluent.html| title=With Revamped Gold Cards, Bruised American Express Returns Focus to Affluent| first=Hilary| last=Stout| work=[[The New York Times]]| date=February 26, 2015| access-date=April 9, 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205130404/https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/27/business/american-express-turns-to-its-core-customers-the-affluent.html| archive-date=February 5, 2018| url-status=live}}</ref> Its platinum card debuted in 1984.<ref>{{cite press release| url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/the-platinum-cardr-from-american-express-celebrates-its-20th-anniversary-71350477.html| title=The Platinum Card From American Express Celebrates Its 20th Anniversary| publisher=American Express| via=[[PRNewswire]]| date=July 21, 2004| access-date=April 9, 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170410213712/http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/the-platinum-cardr-from-american-express-celebrates-its-20th-anniversary-71350477.html| archive-date=April 10, 2017| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, American Express introduced the [[Centurion Card]], often referred to as the \"black card,\" which caters to an even more affluent customer segment. The card was initially available only to select users of the Platinum card. The annual fee for the card in the United States is $5,000 (up from $1,000 at introduction) with an additional one-time initiation fee of $10,000. American Express created the card line amid rumors and [[urban legend]]s in the 1980s that it produced an ultra-exclusive black card for elite users who could purchase anything with it.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.snopes.com/business/bank/blackcard.asp| website=[[Snopes.com]]| title=Black American Express Card| date=December 6, 2006| accessdate=December 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\nAmerican Express cards issued in the United States range in cost between no annual fee (for Blue and many other consumer and business cards) and a $550 annual fee (for the Platinum card).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/03/02/american-express-revamps-platinum-card-with-200-bonuses-and-550-fee.html|title=Amex revamps Platinum card with new bonuses ... and fees|last=Anderson|first=Tom|date=2017-03-02|website=[[CNBC]]|access-date=2019-08-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920204221/https://www.cnbc.com/2017/03/02/american-express-revamps-platinum-card-with-200-bonuses-and-550-fee.html|archive-date=September 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Annual fees for the Green card start at $150, while Gold card annual fees start at $250.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.americanexpress.com/us/credit-cards/card/green/ |title=Green |website=americanexpress.com |access-date=2019-11-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191127154053/https://www.americanexpress.com/us/credit-cards/card/green |archive-date=November 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.americanexpress.com/us/credit-cards/card/gold-card/ |title=Gold Card |website=americanexpress.com |access-date=2019-11-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016202103/https://www.americanexpress.com/us/credit-cards/card/gold-card/ |archive-date=October 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAmerican Express has several co-branded credit cards, with most falling into one of three categories:\n* Airlines: [[Aerolineas Argentinas]], [[Aerom\u00e9xico]], [[Air Canada]], [[Air France]], [[Alitalia]], [[British Airways]], [[Cathay Pacific]], [[Delta Air Lines]], [[Icelandair]], [[KLM]], [[Qantas]], [[Scandinavian Airlines]], [[Singapore Airlines]], [[SriLankan Airlines]], [[Thai Airways]], [[Virgin Atlantic]], [[Virgin Australia]], among others.\n* Hotels: [[Best Western]], [[Hilton Hotels]], and [[Marriott International]]\n* Retailers: [[David Jones Limited|David Jones]], [[Holt Renfrew]], [[Harrods]], [[Macy's]], [[Bloomingdales]], [[Lowe's]], [[Mercedes Benz]], [[Dillard's]] and others.\n\nA credit card aimed at young adults is called ''Blue'', which has no annual fee and a [[loyalty program]]. A television media campaign for Blue adopted the 1979 UK [[Synthpop]] hit \"[[Cars (song)|Cars]]\" by [[Gary Numan]] as its [[theme music]]. A [[cashback reward program]] version, \"Blue Cash\", quickly followed. American Express also targeted young adults with City Reward Cards that earn INSIDE Rewards points to eat, drink, and play at New York, Chicago and LA hot spots. American Express began phasing out the INSIDE cards in mid-2008, with no new applications being taken as of July 2008.\n\nIn 2005, American Express introduced Clear, advertised as the first credit card with no fees of any kind.  Other cards introduced in 2005, included \"The Knot\" and \"The Nest\" Credit Cards from American Express, co-branded cards developed with the wedding planning website theknot.com.\n\nIn 2006, the UK division of American Express joined the [[Product Red]] coalition and issued a Red Card, donating with each purchase through [[The Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria]] to help African women and children suffering from HIV/AIDS, malaria, and other diseases.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/american-express-launches-red-card-digital-campaign/544285| title=American Express launches Red Card with digital campaign| first=Emma| last=Rig| journal=[[Campaign (magazine)|Campaign]]| date=March 3, 2006| accessdate=February 4, 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180206131435/https://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/american-express-launches-red-card-digital-campaign/544285| archive-date=February 6, 2018| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, American Express introduced the ZYNC charge card. White in color, this card was created for people aged 20\u201340.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://bucks.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/12/08/american-express-zync-will-young-adults-want-a-charge-card/| title=American Express Zync: Will Young Adults Want a Charge Card?| last=Lieber| first=Ron| work=[[The New York Times]]| access-date=2018-01-18| language=en| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180119060640/https://bucks.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/12/08/american-express-zync-will-young-adults-want-a-charge-card/| archive-date=January 19, 2018| url-status=live}}</ref> The Zync charge card has since been discontinued with the exception of current cardholders who are [[grandfathered]] into the ZYNC.\n\nIn late 2012, American Express and [[Walmart]] announced the launch of Bluebird, a [[prepaid debit card]] similar to that of [[Green Dot Corporation|Green Dot]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://about.americanexpress.com/news/pr/2012/american-express-and-walmart-launch-bluebird.aspx| title=American Express and Walmart Launch Bluebird: a New Alternative to Debit and Checking Accounts| accessdate=September 21, 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911181007/http://about.americanexpress.com/news/pr/2012/american-express-and-walmart-launch-bluebird.aspx| archive-date=September 11, 2014| url-status=dead| df=mdy-all}}</ref> Bluebird is being touted as having some of the benefits of traditional American Express cards, such as [[roadside assistance]] and [[identity theft]] protection. The card can also be used as a substitute to a traditional [[Transactional account|checking account]]. Unlike other such cards, Bluebird is [[Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation|FDIC]]-insured.<ref>Kopecki, Dawn. (2013-03-26) [https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-03-26/amex-bluebird-customers-get-fdic-backing-check-writing-feature.html AmEx Bluebird Customers Get FDIC Backing, Check-Writing Feature] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131108053845/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-03-26/amex-bluebird-customers-get-fdic-backing-check-writing-feature.html |date=November 8, 2013 }}. Bloomberg Technology; Retrieved on 2013-08-16; Subscription required.</ref>  Bluebird accounts have standard FDIC deposit insurance and check writing capabilities, and customers can now{{when|date=August 2019}} have Social Security payments, military pay, Tax Return, paycheck and other government benefits deposited directly into their accounts.\n\n===Card acceptance outside the United States===\nAmerican Express credit cards are noted by travel guides, including [[Rough Guides]] and [[Lonely Planet]], as being less commonly accepted in Europe than Visa or Mastercard.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roughguides.com/destinations/europe/france/travel-essentials/|title=Travel essentials|work=[[Rough Guides]]|accessdate=September 21, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140901022929/http://www.roughguides.com/destinations/europe/france/travel-essentials/|archive-date=September 1, 2014|url-status=live}}'' Note: Click 'Read more' to expand information''</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.lonelyplanet.com/denmark/a/nar-gr/money-and-costs/358836| title=Denmark: Money and Costs| work=[[Lonely Planet]]| accessdate=February 4, 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205184433/https://www.lonelyplanet.com/denmark/a/nar-gr/money-and-costs/358836| archive-date=February 5, 2018| url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.visitlondon.com/traveller-information/essential-information/money/british-money| title=British Money| date=April 10, 2007| publisher=[[London and Partners|Visit London]]| accessdate=February 4, 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222025946/http://www.visitlondon.com/traveller-information/essential-information/money/british-money| archive-date=December 22, 2016| url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.dreamofitaly.com/public/Italy-Travel-FAQ-What-is-The-Best-Way-to-Get-Euros-and-Pay-For-Things-in-Italy.cfm| title=Italy Travel F.A.Q.: What is The Best Way to Get Euros and Pay For Things in Italy?| publisher=Dream of Italy| access-date=May 29, 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529122702/http://www.dreamofitaly.com/public/Italy-Travel-FAQ-What-is-The-Best-Way-to-Get-Euros-and-Pay-For-Things-in-Italy.cfm| archive-date=May 29, 2014| url-status=live}}</ref> In an interview with an American Express spokesman in 2010, about card acceptance in the UK, the ''[[Daily Mail]]'''s financial website, ''This is Money'', noted that \"The list of places that are taking American Express appears to be growing, rather than slowing, but it seems to be a little hit-and-miss. It's not a good feeling to enter a shop, not knowing whether or not they accept the card.\"<ref name=\"thisismoney\">{{cite journal| first=Lee| last=Boyce| url=http://www.thisismoney.co.uk/money/experts/article-1699000/Why-dont-places-take-American-Express.html| title=Why don't more places take American Express?| journal=This is Money| date=July 22, 2010| accessdate=February 4, 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205130042/http://www.thisismoney.co.uk/money/experts/article-1699000/Why-dont-places-take-American-Express.html| archive-date=February 5, 2018| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Card design===\nThe company logo, a gladiator or centurion, appears at the center of the iconic Zync, Cobalt, Green, Gold, Platinum, and Centurion cards. The figure and his pose evoke [[classical antiquity]]. These cards also feature intricate border and background designs that read \"American Express.\" The designs on these cards, especially the Green card, bear resemblance to those on United States [[Federal Reserve Notes]].\n\n===ExpressPay===\n[[File:EMVCoContactlessIndicator.svg|right|75px]]\n[[File:Americanexpressplatinumemvcontactless.jpg|thumb|left|A Platinum American Express Charge Card issued in the UK that is contactless-enabled]]\nIn 2005, American Express introduced ExpressPay, similar to Mastercard [[Mastercard#Mastercard Contactless|Contactless]] and Visa [[payWave]], all of which use the symbol appearing on the right. It is a [[contactless payment]] system based on wireless [[RFID]], where transactions are completed by holding the credit card near a receiver at which point the debt is immediately added to the account. All three contactless systems use the same logo. The card is not swiped or inserted into a smart card reader and no PIN is entered.\n\nMany merchants, in the U.S. and globally, offer American Express contactless payment, including [[Meijer]], [[Walgreens]], [[Best Buy]], [[Chevron Corporation]], [[Starbucks]], and [[McDonald's]].\n\n===American Express OPEN===\nAmerican Express OPEN, the small-business branch of American Express, offers various types of charge cards for small businesses to manage their expenses.\n\nIn late 2007, the company announced the new Plum Card as the latest addition to their card line for [[small business]] owners.<ref name=\"American-Express-Oct-2007-8-K\">{{cite web |url=http://edgar.secdatabase.com/2534/496207000049/filing-main.htm |title=American Express, Form 8-K, Current Report, Filing Date Oct 22, 2007 |publisher=Securities and Exchange Commission |accessdate=Jan 6, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512043558/http://edgar.secdatabase.com/2534/496207000049/filing-main.htm |archive-date=May 12, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> The card provides a 1.5% early pay discount or up to two months to defer payment on purchases. The 1.5% discount is available for billing periods where the cardmember spends at least $5,000. The first 10,000 cards were issued to members on December 16, 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.plumcard.com |title=Official Plum Card Website |publisher=Plumcard.com |accessdate=December 18, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010195402/http://www.plumcard.com/ |archive-date=October 10, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, American Express closed all Business Line of Credit accounts. This decision was reached in tandem with the Federal Reserve's approval of American Express's request to become a [[commercial bank]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.usbusinessfinancecorp.com/financeblog/american-express-closes-business-lines-of-credit.html |title=American Express Closes Business Lines of Credit |access-date=April 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170410214503/http://www.usbusinessfinancecorp.com/financeblog/american-express-closes-business-lines-of-credit.html |archive-date=April 10, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2016|7}}, American Express has several credit cards designed for small business. These include SimplyCash Plus Business Credit Card. Cash back earned is automatically credited to the cardholder's statement and other benefits are included.  Other cards include the Business Platinum Card from American Express OPEN, the Business Gold Rewards Card from American Express OPEN, the Blue for Business Credit Card from American Express, Business Green Rewards Card from American Express OPEN, the Business Green Rewards Card from American Express OPEN and the Plum Card from American Express OPEN.  These cards have return protection, year-end summaries and other tools to help with the business accounting and control.<ref name=Daniel>Daniel, Ivan. [https://get.com/blog/american-express-cards-small-business/ Best American Express Cards For Small Business] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819011220/https://get.com/blog/american-express-cards-small-business/ |date=August 19, 2016 }} Get.com. July 7, 2016. Retrieved July 13, 2016.</ref>\n\n===Commercial cards and services===\nIn 2008, American Express acquired the Corporate Payment Services business of GE, which primarily focused on providing Purchasing Card solutions for large global clients.<ref name=\"American-Express-Mar-2008-8-K\">{{cite web |url=http://edgar.secdatabase.com/824/496208000005/filing-main.htm |title=American Express, Form 8-K, Current Report, Filing Date Mar 27, 2008 |publisher=Securities and Exchange Commission |accessdate=Jan 6, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512050655/http://edgar.secdatabase.com/824/496208000005/filing-main.htm |archive-date=May 12, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> As part of the $1b+ transaction, American Express also added a new product, called V-Payment, to its product portfolio. V-Payment is unique in that it enables a tightly controlled, single-use card number for increased control.\n\n{{As of|2016|7}}, American Express offered several business, corporate and travel credit and charge cards and services and data and information services related to their use in the competitive markets for these cards.<ref name=DeLuna>[http://www.businesstravelnews.com/Payment-Expense/Amex-Cuts-CEOs-Pay Amex Cuts CEO Pay] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160910182357/http://www.businesstravelnews.com/Payment-Expense/Amex-Cuts-CEOs-Pay |date=September 10, 2016 }} DeLuna, JoAnn, Business Travel News. March 28, 2016. Retrieved July 13, 2016.</ref>\n\nThe online \"American Express @ Work\" function gives corporations a site on which to apply for, cancel or suspend cards, monitor policy compliance and track expenses. The cardholder company can create and generate reports for a corporate expense account program, including analytics and data consolidation or integration.<ref name=Kerr>\nKerr,\n Tom. [http://www.comparecards.com/blog/business-benefits-of-amex-corporate-cards/ Business Benefits of Amex Corporate Cards] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815220128/http://www.comparecards.com/blog/business-benefits-of-amex-corporate-cards/ |date=August 15, 2016 }} [[LendingTree|Compare Wallet]], July 26, 2017, Retrieved February 4, 2018.  ''This content is not provided by American Express. Any opinions, analyses, reviews or recommendations expressed in this article are those of the author's alone, and have not been reviewed, approved or otherwise endorsed by American Express.''\n</ref> Reports can be tailored for various sized companies. Through a Standard Expense Reporting feature in its \"Manage Your Card Account site\", American Express corporate cards provide cardholders access to pre-populated expense reports. The cardholder needs to annotate expenses and add out-of-pocket charges upon completion of which the report can be downloaded in electronic or paper format.<ref name=Kerr/>\n\nAmerican Express Corporate Card program can be used with a third-party on-demand expense management tool by Concur, a provider of integrated travel and expense management services.  This tool simplifies the creation of expense account reports and the corporate approval process. Corporate card activity, including viewing statements, making payments, setting up alerts and making inquiries and disputing charges, can be managed through an account online or via mobile device through this service.<ref name=Kerr/>\n\nThe corporate cards have benefits including discounts and rebates for travel and transportation, travel and emergency help, travel insurance and baggage protection.<ref name=Kerr/> Upgrades from the Corporate \"Green\" Card to the Corporate Gold Card or Corporate Platinum Card, although subject to fees and terms and conditions, have several additional benefits at each card level, such as free breakfast or late checkout at many hotels.<ref name=Kerr/> The American Express/Business Extra Corporate Credit Card is affiliated with American Airlines and provides a 4% rebate on eligible American Airlines travel purchased with the card.<ref name=Kerr/>\n\nAmerican Express has a specialized corporate meeting credit card.<ref>[https://business.americanexpress.com/us/corporate-cards/corporate-meeting-card American Express Corporate Meeting Card information] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160620025159/https://business.americanexpress.com/us/corporate-cards/corporate-meeting-card |date=June 20, 2016 }} Retrieved July 13, 2016.</ref> Another specialized American Express business card is the American Express Corporate Purchasing Card, which can be assigned to individual employees or departments. Reconciliation and accounting services are available to make these functions easier for the corporation.<ref>[https://business.americanexpress.com/us/corporate-cards/p-card American Express Corporate Purchasing Card information] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160914123814/https://business.americanexpress.com/us/corporate-cards/p-card |date=September 14, 2016 }} Retrieved July 13, 2016.</ref>\n\n===Non-proprietary cards===\nIn December 2000, American Express agreed to acquire the US$226{{nbsp}}million credit card portfolio of [[Bank of Hawaii]], then a division of [[Pacific Century Financial Corporation|Pacific Century Financial Corp.]]<ref name=\"American-Express-Jan-2001-8-K\">{{cite web |url=http://edgar.secdatabase.com/2655/496201500004/filing-main.htm |title=American Express, Form 8-K, Current Report, Filing Date Jan 22, 2001 |publisher=Securities and Exchange Commission |accessdate=Jan 6, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512082051/http://edgar.secdatabase.com/2655/496201500004/filing-main.htm |archive-date=May 12, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> In January 2006, American Express sold its Bank of Hawaii card portfolio to [[Bank of America]] ([[MBNA]]). Bank of America will issue [[Visa Inc.|Visa]] and American Express cards under the Bank of Hawaii name.\n\nUntil 2004, Visa and [[Mastercard]] rules prohibited issuers of their cards from issuing American Express cards in the United States. This meant, as a practical matter, that U.S. banks could not issue American Express cards. These rules were struck-down as a result of antitrust litigation brought by the [[United States Department of Justice|U.S. Department of Justice]], and are no longer in effect.<ref name=\"American-Express-Mar-2004-10-K\">{{cite web |url=http://edgar.secdatabase.com/1342/95011704000966/filing-main.htm |title=American Express, Form 10-K, Annual Report, Filing Date Mar 12, 2004 |publisher=Securities and Exchange Commission |accessdate=Jan 6, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512060014/http://edgar.secdatabase.com/1342/95011704000966/filing-main.htm |archive-date=May 12, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> In January 2004, American Express reached a deal to have its cards issued by a U.S. bank, [[MBNA]] America.<ref name=\"American-Express-Feb-2004-8-K\">{{cite web |url=http://edgar.secdatabase.com/1529/496204000044/filing-main.htm |title=American Express, Form 8-K, Current Report, Filing Date Feb 2, 2004 |publisher=Securities and Exchange Commission |accessdate=January 6, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512044824/http://edgar.secdatabase.com/1529/496204000044/filing-main.htm |archive-date=May 12, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Initially decried by Mastercard executives as nothing but an \"experiment\", these cards were released in October 2004.<ref name=\"American-Express-Jan-2005-8-K\">{{cite web |url=http://edgar.secdatabase.com/2830/496205000012/filing-main.htm |title=American Express, Form 8-K, Current Report, Filing Date Jan 24, 2005 |publisher=Securities and Exchange Commission |accessdate=Jan 6, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512061705/http://edgar.secdatabase.com/2830/496205000012/filing-main.htm |archive-date=May 12, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Some said that the relationship was going to be threatened by MBNA's merger with Bank of America, a major Visa issuer and original developer of Visa (and its predecessor, BankAmericard). However, an agreement was reached between American Express and Bank of America on December 21, 2005.<ref name=\"American-Express-Dec-2005-8-K\">{{cite web |url=http://edgar.secdatabase.com/39/496205000220/filing-main.htm |title=American Express, Form 8-K, Current Report, Filing Date Dec 23, 2005 |publisher=Securities and Exchange Commission |accessdate=Jan 6, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512054046/http://edgar.secdatabase.com/39/496205000220/filing-main.htm |archive-date=May 12, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Under the terms of the agreement, Bank of America will own the customer loans and American Express will process the transactions. Also, American Express will dismiss Bank of America from its antitrust litigation against Visa, Mastercard, and a number of U.S. banks. Finally, both Bank of America and American Express also said an existing card-issuing partnership between MBNA and American Express will continue after the Bank of America-MBNA merger. The first card from the partnership, the no-annual-fee Bank of America Rewards American Express card, was released on June 30, 2006.\n\nSince then, [[Citibank]], [[Wells Fargo]], [[First National Bank of Omaha]], [[USAA]], [[Synchrony Financial]], and [[US Bancorp]] have started issuing American Express cards. Citi issues the [[Macy's]] and [[Bloomingdale's]] American Express cards along with Citi-branded cards. Wells Fargo issues American Express cards under their own brand and for [[Dillard's]]. US Bancorp issues American Express-branded cards for US Bank along with Elan Card Services, a subsidiary that issues credit cards on behalf of small to midsize banks. Some [[credit unions]], including [[PenFed]], also issue American Express cards. [[JPMorgan Chase]] is the largest bank and the only [[Big Four (banking)#United States|Big Four bank]] in the US that does not partner with American Express. Instead, JPMorgan made the decision in 2013, to partner with Visa on the ChaseNet closed-loop network that is similar in terms of functionality to the American Express network.\n\n===Merchant account===\nMany [[retail]]ers do not accept American Express cards.<ref name=\"Digital journal\">{{Cite journal| url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/pr/1994577| title=Florida Merchant Services Provider Gets Full American Express Acquiring Program| journal=Digital Journal| accessdate=June 17, 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714192921/http://www.digitaljournal.com/pr/1994577| archive-date=July 14, 2014| url-status=live}}</ref>{{Specify |reason=how many? |date=October 2017}} American Express charges [[Merchant account|merchants]] significantly higher fees than other credit card providers.<ref name=\"The Motley Fool\">{{cite journal| title=Here's Why American Express Can Charge More Than Visa or MasterCard| url=http://www.fool.com/investing/general/2014/06/16/heres-why-american-express-can-charge-more-than-vi.aspx| first=Matthew| last=Frankel| date=June 16, 2014| journal=[[The Motley Fool]]| accessdate=February 4, 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171015202816/https://www.fool.com/investing/general/2014/06/16/heres-why-american-express-can-charge-more-than-vi.aspx| archive-date=October 15, 2017| url-status=live}}</ref>  In a court case [[Ohio v. American Express Co.]], merchants filed a [[class action]] lawsuit against American Express and claimed that charging high fees is a violation of the [[Sherman Antitrust Act]].<ref name=\"Law 360\">{{Cite journal| url=http://www.law360.com/articles/544885/no-market-power-needed-in-2nd-circ-vertical-restraint-cases| title=No Market Power Needed In 2nd Circ. Vertical Restraint Cases| journal=[[Law360]]| accessdate=June 5, 2014| url-access=subscription| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714164229/http://www.law360.com/articles/544885/no-market-power-needed-in-2nd-circ-vertical-restraint-cases| archive-date=July 14, 2014| url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Buffalo Law Journal\">{{cite news| url=http://www.bizjournals.com/buffalo/blog/buffalo-law-journal/2014/06/five-questions-with-john-godwin.html| title=Five questions with... John Godwin| publisher=Buffalo Law Journal| first=Michael| last=Petro| date=June 19, 2014| accessdate=February 4, 2018| url-access=subscription| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715044638/http://www.bizjournals.com/buffalo/blog/buffalo-law-journal/2014/06/five-questions-with-john-godwin.html| archive-date=July 15, 2014| url-status=live}}</ref> According to the lawsuit, accepting American Express cards costs merchants the most.<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/05/07/us-usa-antitrust-amex-idUSBREA460QI20140507| title=U.S. judge: Government's antitrust suit vs AmEx may proceed| date=May 7, 2014| first=Andrew| last=Longstreth| work=Reuters| accessdate=February 4, 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924200555/http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/05/07/us-usa-antitrust-amex-idUSBREA460QI20140507| archive-date=September 24, 2015| url-status=live}}</ref> In January 2017, the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals affirmed a lower court ruling that American Express could block merchants that accept its cards from steering customers to other cards, like those offered by Visa and Mastercard.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-american-express-antitrust/u-s-loses-bid-to-overturn-amex-antitrust-decision-idUSKBN14P2JE| title=U.S. loses bid to overturn AmEx antitrust decision| date=January 15, 2017| work=Reuters| first=Jonathan| last=Stempel| accessdate=February 4, 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020084400/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-american-express-antitrust/u-s-loses-bid-to-overturn-amex-antitrust-decision-idUSKBN14P2JE| archive-date=October 20, 2017| url-status=live}}</ref> In June 2018, the [[Supreme Court of the United States|U.S. Supreme Court]] affirmed the 2nd Circuit Court's ruling.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Ohio v. American Express Co. |vol=585 |opinion=16-1454 |court=[[Supreme Court of the United States|U.S.]] |date=June 25, 2018 |url=https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/17pdf/16-1454_5h26.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Non-card products==\n\n===Traveler's checks===\nAmerican Express is the largest provider of [[traveler's check]]s in the world.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/travelers-checks-still-thing-113000341.html |title=Are Traveler's Checks Still a Thing? |last=Szczypinski |first=Sarah |work=Yahoo! Finance |date=August 25, 2016 |accessdate=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507090227/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/travelers-checks-still-thing-113000341.html |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, American Express released the American Express Travelers Check Card, a [[stored-value card]] that serves the same purposes as a traveler's check, but can be used in stores like a credit card. AmEx discontinued the card in October 2007, due to \"changing market conditions\" and issued refund checks to cardholders for the remaining balances.\n\n===Shearson/American Express===\n{{see also|Shearson/American Express}}\n[[File:Shearson AmEx Logo.png|320px|Shearson/American Express logo c. 1982|thumb|right]]\n\nDuring the 1980s, American Express began purchasing [[brokerage firm|stock brokerage]] firms as part of an expansion. In mid-1981, it purchased [[Sanford I. Weill]]'s [[Shearson Loeb Rhoades]], the second largest securities firm in the United States to form Shearson/American Express. Shearson Loeb Rhoades, itself was the culmination of several mergers in the 1970s as Weill's [[Hayden, Stone & Co.]] merged with [[Shearson, Hammill & Co.]] in 1974, to form [[Shearson Hayden Stone]]. Shearson Hayden Stone then merged with [[Loeb, Rhoades, Hornblower & Co.]] (formerly [[Loeb, Rhoades & Co.]]) to form Shearson Loeb Rhoades in 1979. With capital totalling $250&nbsp;million at the time of its acquisition, Shearson Loeb Rhoades trailed only [[Merrill Lynch]] as the securities industry's largest [[brokerage firm]]. After its acquisition by American Express, the firm was renamed Shearson/American Express.\n\nIn 1984, Shearson/American Express purchased the 90-year-old [[Investors Diversified Services]], bringing with it a fleet of financial advisors and investment products. Also in 1984, American Express acquired the [[investment banking]] and trading firm, [[Lehman Brothers|Lehman Brothers Kuhn Loeb]], and added it to the Shearson family, creating Shearson Lehman/American Express. In 1988, the firm acquired [[E. F. Hutton & Co.]], forming [[Shearson Lehman Hutton]] until 1990, when the firm's name became Shearson Lehman Brothers. When Harvey Golub took the reins in 1993, he negotiated the sale of Shearson's retail brokerage and [[Investment management|asset management]] business to [[Primerica]] and in following year, spun off of the remaining investment banking and institutional businesses as [[Lehman Brothers|Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc]].\n\n===Financial advisors===\nOn September 30, 2005, American Express spun-off its American Express Financial Advisors unit, [[Ameriprise Financial]], to its shareholders.  On September 30, 2005, [[RSM McGladrey]] acquired American Express Tax & Business Services (TBS).<ref name=\"American-Express-Oct-2005-8-K\">{{cite web |url=http://edgar.secdatabase.com/31/496205000212/filing-main.htm |title=American Express, Form 8-K, Current Report, Filing Date Oct 24, 2005 |publisher=Securities and Exchange Commission |accessdate=Jan 6, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512063829/http://edgar.secdatabase.com/31/496205000212/filing-main.htm |archive-date=May 12, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===International bank===\nIn 2008, [[Standard Chartered Bank]] acquired American Express Bank Ltd, the international banking subsidiary of American Express for US$823{{nbsp}}million.<ref name=\"American-Express-Sep-2007-8-K\">{{cite web |url=http://edgar.secdatabase.com/2528/496207000043/filing-main.htm |title=American Express, Form 8-K, Current Report, Filing Date Sep 18, 2007 |publisher=Securities and Exchange Commission |accessdate=January 6, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512071516/http://edgar.secdatabase.com/2528/496207000043/filing-main.htm |archive-date=May 12, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2007/sep/18/9| title=Standard Chartered buys American Express Bank| work=[[The Guardian]]| location=London| first=Andrew| last=Clark| date=September 18, 2007| access-date=December 11, 2016| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316210222/https://www.theguardian.com/business/2007/sep/18/9| archive-date=March 16, 2017| url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Frequently Asked Questions on the Standard Chartered Bank acquisition of American Express Bank|url=http://cmax.americanexpress.com/Internet/PrivateBank/pdf/SCB_AEB_Client_FAQ.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131215195529/http://cmax.americanexpress.com/Internet/PrivateBank/pdf/SCB_AEB_Client_FAQ.pdf|archive-date=December 15, 2013|publisher=American Express|accessdate=January 11, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.sc.com/in/_documents/tools-utilities/ar_0607.pdf |title=Auditors' Report on the financial statements of Standard Chartered Bank \u2013 India Branches under Section 30 of the Banking Regulation Act, 1949, Page 7, Economic & Political Weekly EPW June 28, 2008 |publisher=Standard Chartered |accessdate=January 11, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131215223604/https://www.sc.com/in/_documents/tools-utilities/ar_0607.pdf |archive-date=December 15, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sc.com/vn/latest-news/03-08-completes-acquisition-of-american-express-bank/en/ |title=Standard Chartered completes acquisition of American Express Bank for $823 million |publisher=Standard Chartered Bank |date=March 3, 2008 |access-date=April 8, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170408082638/https://www.sc.com/vn/latest-news/03-08-completes-acquisition-of-american-express-bank/en/ |archive-date=April 8, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Travel===\n{{unreferenced section|date=September 2019}}\nAmerican Express established a Travel Division in 1915, that tied together all earlier efforts at making travel easier, and soon established its first [[travel agency|travel agencies]]. In the 1930s, the Travel Division had grown widely. [[Albert K. Dawson]] was instrumental in expanding business operations overseas, even investing in tourist relations with the [[Soviet Union]]. During [[World War I]], Dawson was a photographer and film correspondent with the German army.\n\nIn March 2014, American Express announced that it signed an agreement to create a joint venture for business travel and spun off its corporate travel business as [[American Express Global Business Travel]].\n\n===Publishing===\nThe American Express Publishing Corporation published the ''[[Travel + Leisure]],'' ''[[Food & Wine (magazine)|Food & Wine]],'' ''[[Executive Travel magazine|Executive Travel]]'', ''Black Ink'', and ''[[Departures Magazine|Departures]]'' magazines until October 1, 2013, when it sold those titles to [[Time Inc.]]<ref>{{cite news| title=Media It's Official: Time Inc. Buys AmEx's Food & Wine, Travel & Leisure Magazines| url=http://adage.com/article/media/time-buys-amex-s-food-wine-travel-leisure/244065/| work=[[Advertising Age]]| date=September 10, 2013| accessdate=February 4, 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131012104625/http://adage.com/article/media/time-buys-amex-s-food-wine-travel-leisure/244065/| archive-date=October 12, 2013| url-status=live}}</ref>  It publishes ''American Express Skyguide'' and is based in New York City.<ref name=\"American-Express-Feb-2012-10-K\">{{cite web |url=http://pdf.secdatabase.com/1125/0001193125-12-077400.pdf |title=American Express, Form 10-K, Annual Report, Filing Date Feb 24, 2012 |publisher=Securities and Exchange Commission |accessdate=Jan 6, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512063058/http://pdf.secdatabase.com/1125/0001193125-12-077400.pdf |archive-date=May 12, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{as of|2014|February|}}, [[Time Inc.]] is restructuring the portfolio of publications.<ref name=\"Time Inc. Lays Out Restructuring\">{{cite journal| url=http://www.wwd.com/media-news/fashion-memopad/time-inc-lays-out-restructuring-7407860?src=nl/mornReport/20140205| title=Time Inc. Lays Out Restructuring| journal=[[Women's Wear Daily]]| date=February 5, 2014| accessdate=February 4, 2014| last=Steigrad| first=Alexandra| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140215035949/http://www.wwd.com/media-news/fashion-memopad/time-inc-lays-out-restructuring-7407860?src=nl%2FmornReport%2F20140205| archive-date=February 15, 2014| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Individual banking===\n{{unreferenced section|date=September 2019}}\nAmerican Express FSB ([[federal savings bank]]) is a [[direct bank]] offering a standard [[savings account]] to individuals.  Checking account services are not provided.\n\n==Advertising campaigns==\n\n===Don't Leave Home Without Them===\nIn 1975, [[David Ogilvy (businessman)|David Ogilvy]] of [[Ogilvy & Mather]] developed the highly successful \"Don't Leave Home Without Them\" [[Advertising campaign|ad campaign]] for American Express Traveler's Cheques, featuring Oscar-award-winning actor [[Karl Malden]]. Malden served as the public face of American Express Travelers Cheques for 25 years. In the UK, the spokesman was the [[Celebrity|television personality]] [[Alan Whicker]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/2010/05/28/nike-bmw-amex-apple-cmo-network-best-advertising-taglines_slide_4.html |title=Best-Loved Advertising Taglines |last=Bruno |first=Ken |work=[[Forbes]] |date=May 29, 2010 |accessdate=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507090036/https://www.forbes.com/2010/05/28/nike-bmw-amex-apple-cmo-network-best-advertising-taglines_slide_4.html |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAfter Malden's departure, and as the card assumed importance over the traveler's cheques, American Express continued to use celebrities, such as [[Mel Blanc]] and ballerina [[Cynthia Gregory]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=American Express commercial featuring Mel Blanc|oclc=715152953}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://articles.latimes.com/1987-01-04/entertainment/ca-1757_1_dance-studio |title=Cynthia Gregory At 40: 'I Did It The Hard Way' |last=Perlmutter |first=Donna |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=January 4, 1987 |accessdate=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180420185049/http://articles.latimes.com/1987-01-04/entertainment/ca-1757_1_dance-studio |archive-date=April 20, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> A typical ad for the American Express Card began with a celebrity asking viewers: \"Do you know me?\" Although he/she gave hints to his/her identity, the star's name was never mentioned except as imprinted on an American Express Card, after which announcer [[Peter Thomas (television narrator)|Peter Thomas]] told viewers how to apply for it.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://archive.naplesnews.com/news/local/famed-voice-over-icon-peter-thomas-dies-at-91-022ad336-4bbf-5cbb-e053-0100007f64ba-377801571.html/ |title=Famed voice-over icon Peter Thomas dies at 91 |last=Schlichter |first=Jay |newspaper=Naples Daily News |date=May 2, 2016 |accessdate=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229012743/http://archive.naplesnews.com/news/local/famed-voice-over-icon-peter-thomas-dies-at-91-022ad336-4bbf-5cbb-e053-0100007f64ba-377801571.html |archive-date=December 29, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Each ad concluded with the celebrity reminding viewers: \"Don't Leave Home Without It.\" The \"Don't Leave Home Without It\" slogan was revived in 2005.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.atlasobscura.com/articles/how-advertising-invented-8-phrases-we-use-every-day |title=How Advertising Invented 8 Phrases We Use Every Day |last=Grundhauser |first=Eric |magazine=Atlas Obscura |date=October 2, 2015 |accessdate=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507085735/https://www.atlasobscura.com/articles/how-advertising-invented-8-phrases-we-use-every-day |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===The Adventures of Seinfeld & Superman===\n[[File:Seinfeld superman.jpg|thumb|200px|right|[[The Adventures of Seinfeld & Superman]]]]\nAmerican Express continues to use celebrities in their ads. Some notable examples include a late 1990s ad campaign with comedian [[Jerry Seinfeld]], including the two 2004 [[webisode]]s in a series entitled \"[[The Adventures of Seinfeld & Superman]]\".<ref name=NYT>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/03/30/business/media-business-advertising-seinfeld-superman-join-forces-again-spots-for.html? |title=Seinfeld and Superman join forces again in spots for American Express, this time on the Web. |last=Elliott |first=Stuart |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=30 March 2004 |accessdate=19 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===My life. My card. / Are You a Cardmember?===\nIn late 2004, American Express launched the \"My life. My card.\" brand campaign, and later the \"Are You a Cardmember?\" brand campaign in 2007, (both by Ogilvy & Mather), featuring famous American Express cardmembers talking about their lives.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.adweek.com/brand-marketing/ogilvy-changes-amex-tagline-88553/ |title=Ogilvy Changes AmEx Tagline |last=McMains |first=Andrew |magazine=Adweek |date=April 6, 2007 |accessdate=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507090307/http://www.adweek.com/brand-marketing/ogilvy-changes-amex-tagline-88553/ |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The ads have featured actors/actresses [[Kate Winslet]],<ref name=\"amex-adsoftheworld-04/2009\">{{cite web |url=https://www.adsoftheworld.com/campaign/american-express-ogilvy-04-2009 |title=American Express Campaign by Ogilvy - 04/2009 |publisher=Ads of the World |accessdate=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507085750/https://www.adsoftheworld.com/campaign/american-express-ogilvy-04-2009 |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Robert De Niro]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.splendad.com/ads/show/1109-American-Express-Robert-De-Niro.html |title=American Express - Robert De Niro |publisher=splendAd |accessdate=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507085532/http://www.splendad.com/ads/show/1109-American-Express-Robert-De-Niro.html |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Ken Watanabe]],<ref name=\"amex-adsoftheworld-04/2009\"/> and [[Tina Fey]];<ref>{{cite video|publisher=[[YouTube]]|title=Tina Fey American Express Commercial|date=July 1, 2010|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=I7m-iAX3POU|access-date=May 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323090253/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=I7m-iAX3POU|archive-date=March 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Duke University]] basketball coach [[Mike Krzyzewski]];<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.adforum.com/creative-work/ad/player/34474558/coach-k/american-express |title=American Express - \"Coach K\" |publisher=adforum |accessdate=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507085734/https://www.adforum.com/creative-work/ad/player/34474558/coach-k/american-express |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> fashion designers [[Collette Dinnigan]] and [[Diane von F\u00fcrstenberg]];<ref>{{cite video|publisher=[[YouTube]]|title=American Express Collette Dinnigan|date=October 28, 2008| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hG7OMCem_Lc}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.splendad.com/ads/show/1991-American-Express-Diane-von-Furstenberg.html |title=American Express - Diane von Furstenberg |publisher=splendAd |accessdate=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507085451/http://www.splendad.com/ads/show/1991-American-Express-Diane-von-Furstenberg.html |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> comedian and talk show hostess [[Ellen DeGeneres]];<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.splendad.com/ads/show/1120-American-Express-Ellens-Dance.html |title=American Express - Ellen's Dance |publisher=splendAd |accessdate=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507085720/http://www.splendad.com/ads/show/1120-American-Express-Ellens-Dance.html |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> golfer [[Tiger Woods]];<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.adforum.com/creative-work/ad/player/34474557/tiger-woods/american-express |title=American Express - \"Tiger Woods\" |publisher=adforum |accessdate=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507085422/https://www.adforum.com/creative-work/ad/player/34474557/tiger-woods/american-express |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> professional snowboarder [[Shaun White]];<ref>{{cite video|publisher=[[YouTube]]|title=Shaun White American Express Commercial|date=June 3, 2007| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yr4515xEEPM}}</ref> tennis pros [[Venus Williams]], [[Andy Roddick]], and [[Andre Agassi]];<ref>{{cite video|publisher=[[YouTube]]|title=Venus Williams (2004 American Express ad)|date=February 15, 2010| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RhhmCeF1kZw}}</ref><ref>{{cite video|publisher=[[YouTube]]|title=Roddick vs Pong|date=May 28, 2006|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7UfGpt-0ncc|access-date=May 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228010737/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7UfGpt-0ncc|archive-date=February 28, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"MembersProjectAd\">{{cite web |url=https://www.adforum.com/talent/42675-sheryl-crow/work/6698113 |title=American Express - \"The Members Project\" |publisher=adforum |accessdate=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507085313/https://www.adforum.com/talent/42675-sheryl-crow/work/6698113 |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> surfer [[Laird Hamilton]]<ref name=\"amex-adsoftheworld-04/2009\"/> Manchester United manager [[Jos\u00e9 Mourinho]];<ref>{{cite video|publisher=[[YouTube]]|title=American Express Card by Jos\u00e9 Mourinho|date=May 13, 2008| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2HtsaHFAbas}}</ref> film directors [[Martin Scorsese]],<ref>{{cite video|publisher=[[YouTube]]|title=Martin Scorsese American Express|date=September 23, 2007|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=45iZP6AWT3c|access-date=May 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180327013708/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=45iZP6AWT3c|archive-date=March 27, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Wes Anderson]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.splendad.com/ads/show/1500-American-Express-Wes-Anderson.html |title=American Express - Wes Anderson |publisher=splendAd |accessdate=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507085734/http://www.splendad.com/ads/show/1500-American-Express-Wes-Anderson.html |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[M. Night Shyamalan]];<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.splendad.com/ads/show/1111-American-Express-M-Night-Shyamalan.html |title=American Express - M. Night Shyamalan |publisher=splendAd |accessdate=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507085925/http://www.splendad.com/ads/show/1111-American-Express-M-Night-Shyamalan.html |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> singers [[Sheryl Crow]], [[Alicia Keys]] and [[Beyonc\u00e9]].<ref name=\"MembersProjectAd\"/><ref>{{cite video|publisher=[[YouTube]]|title=Beyonce's American express commercial|date=October 4, 2007|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xH0t4Fwx_o8|access-date=May 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419192232/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xH0t4Fwx_o8|archive-date=April 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Animals====\nIn 2007, a two-minute black-and-white ad, entitled \"Animals\" and starring [[Ellen DeGeneres]], won the [[Emmy Award]] for Outstanding Commercial.<ref>{{cite web| title=59th Emmy Awards Nominees and Winners: Outstanding Commercial - 2007| url=http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2007/outstanding-commercial| publisher=Academy of Television Arts & Sciences| accessdate=February 4, 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205190131/http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2007/outstanding-commercial| archive-date=February 5, 2018| url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| url=http://adage.com/article/creativity-news/american-express-animals-earns-emmy-outstanding-commercial/120503/| journal=Advertising Age| title=American Express \"Animals\" earns the Emmy for Outstanding Commercial| date=September 17, 2007| last=Diaz| first=Ann-Christine| accessdate=February 4, 2018| url-access=subscription| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205184437/http://adage.com/article/creativity-news/american-express-animals-earns-emmy-outstanding-commercial/120503/| archive-date=February 5, 2018| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===C F. Frost===\nMany American Express credit card ads feature a sample American Express Card with the name \"C. F. Frost\" on the front. This is not a fabricated name; Charles F. Frost was an advertising executive at Ogilvy & Mather.<ref>{{cite web |first=Cecil |last=Adams |url=http://www.straightdope.com/classics/a1_180.html |title=Who is C. F. Frost, whose name appears on sample American Express cards? |work=[[The Straight Dope]] |date=December 16, 1983 |accessdate=February 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080531010042/http://www.straightdope.com/classics/a1_180.html |archive-date=May 31, 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Cause marketing===\nAmerican Express was one of the earliest users of [[cause marketing]], to great success.<ref name=\"forbescause\">{{cite journal |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/davidhessekiel/2012/01/31/cause-marketing-leaders-of-the-pack/ |title=Cause Marketing Leaders of the Pack |journal=[[Forbes]] |date=January 31, 2012 |accessdate=August 18, 2013 |last=Hessekiel |first=David |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130818053749/http://www.forbes.com/sites/davidhessekiel/2012/01/31/cause-marketing-leaders-of-the-pack/ |archive-date=August 18, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> A 1983 promotion advertised that for each purchase made with an American Express Card, American Express would contribute one penny to the renovation of the [[Statue of Liberty]]. The campaign generated contributions of $1.7&nbsp;million to the Statue of Liberty restoration project. What would soon capture the attention of marketing departments of major corporations was that the promotion generated approximately a 28% increase in American Express card usage by consumers.\n\nIn May 2007, American Express launched an initiative called the Members Project.<ref>[http://www.membersproject.com \"Members Project from American Express\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090405122736/http://www.membersproject.com/ |date=April 5, 2009 }}. Facebook. Retrieved January 9, 2012.</ref><ref name=\"American Express Rewards\">{{cite web |author=Peetu |url=http://americanexpressrewards.net/ |title=American Express Rewards |publisher=American Express Rewards |accessdate=December 18, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111219120103/http://americanexpressrewards.net/ |archivedate=December 19, 2011}}</ref> Cardholders were invited to submit ideas for projects, and were told American Express was funding the winning project.\n\n==Cultural projects==\n\nAmerican Express supports initiatives to enhance the architectural and cultural heritage, with the aim of raising awareness on the importance of historical and environmental conservation, through the restoration of historical monuments. American Express is a founder sponsor of the global program \"World Monuments Watch\",  launched in 1995, by [[World Monuments Fund]]. During the first edition of [[Corporate Art Awards]], in 2016, American Express received by [[pptArt]] the Corporate Art Award for its international restoration program.<ref>{{cite web| title=Winner of the 2016 edition of the Corporate Art Awards| url=https://www.pptart.net/winners| access-date=March 1, 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180213080154/https://www.pptart.net/winners| archive-date=February 13, 2018| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Workplace==\n\n===Offices===\n[[File:American Express Tower 9-11.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Two [[Rescue and recovery effort after the September 11 attacks|rescue workers]] entering the American Express Tower following [[September 11 attacks|September 11]] terrorist attack on [[World Trade Center (1973-2001)|World Trade Center]].]]\n[[File:Amex House, Edward Street, Brighton (from southeast).jpg|thumb|150px|[[Amex House]] in [[Brighton]], England, was built in 1977.]]\n[[File:AmEx Rome 2.jpg|thumb|150px|American Express [[Italy]] HQ in Rome]]\n[[File:AmExSouthFlorida.jpg|thumb|An American Express regional HQ in Sunrise, Florida.]]\nIn April 1986, American Express moved its headquarters to the 51-story [[Three World Financial Center]] in New York City. After [[September 11 attacks|the events of September 11, 2001]], American Express had to leave its headquarters temporarily because it was located directly opposite the [[World Trade Center (1973-2001)|World Trade Center]] and was damaged during the fall of the towers. The company began gradually moving back into its rehabilitated building in 2002.\n\nThe company maintains major offices in [[Sunrise, Florida]], [[Salt Lake City]], and [[Phoenix, Arizona]], with its main [[data center]]s in [[North Carolina]] and Phoenix.\n\nAMEX Bank of Canada was founded in 1853, in Toronto. It currently{{when|date=August 2019}} has 3,000 employees in its head office at Sheppard, east of Highway 404 in [[Toronto]] (relocated from [[Markham, Ontario]], a northern suburb of Toronto where it resided from 1985 to 2015), as well as an office in [[Hamilton, Ontario]]. The company began operations as a bank on July 1, 1990, following an [[order-in-council]] made by the [[Brian Mulroney]] government on November 21, 1988. This decision was not without controversy as federal banking policy at the time would not ordinarily have permitted American Express to operate as a bank.<ref>{{cite journal| last=Newman| first=Peter C.| date=July 30, 1990| title=The brash new kid on the block| journal=[[Maclean's]]| volume=103| number=31| page=33}}</ref>  It is a member of the [[Canadian Bankers Association]] (CBA) and a registered member of the [[Canada Deposit Insurance Corporation]] (CDIC), the federal agency insuring deposits at all of Canada's chartered banks.\n\nAmerican Express has several offices in the UK, including a European Service Center in the [[Carlton Hill, Brighton|Carlton Hill]] area of [[Brighton]], England. The building was completed in 2012. It replaced American Express's former building, Amex House, a large white tower block built in 1977 and surrounded by several other smaller offices around the city.<ref name=\"Collis9\">{{cite book| last=Collis| first=Rose| others=(based on the original by Tim Carder)| title=The New Encyclopaedia of Brighton| edition=1st| year=2010| publisher=Brighton & Hove Libraries| location=Brighton| isbn=978-0-9564664-0-2| page=9}}</ref>  The American Express European Service Center deals with card servicing, sales, fraud and merchant servicing. The official Europe, Middle East, and Africa HQ is located in the [[Belgravia]] district of Westminster, in [[central London]], at Belgrave House on Buckingham Palace Road, SW1; other UK offices are based in [[Sussex]] at [[Burgess Hill]]. In November 2009, [[Brighton and Hove]] City Council granted planning permission for American Express to redevelop the Amex House site.\n\nThe Japan, Asia-Pacific, and Australian Headquarters is co-located in Singapore, at [[Collyer Quay|16 Collyer Quay]], and in [[Sydney]]'s [[King Street Wharf]] area.\n\nThe headquarters of the Latin America and [[Caribbean]] division is in [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida]].\n\nAmerican Express also has a significant presence in India. Its two centres are located at [[Gurgaon]], [[Haryana]] and on Mathura Road in [[New Delhi]]. The Indian operations of American Express revolves around the [[back office]] customer services operations apart from the credit card business for the domestic Indian Economy, arguably the American Express campus in Gurgaon is the largest employee location by head count for Amex and supports business continuity objectives of Amex including during Hurricane Sandy, the center works 24/7 and includes a co-located second building which was recently{{when|date=September 2019}} transferred to a third party service provider but does much work for Amex.\n\n===Job satisfaction===\nIn 2008, American Express was named the 62nd best company to work for in the United States by ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'', ranking it number one for bank card companies.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/bestcompanies/2008/full_list/index.html| title=100 Best Companies to Work For| work=[[CNN Business|CNN Money]]| accessdate=October 9, 2008| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100723223729/http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/bestcompanies/2008/full_list/index.html| archive-date=July 23, 2010| url-status=live}}</ref> In October 2008, Amex Canada Inc. was named one of [[Greater Toronto's Top Employers]] by Mediacorp Canada Inc., which was announced by the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' newspaper.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.eluta.ca/top-employer-amex-canada| title=Reasons for Selection, 2009 Greater Toronto's Top Employers Competition| publisher=Eluta.ca| access-date=January 27, 2009| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091016192436/http://www.eluta.ca/top-employer-amex-canada| archive-date=October 16, 2009| url-status=live}}</ref> In 2018, ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' ranked it the 23rd best company to work for.<ref name=\"fortune100best\">{{Cite web |url=http://fortune.com/best-companies/american-express/ |title=Fortune Best Companies to Work For : American Express |access-date=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507085732/http://fortune.com/best-companies/american-express/ |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2019, ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' ranked it the 9th best company to work for.<ref name=\"fortune100best\"/>\n\n==Management and corporate governance==\nThe officers of the company are listed on the company's website as follows:<ref name=officersanddirectors>{{Cite web |url=http://ir.americanexpress.com/Officers-and-Directors |title=American Express: Officers & Directors |access-date=April 16, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416074126/http://ir.americanexpress.com/Officers-and-Directors |archive-date=April 16, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* Stephen J. Squeri: chairman and chief executive officer\n* Douglas E. Buckminster: group president, global consumer services\n* Jeffrey C. Campbell: executive vice president and [[chief financial officer]]\n* L. Kevin Cox: chief human resources officer\n* Paul D. Fabara: president, Global Services Group\n* Marc D. Gordon: executive vice president and chief information officer\n* Michael J. O'Neill: executive vice president, corporate affairs and communications\n* Denise Pickett: president, global risk, banking and compliance and chief risk officer\n* Elizabeth Rutledge: executive vice president and [[chief marketing officer]]\n* Laureen E. Seeger: executive vice president and [[general counsel]]\n* Anr\u00e9 Williams: group president, global merchant and network services\n\nThe members of the company's board of directors are listed on the company's website as follows:<ref name=officersanddirectors/>\n* Stephen J. Squeri: chairman and CEO of American Express Company\n* Charlene Barshefsky: senior international partner at WilmerHale\n* John J. Brennan: chairman emeritus and senior advisor of The Vanguard Group\n* Ursula Burns: chairman, VEON supervisory board\n* Peter Chernin: founder and CEO of The Chernin Group, LLC\n* Ralph de la Vega: chairman and founder of the De La Vega Group\n* Anne L. Lauvergeon: founder and CEO of A.L.P.\n* Michael O. Leavitt: founder, Leavitt Partners, LLC\n* Theodore J. Leonsis: chairman and CEO, Monumental Sports & Entertainment, LLC\n* Richard C. Levin: senior advisor and former CEO, Coursera\n* Samuel J. Palmisano: former chairman, president and CEO, IBM\n* Daniel L. Vasella: honorary chairman and former chairman and CEO, Novartis AG\n* Robert D. Walter: founder and former chairman and chief executive officer, Cardinal Health, Inc.\n* Ronald A. Williams: former chairman and CEO of Aetna, Inc.\n\n== Ownership ==\n{{as of|2017||}}, American Express shares are mainly held by institutional investors ([[Berkshire Hathaway]], [[Vanguard group]], [[BlackRock]], [[State Street Corporation]] and others.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.nasdaq.com/symbol/axp/ownership-summary| title=American Express Company Ownership Summary| publisher=[[NASDAQ]]| accessdate=April 30, 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316023518/https://www.nasdaq.com/symbol/axp/ownership-summary| archive-date=March 16, 2018| url-status=live}}</ref>)\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Banks}} \n* [[Falmer Stadium]] in [[East Sussex]], [[England]]\n* [[American Express Gold card dress of Lizzy Gardiner]]\n* [[Small Business Saturday]], a registered trademark of American Express\n* [[Damage waiver#Credit card coverage of damage waiver|Credit card coverage of rental car damage waiver]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|American Express}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.americanexpress.com/}}\n{{Finance links\n| name = American Express\n| symbol = AXP\n| sec_cik = AXP\n| yahoo = AXP\n| google = AXP\n}}\n\n{{American Express}}\n{{Credit cards}}\n{{Dow Jones Industrial Average companies}}\n{{Use American English|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:American Express| ]]\n[[Category:1850 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Banks based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Banks of the United States]]\n[[Category:Berkshire Hathaway]]\n[[Category:Butterfield Overland Mail]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Companies in the Dow Jones Industrial Average]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the New York Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Contactless smart cards]]\n[[Category:Credit card issuer associations]]\n[[Category:Credit cards]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 1850]]\n[[Category:Foreign exchange companies]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Payment systems]]\n[[Category:Publicly traded companies based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Travel management]]\n[[Category:Wells Fargo]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Amex||AMEX (disambiguation){{!}}AMEX}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = American Express Company<!--exact legal name as specified in its charter-->\n| logo = American Express logo (2018).svg\n| logo_size = 150px\n| type = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as = {{NYSE|AXP}}<br />[[DJIA|DJIA component]]<br />[[S&P 100|S&P 100 component]]<br />[[S&P 500|S&P 500 component]]\n| predecessor = {{nowrap|Livingston, Fargo & Company}}<br />{{nowrap|Wells, Butterfield & Company}}<br />{{nowrap|Wells & Company}}\n| industry = [[Bank]]ing<br />{{nowrap|[[Financial services]]}}\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|1850|3|18}}, in [[Buffalo, New York]], U.S.\n| location = [[200 Vesey Street]]\n| location_city = [[New York City|New York City, New York]]\n| location_country = United States\n| key_people = {{nowrap|[[Stephen Squeri|Stephen J. Squeri]]}}<br />{{nowrap|{{small|([[Chairman#Public corporations|Chairman]] & [[CEO]])}}}}<br />{{nowrap|Jeffrey C. Campbell}}<br />{{nowrap|{{small|([[Vice president#In business|Executive VP]] & [[CFO]])}}}}\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| products = {{nowrap|[[Charge card]]s}}<br />{{nowrap|[[Credit card]]s}}<br />{{nowrap|[[Traveler's cheque]]s}}<br />{{nowrap|[[Corporate banking]]}}\n| services = [[Financial services|Finance]]<br />[[Insurance]]<br />[[Travel]]\n| revenue = {{increase}} {{US$|43.556 billion|link=yes}} {{small|(2019)<ref name=\"10-K\">{{cite web|url=https://last10k.com/sec-filings/axp#link_fullReport |title=American Express Company 2018 Annual Report (Form 10-K) |date=February 2019 |publisher=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]] |website=last10k.com}}</ref>}}\n| operating_income = {{increase}} {{US$|8.164 billion}} {{small|(2018)<ref name=\"10-K\" />}}\n| net_income = {{increase}} {{US$|6.921 billion}} {{small|(2018)<ref name=\"10-K\" />}}\n| assets = {{increase}} {{US$|188.602 billion}} {{small|(2018)<ref name=\"10-K\" />}}\n| equity = {{increase}} {{US$|22.290 billion}} {{small|(2018)<ref name=\"10-K\" />}}\n| num_employees = 59,000 {{small|(December 2018)<ref name=\"10-K\" />}}\n| homepage = {{URL|https://www.americanexpress.com/}}\n| footnotes = <ref name=PZG>Peter Z. Grossman. ''American Express: The Unofficial History of the People Who Built the Great Financial Empire''. New York: Crown Publishers, 1987. (reprint: Beard Books 2006; {{ISBN|1-58798-283-8}}; Chapter 2.)</ref><ref name=NML>Noel M. Loomis, Wells Fargo. New York: Clarkson N. Potter, Inc., 1968</ref><ref name=\"10-K 2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/4962/000000496220000030/axp-20191231.htm|title=US SEC: Form 10-K American Express Company|publisher=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]]|accessdate=February 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215171453/https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/4962/000000496220000030/axp-20191231.htm|archive-date=February 15, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''American Express Company''', also known as '''Amex''', is an American [[multinational corporation|multinational]] [[financial services]] corporation headquartered at [[200 Vesey Street]] in [[New York City]]. The company was founded in 1850 and is one of the 30 components of the [[Dow Jones Industrial Average]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://money.cnn.com/data/markets/dow/?iid=C_MT_Index | title=Dow Jones Industrial Average | work=[[CNN Business|CNN Money]] | accessdate=October 20, 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014230313/http://money.cnn.com/data/markets/dow/?iid=C_MT_Index | archive-date=October 14, 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref> The company is best known for its [[charge card]], [[credit card]], and [[traveler's cheque]] businesses.\n\nIn 2016, credit cards using the American Express network accounted for 22.9% of the total dollar volume of credit card transactions in the United States.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://wallethub.com/edu/market-share-by-credit-card-network/25531/ | title=Market Share by Credit Card Network | first=Alina | last=Comoreanu | website=Wallet Hub | date=March 7, 2017 | access-date=April 8, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170408171736/https://wallethub.com/edu/market-share-by-credit-card-network/25531/ | archive-date=April 8, 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref> {{as of|2019|December|31|df=US}}, the company had 114.4{{nbsp}}million cards in force, including 54.7{{nbsp}}million cards in force in the United States, each with an average annual spending of $19,972.<ref name=\"10-K 2019\"/>\n\nIn 2017, ''[[Forbes]]'' named American Express as the 23rd most valuable brand in the world (and the highest within financial services), estimating the brand to be worth US$24.5{{nbsp}}billion.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/powerful-brands/list/#tab:rank_industry:Financial%20Services |title=Forbes 2017 Rankings - The World's Most Valuable Brands |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180308010404/https://www.forbes.com/powerful-brands/list/#tab:rank_industry:Financial%20Services |archive-date=March 8, 2018}}</ref> In 2020, ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' magazine ranked American Express at number 9 on their Fortune List of the Top 100 Companies to Work For in 2020 based on an employee survey of satisfaction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/best-companies-to-work-for-based-on-employee-satisfaction-fortune-2020-2|title=The 25 best companies to work for, based on employee satisfaction|publisher=[[Business Insider]]|author=Jessica Snouwaert|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe company's [[logo]], adopted in 1958, is a [[gladiator]] or [[centurion]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.companylogos.ws/americanexpresslogo.html |title= American Express Logo Review |year= 2008 |publisher= Company Logos |accessdate= June 25, 2011 |quote= The initial trademark of 1958 described the gladiator in the American Express logo as a gladiator on a shield whereas the current American Express website lists the logo character as a Gladiator Head Design. However, there are many who believe that the gladiator is a centurion ... |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100920014842/http://companylogos.ws/americanexpresslogo.html |archive-date= September 20, 2010 |url-status= dead }}</ref> whose image appears on the company's [[traveler's cheque]]s, [[charge card]]s and [[credit card]]s.\n\n==Early history==\n[[File:American Express Shipping Receipt 1853.jpg|thumb|right|285px|American Express Co. early shipping [[receipt]]s (1853, 1869)]]\n[[File:American Express Company 1865.JPG|thumb|Share of the American Express Company, issued 13. October 1865; signed by William G. Fargo as Secretary and Henry Wells as President]]\nIn 1850, American Express was started as an [[express mail]] business in [[Buffalo, New York]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Recognizing Responsibility: American Express Company 2007/2008 Corporate Citizenship Report|url=http://about.americanexpress.com/csr/docs/cresp.pdf|publisher=American Express Co.|accessdate=2012-07-25|page=8|quote=In 1850, three men\u2014Henry Wells, William G. Fargo and John Butterfield\u2014founded an express company in Buffalo, New York, to forward freight and valuables across the united States.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111116062825/http://about.americanexpress.com/csr/docs/cresp.pdf|archive-date=November 16, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> It was founded as a joint stock corporation by the merger of the express companies owned by [[Henry Wells]] (Wells & Company), [[William G. Fargo]] (Livingston, Fargo & Company), and [[John Warren Butterfield]] (Wells, Butterfield & Company, the successor earlier in 1850 of Butterfield, Wasson & Company).<ref name=PZG/><ref name=NML/> Wells and Fargo also started [[History of Wells Fargo|Wells Fargo & Co.]]<!-- Link should be to \"History of Wells Fargo\" article as it relates to the original Wells, Fargo & Company founded in 1852 by two of Amex's founders (and ultimately acquired by Amex). \"Wells Fargo & Co.\" redirects to the \"Wells Fargo\" article, which is *only* about the post-1998 bank (its holding company uses that name); other than common historical roots in the 1852 Wells, Fargo & Company, there is NO connection between Amex and modern-day Wells Fargo. --> in 1852 when Butterfield and other directors objected to the proposal that American Express extend its operations to California.\n\nAmerican Express initially established its headquarters in a building at the intersection of Jay Street and [[Hudson Street (Manhattan)|Hudson Street]] in what was later called the [[Tribeca]] section of Manhattan. For years it enjoyed a virtual monopoly on the movement of express shipments (goods, securities, currency, etc.) throughout New York State. In 1874, American Express moved its headquarters to 65 Broadway in what was becoming the [[Financial District, Manhattan|Financial District]] of Manhattan, a location it was to retain through two buildings.<ref name=\"Citycyclopedia\">Kenneth T. Jackson. ''The Encyclopedia of New York City''. The New York Historical Society: [[Yale University Press]], 1995. P. 23.</ref>\n\n===American Express buildings===\nIn 1854, the American Express Co. purchased a lot on Vesey Street in New York City as the site for its stables. The company's first New York headquarters was an 1858 marble Italianate palazzo at 55\u201361 [[Hudson Street (Manhattan)|Hudson Street]], which had a busy freight depot on the ground story with a spur line from the [[Hudson River Railroad]]. A stable was constructed in 1867, five blocks north at 4\u20138 Hubert Street.\n\nThe company prospered sufficiently that headquarters were moved in 1874 from the wholesale shipping district to the budding Financial District, and into rented offices in two five-story brownstone commercial buildings at 63 and 65 Broadway that were owned by the Harmony family.<ref name=\"LANDMARKS\">New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission; [http://www.nyc.gov/html/lpc/downloads/pdf/reports/amerexpress.pdf December 12, 1995, Designation List 269; LP-1932] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020225802/http://www.nyc.gov/html/lpc/downloads/pdf/reports/amerexpress.pdf |date=October 20, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1880, American Express built a new warehouse behind the Broadway Building at 46 Trinity Place. The designer is unknown, but it has a fa\u00e7ade of brick arches that are reminiscent of pre-skyscraper New York. American Express has long been out of this building, but it still bears a [[terracotta]] seal with the American Express Eagle.<ref>White, Norval & Willensky, Elliot; ''[[American Institute of Architects|AIA]] Guide to New York City'', 4th Edition; New York Chapter, American Institute of Architects; Crown Publishers/Random House. 2000. {{ISBN|0-8129-3106-8}}; {{ISBN|0-8129-3107-6}}. p.23.</ref> In 1890\u201391 the company constructed a new ten-story building by [[Edward H. Kendall]] on the site of its former headquarters on [[Hudson Street (Manhattan)|Hudson Street]].\n\nBy 1903, the company had assets of some $28&nbsp;million, second only to the [[Citibank|National City Bank of New York]] among [[financial institution]]s in the city. To reflect this, the company purchased the Broadway buildings and site.<ref name=\"LANDMARKS\" />\n[[File:American Express Company Building 65 Broadway entrance.jpg|thumb|250x250px|The [[65 Broadway|American Express Company Building]] at 65 Broadway \u2013 the former headquarters of the American Express Company]]\n\nAt the end of the Wells-Fargo reign in 1914, an aggressive new president, George Chadbourne Taylor (1868\u20131923), who had worked his way up through the company over the previous thirty years, decided to build a new headquarters. The old buildings, dubbed by [[the New York Times]] as \"among the ancient landmarks\" of lower Broadway, were inadequate for such a rapidly expanding concern.\n\nAfter some delays due to the First World War, the 21-story [[Neoclassicism|neo-classical]] [[65 Broadway|American Express Co. Building]] was constructed in 1916\u201317 to the design of James L. Aspinwall, of the firm of Renwick, Aspinwall & Tucker, the successor to the architectural practice of the eminent [[James Renwick, Jr.]]. The building consolidated the two lots of the former buildings with a single address: [[65 Broadway]]. This building was part of the \"Express Row\" section of lower Broadway at the time. The building completed the continuous masonry wall of its block-front and assisted in transforming Broadway into the \"canyon\" of neo-classical masonry office towers familiar to this day.<ref name=\"AIA22\">{{cite AIA5|page=22}}</ref> American Express sold this building in 1975, but retained travel services there. The building was also the headquarters over the years of other prominent firms, including investment bankers [[J. & W. Seligman & Co.|J.& W. Seligman & Co]]. (1940\u201374), the [[American Bureau of Shipping]], a maritime concern (1977\u201386), and later J.J. Kenny, and [[Standard & Poor's]], the latter of which renamed the building for itself.<ref name=\"LANDMARKS\" /><ref name=\"AIA22\" />\n\n===Nationwide expansion===\nAmerican Express extended its reach nationwide by arranging affiliations with other express companies (including [[History of Wells Fargo|Wells Fargo]]<!-- Link should be to \"History of Wells Fargo\" article as it relates to the original Wells, Fargo & Company founded in 1852 by two of Amex's founders (and ultimately acquired by Amex). The \"Wells Fargo\" article is *only* about the post-1998 bank; other than common historical roots in the 1852 Wells, Fargo & Company, there is NO connection between Amex and modern-day Wells Fargo. --> \u2013 the replacement for the two former companies that merged to form American Express), railroads, and steamship companies.<ref name=\"Citycyclopedia\" />\n\n===Financial services===\nIn 1857, American Express started its expansion in the area of financial services by launching a [[money order]] business<ref name=\"Citycyclopedia\" /> to compete with the [[United States Post Office]]'s money orders.\n\n[[File:Amer express dog 1890.jpg|thumb|right|200px|The American Express logo in 1890 depicting a watchdog lying on top of a shipping trunk to symbolise trust and security]]\nSometime between 1888 and 1890, [[J. C. Fargo]] took a trip to Europe and returned frustrated and infuriated. Despite the fact that he was president of American Express and that he carried with him traditional [[letter of credit|letters of credit]], he found it difficult to obtain cash anywhere except in major cities. Fargo went to [[Marcellus Flemming Berry]] and asked him to create a better solution than the letter of credit. Berry introduced the American Express [[traveler's cheque|Traveler's Cheque]] which was launched in 1891 in denominations of $10, $20, $50, and $100.<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,866900-7,00.html Host With The Most] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100616020709/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,866900-7,00.html |date=June 16, 2010 }}, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', April 9, 1956 issue</ref>\n\nTraveler's cheques established American Express as a truly international company. In 1914, at the onset of [[World War I]], American Express in Europe was among the few companies to honor the letters of credit (issued by various banks) held by Americans in Europe, because other financial institutions refused to assist these stranded travelers.\n\nThe British government appointed American Express its official agent at the beginning of World War I.  They were to deliver letters, money and relief parcels to British prisoners of war.  Their employees went into camps to cash drafts for both British and French prisoners and arranged for them to receive money from home.\n\nBy the end of the war they were delivering 150 tonnes of parcels per day to prisoners in six countries.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Barham|first1=Peter|title=The impact of the Great War in 1916.|journal=Great Eastern Journal|date=January 2016|issue=165|page=14}}</ref>\n\n===Loss of railroad express business===\nAmerican Express became one of the monopolies that [[Theodore Roosevelt|President Theodore Roosevelt]] had the [[Interstate Commerce Commission]] (ICC) investigated during his administration. The interest of the ICC was drawn to its strict control of the railroad express business. However, the solution did not come immediately to hand.<ref name=\"Citycyclopedia\" /> The solution to this problem came as a coincidence to other problems during World War I.\n\nDuring the winter of 1917, the United States suffered a severe coal shortage and on December 26 [[President of the United States|President]] [[Woodrow Wilson]] commandeered the railroads on behalf of the United States government to move [[United States Armed Forces|federal troops]], their supplies, and coal. Treasury Secretary [[William Gibbs McAdoo]] was assigned the task of consolidating the railway lines for the [[war effort]]. All contracts between express companies and railroads were nullified and McAdoo proposed that all existing express companies be consolidated into a single company to serve the country's needs. This ended American Express's express business, and removed them from the ICC's interest. The result was that a new company called the [[Railway Express Agency|American Railway Express Agency]] formed in July 1918. The new entity took custody of all the pooled equipment and property of existing express companies (the largest share of which, 40%, came from American Express, who had owned the rights to the express business over {{convert|71280|mi|km}} of railroad lines, and had 10,000 offices, with over 30,000 employees).\n\n===Investment banking===\nDuring the 1980s, American Express embarked on an effort to become a financial services supercompany and made a number of acquisitions to create an investment banking arm. In mid-1981 it purchased [[Sanford I. Weill]]'s [[Shearson Loeb Rhoades]], the second largest securities firm in the United States to form [[Shearson/American Express]].\n\n[[File:Shearson Lehman Logo.png|170px|Shearson Lehman logo|thumb|right]]\n\nAfter the purchase of Shearson, Weill was given the position of president of American Express in 1983. Weill grew increasingly unhappy with responsibilities within American Express and his conflicts with American Express' CEO [[James D. Robinson III]]. Weill soon realized that he was not positioned to be named CEO and left in August 1985. In 1984, American Express acquired the [[investment banking]] and trading firm [[Lehman Brothers|Lehman Brothers Kuhn Loeb]], and added it to the Shearson family, creating Shearson Lehman/American Express.  It was Lehman's CEO and former trader [[Lewis Glucksman]] who would next lead Shearson Lehman/American Express.\n\nIn 1984, Shearson/American Express purchased the 90-year-old [[Investors Diversified Services]], bringing with it a fleet of financial advisors and investment products. In 1988, Shearson Lehman acquired the brokerage firm [[E.F. Hutton & Co.]]. E.F. Hutton was merged with the investment banking business and the investment banking arm was renamed [[Shearson Lehman Hutton, Inc.]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/12/03/business/shearson-reported-to-acquire-hutton-in-a-1-billion-deal.html |title=Shearson Reported To Acquire Hutton In a $1 Billion Deal |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 3, 1987 |first=Robert J. |last=Cole |access-date=February 5, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161110012931/http://www.nytimes.com/1987/12/03/business/shearson-reported-to-acquire-hutton-in-a-1-billion-deal.html |archive-date=November 10, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nHowever, when [[Harvey Golub]] became CEO of American Express in 1993, American Express decided to get out of the investment banking business and negotiated the sale of Shearson's retail brokerage and [[Investment management|asset management]] business to [[Primerica]]. The Shearson business was merged with Primerica's [[Smith Barney]] to create [[Smith Barney Shearson]]. Ultimately, the Shearson name was dropped in 1994.<ref name=shearsondropped>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/11/10/business/shearson-name-may-disappear.html |title=Shearson Name may Disappear |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=November 10, 1993 |agency=Bloomberg News |access-date=February 5, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161110013647/http://www.nytimes.com/1993/11/10/business/shearson-name-may-disappear.html |archive-date=November 10, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, American Express spun off of the remaining investment banking and institutional businesses as [[Lehman Brothers|Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc]].{{citation needed|date=August 2019}} After almost fifteen years of independence, Lehman Brothers [[Bankruptcy of Lehman Brothers|filed for bankruptcy protection in 2008]] as part of the [[financial crisis of 2007\u201308]].\n\n==Recent history==\n{{unreferenced section|date=September 2019}}\nFormer CEO [[Kenneth Chenault]] took over leadership of American Express in 2001, from [[Harvey Golub]], CEO from 1993 to 2001. Prior to that, the company was headed by [[James D. Robinson III]] from 1977 to 1993, [[Howard L. Clark Sr.]] from 1960 to 1977, and [[Ralph Reed (American Express)|Ralph Reed]] from 1944 to 1960. Current CEO: Stephen Joseph Squeri since February 1, 2018.{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n===Charge card services===\n[[File:World Financial Center.jpg|left|thumb|200px|[[American Express Tower]] (tallest, left) in New York City]]\nAmerican Express executives discussed the possibility of launching a travel [[charge card]] as early as 1946, but it was not until [[Diners Club]] launched a card in March 1950, that American Express began to seriously consider the possibility. At the end of 1957, American Express CEO [[Ralph Reed (American Express)|Ralph Reed]] decided to get into the card business, and by the launch date of October 1, 1958, public interest had become so significant that 250,000 cards were issued prior to the official launch date. The card was launched with an annual fee of $6, $1 higher than Diners Club, to be seen as a premium product. The first cards were made of paper, with the account number and cardmember's name typed. In 1959, American Express began issuing embossed [[ISO/IEC 7810]] plastic cards, an industry first.<ref name=ourstory>{{cite web|website=American Express|url=https://secure.cmax.americanexpress.com/Internet/GlobalCareers/Staffing/Shared/Files/our_story_3.pdf|title=Our Story|access-date=September 8, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303203130/https://secure.cmax.americanexpress.com/Internet/GlobalCareers/Staffing/Shared/Files/our_story_3.pdf|archive-date=March 3, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1966, American Express introduced the Gold Card.<ref name=ourstory/> In 1984, the company launched the Platinum Card, clearly defining different [[market segment]]s within its own business, a practice that has proliferated across a broad array of industries.<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://about.americanexpress.com/news/pr/2011/pct.aspx | title=American Express Platinum Card Packs on the Perks for International Travelers | publisher=American Express | date=April 5, 2011 | access-date=April 12, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170520201642/http://about.americanexpress.com/news/pr/2011/pct.aspx | archive-date=May 20, 2017 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> The Platinum Card was billed as super-exclusive and had a $250 annual fee ({{as of|September 2019|lc=yes}}, the fee is $550<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanexpress.com/us/credit-cards/card/platinum/|website=American Express|title=The Platinum Card|access-date=December 1, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016202121/https://www.americanexpress.com/us/credit-cards/card/platinum/|archive-date=October 16, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>). It was offered by invitation only to American Express customers with at least two years of tenure, significant spending, and excellent payment history; {{as of|2019|lc=yes}}, it is open to applicants on request. In 1987, American Express introduced the Optima card, its first credit card product that did not have to be paid in full at the end of the month.\n\nAmerican Express formed a venture with [[Warner Communications]] in 1979, called [[Warner-Amex Satellite Entertainment]], which created MTV, [[Nickelodeon]], and [[The Movie Channel]]. The partnership lasted only until 1984. The properties were sold to [[Viacom (1971\u20132005)|Viacom]] soon after.\n\nIn April 1992, American Express spun off its former subsidiary, [[First Data Corp.]], in an [[initial public offering]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstdata.com/en_us/about-first-data/media/first-data-history.html|website=First Data|title=First Data History|access-date=April 12, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170317144814/https://www.firstdata.com/en_us/about-first-data/media/first-data-history.html|archive-date=March 17, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, the Optima True Grace card was introduced. The card was unique in that it offered a [[grace period]] on all purchases whether a balance was carried on the card or not (as opposed to traditional revolving credit cards which charge interest on new purchases if so much as $1 was carried over).<ref>{{cite web | url=https://articles.latimes.com/1994-09-07/business/fi-35691_1_grace-period | title=American Express Launches New Credit Card | first=Kathy M. | last=Kristof | newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] | date=September 7, 1994 | access-date=April 12, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170413073208/http://articles.latimes.com/1994-09-07/business/fi-35691_1_grace-period | archive-date=April 13, 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref> The card was discontinued a few years later; the now discontinued{{when|date=August 2019}} One from American Express card offered a similar feature called \"Interest Protection\".\n\n===\"Boston Fee Party\"===\nFrom the early 1980s until the early 1990s, American Express was known for cutting its [[interchange fee]] (also known as a \"discount rate\") to merchants and restaurants if they accepted only American Express and no other credit or charge cards. This prompted competitors such as [[Visa Inc.|Visa]] and [[Mastercard]] to cry foul for a while as the tactics \"locked\" restaurants into American Express. Capitalizing on this elitist image, American Express frequently mentioned such exclusive partnerships in its advertising.<ref>{{cite video|publisher=[[YouTube]]|title=American Express Super Bowl XXV ad feat. Dana Carvey & Jon Lovitz - Travelling (1991)|date=April 16, 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XeSnqSfRkgE|access-date=September 28, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323090235/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XeSnqSfRkgE|archive-date=March 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAside from some holdouts including [[Neiman Marcus]] (which continued exclusivity until 2011), the practice largely ended in 1991. A group of restaurants in [[Boston]] stopped accepting American Express while accepting and encouraging the use of Visa and Mastercard, including some that were exclusive to American Express. The rationale was due to far lower fees as compared with American Express' fees at the time (which were about 4% for each transaction versus around 1.2% at the time for Visa and Mastercard). The revolt, known as the \"Boston Fee Party\" (alluding to the [[Boston Tea Party]]), spread to over 250 restaurants across the United States, including restaurants in other cities such as [[New York City]], [[Chicago]], and [[Los Angeles]]. Visa offered to pay the Fee Party's legal bills, and [[Discover Card]] was able to increase their acceptance among Boston restaurants by 375%. Kenneth Chenault, then head of Travel Related Services prior to becoming American Express CEO, cut fees to bring these restaurants back into the fold.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.bloomberg.com/features/2015-how-amex-lost-costco/| title=How Bad Will It Get for American Express?| last1=Leonard| first1=Devin| last2=Dexheimer| first2=Elizabeth| publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]]| date=October 15, 2015| access-date=March 5, 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170413071646/https://www.bloomberg.com/features/2015-how-amex-lost-costco/| archive-date=April 13, 2017| url-status=live}}</ref> American Express then shifted its focus from exclusivity to broadening acceptance, adding mainstream merchants like [[Walmart]] to the American Express network.\n\n===Conversion to bank holding company===\nOn November 10, 2008, during the [[financial crisis of 2007\u20132008]], the company won [[Federal Reserve System]] approval to convert to a [[bank holding company]], making it eligible for government help under the [[Troubled Asset Relief Program]].<ref name=\"American-Express-Dec-2008-8-K\">{{cite web| url=http://pdf.secdatabase.com/2714/0001104659-08-078273.pdf| title=American Express, Form 8-K, Current Report, Filing Date Dec 23, 2008| publisher=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission|Securities and Exchange Commission]]| accessdate=January 6, 2013| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512070738/http://pdf.secdatabase.com/2714/0001104659-08-078273.pdf| archive-date=May 12, 2013| url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"lanman\">{{cite news |title=American Express Gets Fed Approval to Convert to Bank |network=[[NPR]] |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=96844962 |air-date=November 11, 2008 |series=[[Morning Edition]] |first=Ari |last=Shapiro |author-link=Ari Shapiro |accessdate=February 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205130124/https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=96844962 |archive-date=February 5, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> At that time, American Express had total consolidated assets of about $127{{nbsp}}billion.<ref name=\"lanman\"/> In June 2009, $3.39{{nbsp}}billion in TARP funds were repaid plus $74.4{{nbsp}}million in dividend payments. In July 2009, the company ended its obligations under TARP by buying back $340{{nbsp}}million in Treasury warrants.<ref name=\"American-Express-Jul-2009-8-K\">{{cite web| url=http://edgar.secdatabase.com/2182/496209000030/filing-main.htm| title=American Express, Form 8-K, Current Report, Filing Date Jul 29, 2009| publisher=Securities and Exchange Commission| accessdate=January 6, 2013| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512074543/http://edgar.secdatabase.com/2182/496209000030/filing-main.htm| archive-date=May 12, 2013| url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=AmEx Gets Out of TARP; Pays $340M for Warrants| url=http://wallstreetpit.com/8963-amex-gets-out-of-tarp-pays-340m-for-warrants| publisher=wallstreetpit.com| date=July 29, 2009| accessdate=August 21, 2009| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100205135530/http://wallstreetpit.com/8963-amex-gets-out-of-tarp-pays-340m-for-warrants| archive-date=February 5, 2010| url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=AmEx gets out of TARP| url=http://money.cnn.com/2009/07/29/news/economy/american_express_tarp.reut/index.htm| website=[[CNN Business|CNN Money]]| date=July 29, 2009| accessdate=August 21, 2009| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514205159/http://money.cnn.com/2009/07/29/news/economy/american_express_tarp.reut/index.htm| archive-date=May 14, 2011| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Charging order controversy in the UK===\nIn November 2010, the UK division of American Express was cautioned by the [[Office of Fair Trading]] for the use of controversial [[charging order]]s against those in debt.<ref>{{cite web| title=OFT Warns Credit Card Providers Off 'Charging Orders'| url=http://www.choose.net/money/guide/news/oft-warns-against-charging-orders.html| publisher=Choose| date=November 10, 2010| access-date=January 26, 2012| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302053525/http://www.choose.net/money/guide/news/oft-warns-against-charging-orders.html| archive-date=March 2, 2012| url-status=live}}</ref> The regulator said that the company was one of four companies who were encouraging customers to turn their unsecured credit card debts into a form of secured debt.\n\n===CFPB enforcement action===\nIn October 2012, The [[Consumer Financial Protection Bureau]] (CFPB) announced an enforcement action with orders requiring three American Express subsidiaries to refund an estimated $85{{nbsp}}million to approximately 250,000 customers for illegal card practices between 2003 and 2012. Allegations included that American Express made misleading statements regarding signup bonuses, charged unlawful late fees, discriminated against applicants due to age, and failed to report consumer complaints to regulators.<ref>{{cite press release| url=https://www.consumerfinance.gov/about-us/newsroom/cfpb-orders-american-express-to-pay-85-million-refund-to-consumers-harmed-by-illegal-credit-card-practices/| title=CFPB Orders American Express to Pay $85 Million Refund to Consumers Harmed by Illegal Credit Card Practices| publisher=[[Consumer Financial Protection Bureau]] (CFPB)| date=October 1, 2012| access-date=April 12, 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170413074426/https://www.consumerfinance.gov/about-us/newsroom/cfpb-orders-american-express-to-pay-85-million-refund-to-consumers-harmed-by-illegal-credit-card-practices/| archive-date=April 13, 2017| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Costco exclusivity arrangement (2004\u20132016)===\nBeginning in 2004, [[Costco]] issued co-branded American Express cards which also doubled as a membership card. Costco ended this arrangement in 2016, in the United States and in 2015, in Canada. The cards did not have annual fees and offered cash back in form of in-store rebates on certain tiers of purchases. The TrueEarnings cards issued by Costco in the United States were an extension of an exclusive credit card network deal between Costco and American Express dating from 1999. Costco was the last major U.S. merchant that accepted American Express cards exclusively. In November 2011, [[Neiman Marcus]], which gave similar general-purpose card exclusivity to American Express since 1987, began accepting Visa and [[Mastercard]].{{citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\nCostco's Canadian stores ended its exclusive deal with American Express in January 2015, in favor of one with [[Capital One]] and Mastercard.<ref>{{cite news| last1=Schecter| first1=Barbara| last2=Leong| first2=Melissa| title=Costco to stop accepting American Express cards in Canada, switches to Capital One and Mastercard| url=http://business.financialpost.com/news/retail-marketing/costco-canada-american-express| accessdate=October 29, 2017| work=[[Financial Post]]| date=September 18, 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103213312/http://business.financialpost.com/news/retail-marketing/costco-canada-american-express| archive-date=January 3, 2018| url-status=live}}</ref> Capital One did not buy accounts and balances from American Express, which required Costco Canada members to apply for the new cards instead of automatically qualifying.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/capital-one-said-to-replace-amex-as-costcos-canada-card-issuer/article20665637/| title=Costco Canada switches to MasterCard from AmEx| first=Marina| last=Strauss| newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]]| date=September 18, 2014| access-date=August 24, 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516160940/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/capital-one-said-to-replace-amex-as-costcos-canada-card-issuer/article20665637/| archive-date=May 16, 2017| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn February 12, 2015, it was announced that the partnership between American Express and Costco in the United States would dissolve March 31, 2016, which was later extended to June 19, 2016. By March 2, 2015, Costco announced that [[Citigroup]] would become the exclusive issuer of Costco's credit cards and that [[Visa Inc.]] would replace American Express as the exclusive credit card network accepted at Costco's stores in the United States. The Costco deal with Visa began on June 20, 2016, and in addition to the new Citi card, Costco accepted all other Visa cards.<ref>{{cite news| newspaper=[[San Antonio Express-News]]| url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/business/national/article/What-to-expect-from-Costco-s-new-deal-with-Visa-6119462.php| title=What to Expect From Costco's New Deal With Visa| access-date=January 22, 2016| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201221834/http://www.mysanantonio.com/business/national/article/What-to-expect-from-Costco-s-new-deal-with-Visa-6119462.php| archive-date=February 1, 2016| url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Los Angeles Times\">{{cite news| url=https://latimes.com/business/la-fi-costco-visa-20150302-story.html| title=Costco names Citi, Visa as new credit card partners after AmEx deal ends| work=[[Los Angeles Times]]| date=March 2, 2015| accessdate=July 1, 2015| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150703133135/http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-costco-visa-20150302-story.html| archive-date=July 3, 2015| url-status=live}}</ref> All TrueEarnings card accounts and balances held by American Express were sold to Citigroup, and new Costco Anywhere Visa cards were sent to Costco members prior to the switch date. Concurrent with the switch to Visa, Costco no longer accepted American Express in stores, at Costco.com, or through Costco Travel.\n\nThe Costco partnership represented 8%, or $80{{nbsp}}billion, of American Express' billed business and about 20%, or about $14{{nbsp}}billion, of its interest-bearing credit portfolio, according to Richard Shane of JPMorgan Chase & Co.<ref name=\"Los Angeles Times\"/> The impact of losing the Costco card accounts was significant; in the first quarter without Costco cards, company profit dropped 10% and revenue dropped 5% compared to the previous year.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.bizjournals.com/seattle/news/2016/10/21/costco-american-express-citigroup-credit-card.html| title=The Costco effect: How American Express is faring after losing co-branded credit cards| first=Coral| last=Garnick| newspaper=Puget Sound Business Journal| date=October 21, 2016| access-date=March 15, 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316204246/http://www.bizjournals.com/seattle/news/2016/10/21/costco-american-express-citigroup-credit-card.html| archive-date=March 16, 2017| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Centurion Lounges ===\nAmerican Express has a network of Centurion Lounges at major airports to cater to their Platinum and Centurion card holders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.creditcards.com/credit-card-news/centurion-lounges-guide.php|title=Guide to Centurion lounges|date=2019-02-27|website=CreditCards.com|access-date=2019-08-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190804223536/https://www.creditcards.com/credit-card-news/centurion-lounges-guide.php|archive-date=August 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Free services include concierge, food and alcohol, wifi, etc. The first lounge opened in 2013, at [[Las Vegas McCarran Airport|McCarran Airport]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rewardexpert.com/blog/american-express-centurion-lounge/|title=The Oasis at the Airport: American Express Centurion Lounge|date=2015-01-05|website=The Source for Maximizing Award Travel|access-date=2019-08-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190804230346/https://www.rewardexpert.com/blog/american-express-centurion-lounge/|archive-date=August 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2019 American Express acquired lounge app LoungeBuddy <ref>{{cite news |last1=Liddington-Cox |first1=Alexander |title=Aussie entrepreneur's airline lounge app is snapped up by American Express |url=https://www.businessinsider.com.au/american-express-snaps-up-aussie-entrepreneurs-airline-lounge-app-2019-3 |accessdate=3 November 2019 |work=Business Insider Australia |publisher=Pedestrian Group |date=14 March 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191103234616/https://www.businessinsider.com.au/american-express-snaps-up-aussie-entrepreneurs-airline-lounge-app-2019-3 |archive-date=November 3, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Finances ==\nFor the fiscal year 2017, American Express reported earnings of US$2.634{{nbsp}}billion, with an annual revenue of US$35.583{{nbsp}}billion, an increase of 5.2% over the previous fiscal cycle. Its shares traded at over $83 per share, and its market capitalization was valued at over US$86.5{{nbsp}}billion in October 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.macrotrends.net/stocks/charts/AXP/american-express/revenue|title=American Express Revenue 2006-2018 {{!}} AXP|website=www.macrotrends.net|access-date=2018-10-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181030170433/https://www.macrotrends.net/stocks/charts/AXP/american-express/revenue|archive-date=October 30, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> American Express ranked {{No.|86}} in the 2018 [[Fortune 500]] list of the largest United States corporations by total revenue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fortune.com/fortune500/list/|title=Fortune 500 Companies 2018: Who Made the List|website=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]|access-date=2018-11-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181110190356/http://fortune.com/fortune500/list/|archive-date=November 10, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable float-left\" style=\"text-align: right;\"\n!Year\n!Revenue<br />in mil. USD$\n!Net income<br />in mil. USD$\n!Total Assets<br />in mil. USD$\n!Price per Share<br />in USD$\n!Employees\n|-\n|2005\n|24,404\n|3,734\n|113,960\n|39.22\n|\n|-\n|2006\n|27,692\n|3,707\n|128,329\n|44.74\n|\n|-\n|2007\n|31,540\n|3,986\n|149,743\n|49.21\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|31,920\n|2,684\n|126,074\n|31.91\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|26,543\n| 2,130\n|125,145\n|23.49\n|\n|-\n|2010\n|30,005\n| 4,006\n|146,689\n|36.98\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|32,282\n|4,877\n|153,337\n|42.84\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|33,781\n|4,433\n|153,140\n|51.29\n|\n|-\n|2013\n|34,828\n|5,312\n|153,375\n|67.63\n|62,000\n|-\n|2014\n|35,895\n|5,839\n|159,103\n|84.25\n|54,000\n|-\n|2015\n|34,441\n| 5,063\n|161,184\n|74.06\n|54,800\n|-\n|2016\n|33,823\n|5,285\n|158,893\n|61.68\n|56,400\n|-\n|2017\n|35,583\n|2,634\n|181,159\n|83.28\n|55,000\n|}\n\n==Card products==\n{{As of|2019|12|31}}, the company had 114.4 million cards in force, including 54.7{{nbsp}}million cards in force in the United States, each with an average annual spending of $19,972.<ref name=\"10-K 2019\"/> These include consumer, small business and corporate cards issued by American Express themselves and cards issued by its Global Service Network partners that run on its network (such as Commonwealth Bank, Westpac and NAB in Australia and Lloyds Bank and Barclays Bank in the UK). On March 1, 2017, Australia's fourth largest bank ANZ announced that it was no longer issuing American Express cards, with the support phased out entirely by August 5, 2017.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.ausbt.com.au/anz-stops-issuing-american-express-credit-cards| title=ANZ stops issuing American Express credit cards| work=Australian Business Traveller| first=Chris| last=Chamberlin| date=March 1, 2017| accessdate=February 4, 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205184349/https://www.ausbt.com.au/anz-stops-issuing-american-express-credit-cards| archive-date=February 5, 2018| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAmerican Express is the fourth largest general-purpose card network on a global basis based on purchase volume, behind China UnionPay, Visa and MasterCard.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://ir.americanexpress.com/Cache/1001233963.PDF?O=PDF&T=&Y=&D=&FID=1001233963&iid=102700| publisher=American express| title=American Express Company Annual Report, 2017| accessdate=March 13, 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180407031203/http://ir.americanexpress.com/Cache/1001233963.PDF?O=PDF&T=&Y=&D=&FID=1001233963&iid=102700| archive-date=April 7, 2018| url-status=live}}</ref> It is the 4th largest card network in the world, based on the number of cards it has in circulation.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.cardhub.com/edu/credit-card-companies/| title=List of Credit Card Companies & Networks: Differences, Contact Info & More| work=Card Hub| accessdate=September 21, 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808053813/http://www.cardhub.com/edu/credit-card-companies/| archive-date=August 8, 2014| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAmerican Express is one of the partner banks to both [[Google]] and [[Apple Inc.|Apple]]'s mobile wallet systems ([[Google Pay]] and [[Apple Pay]], respectively) meaning that cardholders can use their American Express-issued cards to pay at establishments where [[Near field communication|NFC]] payments are accepted. American Express offers various [[Contactless smart card|contactless credit cards]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Contactless | publisher=American Express | url=https://www.americanexpress.com/us/credit-cards/features-benefits/contactless/index.html | access-date=August 22, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190822224502/https://www.americanexpress.com/us/credit-cards/features-benefits/contactless/index.html | archive-date=August 22, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=What Are Contactless Credit Cards? And How Do I Get One? | publisher=Credit Card Insider | date=November 29, 2018 | url=https://www.creditcardinsider.com/blog/what-are-contactless-credit-cards-and-how-do-i-get-one/ | access-date=August 22, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190822224501/https://www.creditcardinsider.com/blog/what-are-contactless-credit-cards-and-how-do-i-get-one/ | archive-date=August 22, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Consumer cards===\n[[File:HK West Kln Waterfront Promenade Hong Kong Wine & Dine Festival Nov-2012 booths American Express sponsor view ICC.JPG|thumb|260px|An advertisement for the American Express Platinum Credit Card in Hong Kong]]\n{{See also|Centurion Card|Accolades Card}}\nAmerican Express is best known for its Green, Gold, and Platinum charge cards.  The Gold Card has recently{{when?|date=September 2019}} been converted to a credit card for UK residents but remains a charge card in the U.S.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thriftypoints.com/american-express-preferred-rewards-gold-card/|title=Amex Gold Card - American Express Preferred Rewards Gold Card Review UK|date=2019-03-05|website=Thrifty Points|access-date=2019-04-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190421143905/https://thriftypoints.com/american-express-preferred-rewards-gold-card/|archive-date=April 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1958, American Express issued its first [[charge card]], which required payment at the end of every month.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/clairetsosie/2016/08/29/what-the-first-credit-cards-were-like/| title=What The First Credit Cards Were Like| first=Claire| last=Tsosie| journal=[[Forbes]]| date=August 29, 2016| access-date=April 9, 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170410133053/https://www.forbes.com/sites/clairetsosie/2016/08/29/what-the-first-credit-cards-were-like/| archive-date=April 10, 2017| url-status=live}}</ref> In 1966, the company issued its first gold card, in an effort to cater to the upper echelon of business travel.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/27/business/american-express-turns-to-its-core-customers-the-affluent.html| title=With Revamped Gold Cards, Bruised American Express Returns Focus to Affluent| first=Hilary| last=Stout| work=[[The New York Times]]| date=February 26, 2015| access-date=April 9, 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205130404/https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/27/business/american-express-turns-to-its-core-customers-the-affluent.html| archive-date=February 5, 2018| url-status=live}}</ref> Its platinum card debuted in 1984.<ref>{{cite press release| url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/the-platinum-cardr-from-american-express-celebrates-its-20th-anniversary-71350477.html| title=The Platinum Card From American Express Celebrates Its 20th Anniversary| publisher=American Express| via=[[PRNewswire]]| date=July 21, 2004| access-date=April 9, 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170410213712/http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/the-platinum-cardr-from-american-express-celebrates-its-20th-anniversary-71350477.html| archive-date=April 10, 2017| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, American Express introduced the [[Centurion Card]], often referred to as the \"black card,\" which caters to an even more affluent customer segment. The card was initially available only to select users of the Platinum card. The annual fee for the card in the United States is $5,000 (up from $1,000 at introduction) with an additional one-time initiation fee of $10,000. American Express created the card line amid rumors and [[urban legend]]s in the 1980s that it produced an ultra-exclusive black card for elite users who could purchase anything with it.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.snopes.com/business/bank/blackcard.asp| website=[[Snopes.com]]| title=Black American Express Card| date=December 6, 2006| accessdate=December 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\nAmerican Express cards issued in the United States range in cost between no annual fee (for Blue and many other consumer and business cards) and a $550 annual fee (for the Platinum card).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/03/02/american-express-revamps-platinum-card-with-200-bonuses-and-550-fee.html|title=Amex revamps Platinum card with new bonuses ... and fees|last=Anderson|first=Tom|date=2017-03-02|website=[[CNBC]]|access-date=2019-08-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920204221/https://www.cnbc.com/2017/03/02/american-express-revamps-platinum-card-with-200-bonuses-and-550-fee.html|archive-date=September 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Annual fees for the Green card start at $150, while Gold card annual fees start at $250.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.americanexpress.com/us/credit-cards/card/green/ |title=Green |website=americanexpress.com |access-date=2019-11-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191127154053/https://www.americanexpress.com/us/credit-cards/card/green |archive-date=November 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.americanexpress.com/us/credit-cards/card/gold-card/ |title=Gold Card |website=americanexpress.com |access-date=2019-11-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016202103/https://www.americanexpress.com/us/credit-cards/card/gold-card/ |archive-date=October 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAmerican Express has several co-branded credit cards, with most falling into one of three categories:\n* Airlines: [[Aerolineas Argentinas]], [[Aerom\u00e9xico]], [[Air Canada]], [[Air France]], [[Alitalia]], [[British Airways]], [[Cathay Pacific]], [[Delta Air Lines]], [[Icelandair]], [[KLM]], [[Qantas]], [[Scandinavian Airlines]], [[Singapore Airlines]], [[SriLankan Airlines]], [[Thai Airways]], [[Virgin Atlantic]], [[Virgin Australia]], among others.\n* Hotels: [[Best Western]], [[Hilton Hotels]], and [[Marriott International]]\n* Retailers: [[David Jones Limited|David Jones]], [[Holt Renfrew]], [[Harrods]], [[Macy's]], [[Bloomingdales]], [[Lowe's]], [[Mercedes Benz]], [[Dillard's]] and others.\n\nA credit card aimed at young adults is called ''Blue'', which has no annual fee and a [[loyalty program]]. A television media campaign for Blue adopted the 1979 UK [[Synthpop]] hit \"[[Cars (song)|Cars]]\" by [[Gary Numan]] as its [[theme music]]. A [[cashback reward program]] version, \"Blue Cash\", quickly followed. American Express also targeted young adults with City Reward Cards that earn INSIDE Rewards points to eat, drink, and play at New York, Chicago and LA hot spots. American Express began phasing out the INSIDE cards in mid-2008, with no new applications being taken as of July 2008.\n\nIn 2005, American Express introduced Clear, advertised as the first credit card with no fees of any kind.  Other cards introduced in 2005, included \"The Knot\" and \"The Nest\" Credit Cards from American Express, co-branded cards developed with the wedding planning website theknot.com.\n\nIn 2006, the UK division of American Express joined the [[Product Red]] coalition and issued a Red Card, donating with each purchase through [[The Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria]] to help African women and children suffering from HIV/AIDS, malaria, and other diseases.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/american-express-launches-red-card-digital-campaign/544285| title=American Express launches Red Card with digital campaign| first=Emma| last=Rig| journal=[[Campaign (magazine)|Campaign]]| date=March 3, 2006| accessdate=February 4, 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180206131435/https://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/american-express-launches-red-card-digital-campaign/544285| archive-date=February 6, 2018| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, American Express introduced the ZYNC charge card. White in color, this card was created for people aged 20\u201340.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://bucks.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/12/08/american-express-zync-will-young-adults-want-a-charge-card/| title=American Express Zync: Will Young Adults Want a Charge Card?| last=Lieber| first=Ron| work=[[The New York Times]]| access-date=2018-01-18| language=en| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180119060640/https://bucks.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/12/08/american-express-zync-will-young-adults-want-a-charge-card/| archive-date=January 19, 2018| url-status=live}}</ref> The Zync charge card has since been discontinued with the exception of current cardholders who are [[grandfathered]] into the ZYNC.\n\nIn late 2012, American Express and [[Walmart]] announced the launch of Bluebird, a [[prepaid debit card]] similar to that of [[Green Dot Corporation|Green Dot]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://about.americanexpress.com/news/pr/2012/american-express-and-walmart-launch-bluebird.aspx| title=American Express and Walmart Launch Bluebird: a New Alternative to Debit and Checking Accounts| accessdate=September 21, 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911181007/http://about.americanexpress.com/news/pr/2012/american-express-and-walmart-launch-bluebird.aspx| archive-date=September 11, 2014| url-status=dead| df=mdy-all}}</ref> Bluebird is being touted as having some of the benefits of traditional American Express cards, such as [[roadside assistance]] and [[identity theft]] protection. The card can also be used as a substitute to a traditional [[Transactional account|checking account]]. Unlike other such cards, Bluebird is [[Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation|FDIC]]-insured.<ref>Kopecki, Dawn. (2013-03-26) [https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-03-26/amex-bluebird-customers-get-fdic-backing-check-writing-feature.html AmEx Bluebird Customers Get FDIC Backing, Check-Writing Feature] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131108053845/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-03-26/amex-bluebird-customers-get-fdic-backing-check-writing-feature.html |date=November 8, 2013 }}. Bloomberg Technology; Retrieved on 2013-08-16; Subscription required.</ref>  Bluebird accounts have standard FDIC deposit insurance and check writing capabilities, and customers can now{{when|date=August 2019}} have Social Security payments, military pay, Tax Return, paycheck and other government benefits deposited directly into their accounts.\n\n===Card acceptance outside the United States===\nAmerican Express credit cards are noted by travel guides, including [[Rough Guides]] and [[Lonely Planet]], as being less commonly accepted in Europe than Visa or Mastercard.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roughguides.com/destinations/europe/france/travel-essentials/|title=Travel essentials|work=[[Rough Guides]]|accessdate=September 21, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140901022929/http://www.roughguides.com/destinations/europe/france/travel-essentials/|archive-date=September 1, 2014|url-status=live}}'' Note: Click 'Read more' to expand information''</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.lonelyplanet.com/denmark/a/nar-gr/money-and-costs/358836| title=Denmark: Money and Costs| work=[[Lonely Planet]]| accessdate=February 4, 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205184433/https://www.lonelyplanet.com/denmark/a/nar-gr/money-and-costs/358836| archive-date=February 5, 2018| url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.visitlondon.com/traveller-information/essential-information/money/british-money| title=British Money| date=April 10, 2007| publisher=[[London and Partners|Visit London]]| accessdate=February 4, 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222025946/http://www.visitlondon.com/traveller-information/essential-information/money/british-money| archive-date=December 22, 2016| url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.dreamofitaly.com/public/Italy-Travel-FAQ-What-is-The-Best-Way-to-Get-Euros-and-Pay-For-Things-in-Italy.cfm| title=Italy Travel F.A.Q.: What is The Best Way to Get Euros and Pay For Things in Italy?| publisher=Dream of Italy| access-date=May 29, 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529122702/http://www.dreamofitaly.com/public/Italy-Travel-FAQ-What-is-The-Best-Way-to-Get-Euros-and-Pay-For-Things-in-Italy.cfm| archive-date=May 29, 2014| url-status=live}}</ref> In an interview with an American Express spokesman in 2010, about card acceptance in the UK, the ''[[Daily Mail]]'''s financial website, ''This is Money'', noted that \"The list of places that are taking American Express appears to be growing, rather than slowing, but it seems to be a little hit-and-miss. It's not a good feeling to enter a shop, not knowing whether or not they accept the card.\"<ref name=\"thisismoney\">{{cite journal| first=Lee| last=Boyce| url=http://www.thisismoney.co.uk/money/experts/article-1699000/Why-dont-places-take-American-Express.html| title=Why don't more places take American Express?| journal=This is Money| date=July 22, 2010| accessdate=February 4, 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205130042/http://www.thisismoney.co.uk/money/experts/article-1699000/Why-dont-places-take-American-Express.html| archive-date=February 5, 2018| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Card design===\nThe company logo, a gladiator or centurion, appears at the center of the iconic Zync, Cobalt, Green, Gold, Platinum, and Centurion cards. The figure and his pose evoke [[classical antiquity]]. These cards also feature intricate border and background designs that read \"American Express.\" The designs on these cards, especially the Green card, bear resemblance to those on United States [[Federal Reserve Notes]].\n\n===ExpressPay===\n[[File:EMVCoContactlessIndicator.svg|right|75px]]\n[[File:Americanexpressplatinumemvcontactless.jpg|thumb|left|A Platinum American Express Charge Card issued in the UK that is contactless-enabled]]\nIn 2005, American Express introduced ExpressPay, similar to Mastercard [[Mastercard#Mastercard Contactless|Contactless]] and Visa [[payWave]], all of which use the symbol appearing on the right. It is a [[contactless payment]] system based on wireless [[RFID]], where transactions are completed by holding the credit card near a receiver at which point the debt is immediately added to the account. All three contactless systems use the same logo. The card is not swiped or inserted into a smart card reader and no PIN is entered.\n\nMany merchants, in the U.S. and globally, offer American Express contactless payment, including [[Meijer]], [[Walgreens]], [[Best Buy]], [[Chevron Corporation]], [[Starbucks]], and [[McDonald's]].\n\n===American Express OPEN===\nAmerican Express OPEN, the small-business branch of American Express, offers various types of charge cards for small businesses to manage their expenses.\n\nIn late 2007, the company announced the new Plum Card as the latest addition to their card line for [[small business]] owners.<ref name=\"American-Express-Oct-2007-8-K\">{{cite web |url=http://edgar.secdatabase.com/2534/496207000049/filing-main.htm |title=American Express, Form 8-K, Current Report, Filing Date Oct 22, 2007 |publisher=Securities and Exchange Commission |accessdate=Jan 6, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512043558/http://edgar.secdatabase.com/2534/496207000049/filing-main.htm |archive-date=May 12, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> The card provides a 1.5% early pay discount or up to two months to defer payment on purchases. The 1.5% discount is available for billing periods where the cardmember spends at least $5,000. The first 10,000 cards were issued to members on December 16, 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.plumcard.com |title=Official Plum Card Website |publisher=Plumcard.com |accessdate=December 18, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010195402/http://www.plumcard.com/ |archive-date=October 10, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, American Express closed all Business Line of Credit accounts. This decision was reached in tandem with the Federal Reserve's approval of American Express's request to become a [[commercial bank]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.usbusinessfinancecorp.com/financeblog/american-express-closes-business-lines-of-credit.html |title=American Express Closes Business Lines of Credit |access-date=April 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170410214503/http://www.usbusinessfinancecorp.com/financeblog/american-express-closes-business-lines-of-credit.html |archive-date=April 10, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2016|7}}, American Express has several credit cards designed for small business. These include SimplyCash Plus Business Credit Card. Cash back earned is automatically credited to the cardholder's statement and other benefits are included.  Other cards include the Business Platinum Card from American Express OPEN, the Business Gold Rewards Card from American Express OPEN, the Blue for Business Credit Card from American Express, Business Green Rewards Card from American Express OPEN, the Business Green Rewards Card from American Express OPEN and the Plum Card from American Express OPEN.  These cards have return protection, year-end summaries and other tools to help with the business accounting and control.<ref name=Daniel>Daniel, Ivan. [https://get.com/blog/american-express-cards-small-business/ Best American Express Cards For Small Business] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819011220/https://get.com/blog/american-express-cards-small-business/ |date=August 19, 2016 }} Get.com. July 7, 2016. Retrieved July 13, 2016.</ref>\n\n===Commercial cards and services===\nIn 2008, American Express acquired the Corporate Payment Services business of GE, which primarily focused on providing Purchasing Card solutions for large global clients.<ref name=\"American-Express-Mar-2008-8-K\">{{cite web |url=http://edgar.secdatabase.com/824/496208000005/filing-main.htm |title=American Express, Form 8-K, Current Report, Filing Date Mar 27, 2008 |publisher=Securities and Exchange Commission |accessdate=Jan 6, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512050655/http://edgar.secdatabase.com/824/496208000005/filing-main.htm |archive-date=May 12, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> As part of the $1b+ transaction, American Express also added a new product, called V-Payment, to its product portfolio. V-Payment is unique in that it enables a tightly controlled, single-use card number for increased control.\n\n{{As of|2016|7}}, American Express offered several business, corporate and travel credit and charge cards and services and data and information services related to their use in the competitive markets for these cards.<ref name=DeLuna>[http://www.businesstravelnews.com/Payment-Expense/Amex-Cuts-CEOs-Pay Amex Cuts CEO Pay] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160910182357/http://www.businesstravelnews.com/Payment-Expense/Amex-Cuts-CEOs-Pay |date=September 10, 2016 }} DeLuna, JoAnn, Business Travel News. March 28, 2016. Retrieved July 13, 2016.</ref>\n\nThe online \"American Express @ Work\" function gives corporations a site on which to apply for, cancel or suspend cards, monitor policy compliance and track expenses. The cardholder company can create and generate reports for a corporate expense account program, including analytics and data consolidation or integration.<ref name=Kerr>\nKerr,\n Tom. [http://www.comparecards.com/blog/business-benefits-of-amex-corporate-cards/ Business Benefits of Amex Corporate Cards] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815220128/http://www.comparecards.com/blog/business-benefits-of-amex-corporate-cards/ |date=August 15, 2016 }} [[LendingTree|Compare Wallet]], July 26, 2017, Retrieved February 4, 2018.  ''This content is not provided by American Express. Any opinions, analyses, reviews or recommendations expressed in this article are those of the author's alone, and have not been reviewed, approved or otherwise endorsed by American Express.''\n</ref> Reports can be tailored for various sized companies. Through a Standard Expense Reporting feature in its \"Manage Your Card Account site\", American Express corporate cards provide cardholders access to pre-populated expense reports. The cardholder needs to annotate expenses and add out-of-pocket charges upon completion of which the report can be downloaded in electronic or paper format.<ref name=Kerr/>\n\nAmerican Express Corporate Card program can be used with a third-party on-demand expense management tool by Concur, a provider of integrated travel and expense management services.  This tool simplifies the creation of expense account reports and the corporate approval process. Corporate card activity, including viewing statements, making payments, setting up alerts and making inquiries and disputing charges, can be managed through an account online or via mobile device through this service.<ref name=Kerr/>\n\nThe corporate cards have benefits including discounts and rebates for travel and transportation, travel and emergency help, travel insurance and baggage protection.<ref name=Kerr/> Upgrades from the Corporate \"Green\" Card to the Corporate Gold Card or Corporate Platinum Card, although subject to fees and terms and conditions, have several additional benefits at each card level, such as free breakfast or late checkout at many hotels.<ref name=Kerr/> The American Express/Business Extra Corporate Credit Card is affiliated with American Airlines and provides a 4% rebate on eligible American Airlines travel purchased with the card.<ref name=Kerr/>\n\nAmerican Express has a specialized corporate meeting credit card.<ref>[https://business.americanexpress.com/us/corporate-cards/corporate-meeting-card American Express Corporate Meeting Card information] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160620025159/https://business.americanexpress.com/us/corporate-cards/corporate-meeting-card |date=June 20, 2016 }} Retrieved July 13, 2016.</ref> Another specialized American Express business card is the American Express Corporate Purchasing Card, which can be assigned to individual employees or departments. Reconciliation and accounting services are available to make these functions easier for the corporation.<ref>[https://business.americanexpress.com/us/corporate-cards/p-card American Express Corporate Purchasing Card information] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160914123814/https://business.americanexpress.com/us/corporate-cards/p-card |date=September 14, 2016 }} Retrieved July 13, 2016.</ref>\n\n===Non-proprietary cards===\nIn December 2000, American Express agreed to acquire the US$226{{nbsp}}million credit card portfolio of [[Bank of Hawaii]], then a division of [[Pacific Century Financial Corporation|Pacific Century Financial Corp.]]<ref name=\"American-Express-Jan-2001-8-K\">{{cite web |url=http://edgar.secdatabase.com/2655/496201500004/filing-main.htm |title=American Express, Form 8-K, Current Report, Filing Date Jan 22, 2001 |publisher=Securities and Exchange Commission |accessdate=Jan 6, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512082051/http://edgar.secdatabase.com/2655/496201500004/filing-main.htm |archive-date=May 12, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> In January 2006, American Express sold its Bank of Hawaii card portfolio to [[Bank of America]] ([[MBNA]]). Bank of America will issue [[Visa Inc.|Visa]] and American Express cards under the Bank of Hawaii name.\n\nUntil 2004, Visa and [[Mastercard]] rules prohibited issuers of their cards from issuing American Express cards in the United States. This meant, as a practical matter, that U.S. banks could not issue American Express cards. These rules were struck-down as a result of antitrust litigation brought by the [[United States Department of Justice|U.S. Department of Justice]], and are no longer in effect.<ref name=\"American-Express-Mar-2004-10-K\">{{cite web |url=http://edgar.secdatabase.com/1342/95011704000966/filing-main.htm |title=American Express, Form 10-K, Annual Report, Filing Date Mar 12, 2004 |publisher=Securities and Exchange Commission |accessdate=Jan 6, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512060014/http://edgar.secdatabase.com/1342/95011704000966/filing-main.htm |archive-date=May 12, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> In January 2004, American Express reached a deal to have its cards issued by a U.S. bank, [[MBNA]] America.<ref name=\"American-Express-Feb-2004-8-K\">{{cite web |url=http://edgar.secdatabase.com/1529/496204000044/filing-main.htm |title=American Express, Form 8-K, Current Report, Filing Date Feb 2, 2004 |publisher=Securities and Exchange Commission |accessdate=January 6, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512044824/http://edgar.secdatabase.com/1529/496204000044/filing-main.htm |archive-date=May 12, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Initially decried by Mastercard executives as nothing but an \"experiment\", these cards were released in October 2004.<ref name=\"American-Express-Jan-2005-8-K\">{{cite web |url=http://edgar.secdatabase.com/2830/496205000012/filing-main.htm |title=American Express, Form 8-K, Current Report, Filing Date Jan 24, 2005 |publisher=Securities and Exchange Commission |accessdate=Jan 6, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512061705/http://edgar.secdatabase.com/2830/496205000012/filing-main.htm |archive-date=May 12, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Some said that the relationship was going to be threatened by MBNA's merger with Bank of America, a major Visa issuer and original developer of Visa (and its predecessor, BankAmericard). However, an agreement was reached between American Express and Bank of America on December 21, 2005.<ref name=\"American-Express-Dec-2005-8-K\">{{cite web |url=http://edgar.secdatabase.com/39/496205000220/filing-main.htm |title=American Express, Form 8-K, Current Report, Filing Date Dec 23, 2005 |publisher=Securities and Exchange Commission |accessdate=Jan 6, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512054046/http://edgar.secdatabase.com/39/496205000220/filing-main.htm |archive-date=May 12, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Under the terms of the agreement, Bank of America will own the customer loans and American Express will process the transactions. Also, American Express will dismiss Bank of America from its antitrust litigation against Visa, Mastercard, and a number of U.S. banks. Finally, both Bank of America and American Express also said an existing card-issuing partnership between MBNA and American Express will continue after the Bank of America-MBNA merger. The first card from the partnership, the no-annual-fee Bank of America Rewards American Express card, was released on June 30, 2006.\n\nSince then, [[Citibank]], [[Wells Fargo]], [[First National Bank of Omaha]], [[USAA]], [[Synchrony Financial]], and [[US Bancorp]] have started issuing American Express cards. Citi issues the [[Macy's]] and [[Bloomingdale's]] American Express cards along with Citi-branded cards. Wells Fargo issues American Express cards under their own brand and for [[Dillard's]]. US Bancorp issues American Express-branded cards for US Bank along with Elan Card Services, a subsidiary that issues credit cards on behalf of small to midsize banks. Some [[credit unions]], including [[PenFed]], also issue American Express cards. [[JPMorgan Chase]] is the largest bank and the only [[Big Four (banking)#United States|Big Four bank]] in the US that does not partner with American Express. Instead, JPMorgan made the decision in 2013, to partner with Visa on the ChaseNet closed-loop network that is similar in terms of functionality to the American Express network.\n\n===Merchant account===\nMany [[retail]]ers do not accept American Express cards.<ref name=\"Digital journal\">{{Cite journal| url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/pr/1994577| title=Florida Merchant Services Provider Gets Full American Express Acquiring Program| journal=Digital Journal| accessdate=June 17, 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714192921/http://www.digitaljournal.com/pr/1994577| archive-date=July 14, 2014| url-status=live}}</ref>{{Specify |reason=how many? |date=October 2017}} American Express charges [[Merchant account|merchants]] significantly higher fees than other credit card providers.<ref name=\"The Motley Fool\">{{cite journal| title=Here's Why American Express Can Charge More Than Visa or MasterCard| url=http://www.fool.com/investing/general/2014/06/16/heres-why-american-express-can-charge-more-than-vi.aspx| first=Matthew| last=Frankel| date=June 16, 2014| journal=[[The Motley Fool]]| accessdate=February 4, 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171015202816/https://www.fool.com/investing/general/2014/06/16/heres-why-american-express-can-charge-more-than-vi.aspx| archive-date=October 15, 2017| url-status=live}}</ref>  In a court case [[Ohio v. American Express Co.]], merchants filed a [[class action]] lawsuit against American Express and claimed that charging high fees is a violation of the [[Sherman Antitrust Act]].<ref name=\"Law 360\">{{Cite journal| url=http://www.law360.com/articles/544885/no-market-power-needed-in-2nd-circ-vertical-restraint-cases| title=No Market Power Needed In 2nd Circ. Vertical Restraint Cases| journal=[[Law360]]| accessdate=June 5, 2014| url-access=subscription| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714164229/http://www.law360.com/articles/544885/no-market-power-needed-in-2nd-circ-vertical-restraint-cases| archive-date=July 14, 2014| url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Buffalo Law Journal\">{{cite news| url=http://www.bizjournals.com/buffalo/blog/buffalo-law-journal/2014/06/five-questions-with-john-godwin.html| title=Five questions with... John Godwin| publisher=Buffalo Law Journal| first=Michael| last=Petro| date=June 19, 2014| accessdate=February 4, 2018| url-access=subscription| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715044638/http://www.bizjournals.com/buffalo/blog/buffalo-law-journal/2014/06/five-questions-with-john-godwin.html| archive-date=July 15, 2014| url-status=live}}</ref> According to the lawsuit, accepting American Express cards costs merchants the most.<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/05/07/us-usa-antitrust-amex-idUSBREA460QI20140507| title=U.S. judge: Government's antitrust suit vs AmEx may proceed| date=May 7, 2014| first=Andrew| last=Longstreth| work=Reuters| accessdate=February 4, 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924200555/http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/05/07/us-usa-antitrust-amex-idUSBREA460QI20140507| archive-date=September 24, 2015| url-status=live}}</ref> In January 2017, the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals affirmed a lower court ruling that American Express could block merchants that accept its cards from steering customers to other cards, like those offered by Visa and Mastercard.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-american-express-antitrust/u-s-loses-bid-to-overturn-amex-antitrust-decision-idUSKBN14P2JE| title=U.S. loses bid to overturn AmEx antitrust decision| date=January 15, 2017| work=Reuters| first=Jonathan| last=Stempel| accessdate=February 4, 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020084400/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-american-express-antitrust/u-s-loses-bid-to-overturn-amex-antitrust-decision-idUSKBN14P2JE| archive-date=October 20, 2017| url-status=live}}</ref> In June 2018, the [[Supreme Court of the United States|U.S. Supreme Court]] affirmed the 2nd Circuit Court's ruling.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Ohio v. American Express Co. |vol=585 |opinion=16-1454 |court=[[Supreme Court of the United States|U.S.]] |date=June 25, 2018 |url=https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/17pdf/16-1454_5h26.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Non-card products==\n\n===Traveler's checks===\nAmerican Express is the largest provider of [[traveler's check]]s in the world.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/travelers-checks-still-thing-113000341.html |title=Are Traveler's Checks Still a Thing? |last=Szczypinski |first=Sarah |work=Yahoo! Finance |date=August 25, 2016 |accessdate=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507090227/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/travelers-checks-still-thing-113000341.html |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, American Express released the American Express Travelers Check Card, a [[stored-value card]] that serves the same purposes as a traveler's check, but can be used in stores like a credit card. AmEx discontinued the card in October 2007, due to \"changing market conditions\" and issued refund checks to cardholders for the remaining balances.\n\n===Shearson/American Express===\n{{see also|Shearson/American Express}}\n[[File:Shearson AmEx Logo.png|320px|Shearson/American Express logo c. 1982|thumb|right]]\n\nDuring the 1980s, American Express began purchasing [[brokerage firm|stock brokerage]] firms as part of an expansion. In mid-1981, it purchased [[Sanford I. Weill]]'s [[Shearson Loeb Rhoades]], the second largest securities firm in the United States to form Shearson/American Express. Shearson Loeb Rhoades, itself was the culmination of several mergers in the 1970s as Weill's [[Hayden, Stone & Co.]] merged with [[Shearson, Hammill & Co.]] in 1974, to form [[Shearson Hayden Stone]]. Shearson Hayden Stone then merged with [[Loeb, Rhoades, Hornblower & Co.]] (formerly [[Loeb, Rhoades & Co.]]) to form Shearson Loeb Rhoades in 1979. With capital totalling $250&nbsp;million at the time of its acquisition, Shearson Loeb Rhoades trailed only [[Merrill Lynch]] as the securities industry's largest [[brokerage firm]]. After its acquisition by American Express, the firm was renamed Shearson/American Express.\n\nIn 1984, Shearson/American Express purchased the 90-year-old [[Investors Diversified Services]], bringing with it a fleet of financial advisors and investment products. Also in 1984, American Express acquired the [[investment banking]] and trading firm, [[Lehman Brothers|Lehman Brothers Kuhn Loeb]], and added it to the Shearson family, creating Shearson Lehman/American Express. In 1988, the firm acquired [[E. F. Hutton & Co.]], forming [[Shearson Lehman Hutton]] until 1990, when the firm's name became Shearson Lehman Brothers. When Harvey Golub took the reins in 1993, he negotiated the sale of Shearson's retail brokerage and [[Investment management|asset management]] business to [[Primerica]] and in following year, spun off of the remaining investment banking and institutional businesses as [[Lehman Brothers|Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc]].\n\n===Financial advisors===\nOn September 30, 2005, American Express spun-off its American Express Financial Advisors unit, [[Ameriprise Financial]], to its shareholders.  On September 30, 2005, [[RSM McGladrey]] acquired American Express Tax & Business Services (TBS).<ref name=\"American-Express-Oct-2005-8-K\">{{cite web |url=http://edgar.secdatabase.com/31/496205000212/filing-main.htm |title=American Express, Form 8-K, Current Report, Filing Date Oct 24, 2005 |publisher=Securities and Exchange Commission |accessdate=Jan 6, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512063829/http://edgar.secdatabase.com/31/496205000212/filing-main.htm |archive-date=May 12, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===International bank===\nIn 2008, [[Standard Chartered Bank]] acquired American Express Bank Ltd, the international banking subsidiary of American Express for US$823{{nbsp}}million.<ref name=\"American-Express-Sep-2007-8-K\">{{cite web |url=http://edgar.secdatabase.com/2528/496207000043/filing-main.htm |title=American Express, Form 8-K, Current Report, Filing Date Sep 18, 2007 |publisher=Securities and Exchange Commission |accessdate=January 6, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512071516/http://edgar.secdatabase.com/2528/496207000043/filing-main.htm |archive-date=May 12, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2007/sep/18/9| title=Standard Chartered buys American Express Bank| work=[[The Guardian]]| location=London| first=Andrew| last=Clark| date=September 18, 2007| access-date=December 11, 2016| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316210222/https://www.theguardian.com/business/2007/sep/18/9| archive-date=March 16, 2017| url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Frequently Asked Questions on the Standard Chartered Bank acquisition of American Express Bank|url=http://cmax.americanexpress.com/Internet/PrivateBank/pdf/SCB_AEB_Client_FAQ.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131215195529/http://cmax.americanexpress.com/Internet/PrivateBank/pdf/SCB_AEB_Client_FAQ.pdf|archive-date=December 15, 2013|publisher=American Express|accessdate=January 11, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.sc.com/in/_documents/tools-utilities/ar_0607.pdf |title=Auditors' Report on the financial statements of Standard Chartered Bank \u2013 India Branches under Section 30 of the Banking Regulation Act, 1949, Page 7, Economic & Political Weekly EPW June 28, 2008 |publisher=Standard Chartered |accessdate=January 11, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131215223604/https://www.sc.com/in/_documents/tools-utilities/ar_0607.pdf |archive-date=December 15, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sc.com/vn/latest-news/03-08-completes-acquisition-of-american-express-bank/en/ |title=Standard Chartered completes acquisition of American Express Bank for $823 million |publisher=Standard Chartered Bank |date=March 3, 2008 |access-date=April 8, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170408082638/https://www.sc.com/vn/latest-news/03-08-completes-acquisition-of-american-express-bank/en/ |archive-date=April 8, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Travel===\n{{unreferenced section|date=September 2019}}\nAmerican Express established a Travel Division in 1915, that tied together all earlier efforts at making travel easier, and soon established its first [[travel agency|travel agencies]]. In the 1930s, the Travel Division had grown widely. [[Albert K. Dawson]] was instrumental in expanding business operations overseas, even investing in tourist relations with the [[Soviet Union]]. During [[World War I]], Dawson was a photographer and film correspondent with the German army.\n\nIn March 2014, American Express announced that it signed an agreement to create a joint venture for business travel and spun off its corporate travel business as [[American Express Global Business Travel]].\n\n===Publishing===\nThe American Express Publishing Corporation published the ''[[Travel + Leisure]],'' ''[[Food & Wine (magazine)|Food & Wine]],'' ''[[Executive Travel magazine|Executive Travel]]'', ''Black Ink'', and ''[[Departures Magazine|Departures]]'' magazines until October 1, 2013, when it sold those titles to [[Time Inc.]]<ref>{{cite news| title=Media It's Official: Time Inc. Buys AmEx's Food & Wine, Travel & Leisure Magazines| url=http://adage.com/article/media/time-buys-amex-s-food-wine-travel-leisure/244065/| work=[[Advertising Age]]| date=September 10, 2013| accessdate=February 4, 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131012104625/http://adage.com/article/media/time-buys-amex-s-food-wine-travel-leisure/244065/| archive-date=October 12, 2013| url-status=live}}</ref>  It publishes ''American Express Skyguide'' and is based in New York City.<ref name=\"American-Express-Feb-2012-10-K\">{{cite web |url=http://pdf.secdatabase.com/1125/0001193125-12-077400.pdf |title=American Express, Form 10-K, Annual Report, Filing Date Feb 24, 2012 |publisher=Securities and Exchange Commission |accessdate=Jan 6, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512063058/http://pdf.secdatabase.com/1125/0001193125-12-077400.pdf |archive-date=May 12, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{as of|2014|February|}}, [[Time Inc.]] is restructuring the portfolio of publications.<ref name=\"Time Inc. Lays Out Restructuring\">{{cite journal| url=http://www.wwd.com/media-news/fashion-memopad/time-inc-lays-out-restructuring-7407860?src=nl/mornReport/20140205| title=Time Inc. Lays Out Restructuring| journal=[[Women's Wear Daily]]| date=February 5, 2014| accessdate=February 4, 2014| last=Steigrad| first=Alexandra| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140215035949/http://www.wwd.com/media-news/fashion-memopad/time-inc-lays-out-restructuring-7407860?src=nl%2FmornReport%2F20140205| archive-date=February 15, 2014| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Individual banking===\n{{unreferenced section|date=September 2019}}\nAmerican Express FSB ([[federal savings bank]]) is a [[direct bank]] offering a standard [[savings account]] to individuals.  Checking account services are not provided.\n\n==Advertising campaigns==\n\n===Don't Leave Home Without Them===\nIn 1975, [[David Ogilvy (businessman)|David Ogilvy]] of [[Ogilvy & Mather]] developed the highly successful \"Don't Leave Home Without Them\" [[Advertising campaign|ad campaign]] for American Express Traveler's Cheques, featuring Oscar-award-winning actor [[Karl Malden]]. Malden served as the public face of American Express Travelers Cheques for 25 years. In the UK, the spokesman was the [[Celebrity|television personality]] [[Alan Whicker]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/2010/05/28/nike-bmw-amex-apple-cmo-network-best-advertising-taglines_slide_4.html |title=Best-Loved Advertising Taglines |last=Bruno |first=Ken |work=[[Forbes]] |date=May 29, 2010 |accessdate=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507090036/https://www.forbes.com/2010/05/28/nike-bmw-amex-apple-cmo-network-best-advertising-taglines_slide_4.html |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAfter Malden's departure, and as the card assumed importance over the traveler's cheques, American Express continued to use celebrities, such as [[Mel Blanc]] and ballerina [[Cynthia Gregory]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=American Express commercial featuring Mel Blanc|oclc=715152953}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://articles.latimes.com/1987-01-04/entertainment/ca-1757_1_dance-studio |title=Cynthia Gregory At 40: 'I Did It The Hard Way' |last=Perlmutter |first=Donna |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=January 4, 1987 |accessdate=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180420185049/http://articles.latimes.com/1987-01-04/entertainment/ca-1757_1_dance-studio |archive-date=April 20, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> A typical ad for the American Express Card began with a celebrity asking viewers: \"Do you know me?\" Although he/she gave hints to his/her identity, the star's name was never mentioned except as imprinted on an American Express Card, after which announcer [[Peter Thomas (television narrator)|Peter Thomas]] told viewers how to apply for it.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://archive.naplesnews.com/news/local/famed-voice-over-icon-peter-thomas-dies-at-91-022ad336-4bbf-5cbb-e053-0100007f64ba-377801571.html/ |title=Famed voice-over icon Peter Thomas dies at 91 |last=Schlichter |first=Jay |newspaper=Naples Daily News |date=May 2, 2016 |accessdate=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229012743/http://archive.naplesnews.com/news/local/famed-voice-over-icon-peter-thomas-dies-at-91-022ad336-4bbf-5cbb-e053-0100007f64ba-377801571.html |archive-date=December 29, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Each ad concluded with the celebrity reminding viewers: \"Don't Leave Home Without It.\" The \"Don't Leave Home Without It\" slogan was revived in 2005.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.atlasobscura.com/articles/how-advertising-invented-8-phrases-we-use-every-day |title=How Advertising Invented 8 Phrases We Use Every Day |last=Grundhauser |first=Eric |magazine=Atlas Obscura |date=October 2, 2015 |accessdate=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507085735/https://www.atlasobscura.com/articles/how-advertising-invented-8-phrases-we-use-every-day |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===The Adventures of Seinfeld & Superman===\n[[File:Seinfeld superman.jpg|thumb|200px|right|[[The Adventures of Seinfeld & Superman]]]]\nAmerican Express continues to use celebrities in their ads. Some notable examples include a late 1990s ad campaign with comedian [[Jerry Seinfeld]], including the two 2004 [[webisode]]s in a series entitled \"[[The Adventures of Seinfeld & Superman]]\".<ref name=NYT>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/03/30/business/media-business-advertising-seinfeld-superman-join-forces-again-spots-for.html? |title=Seinfeld and Superman join forces again in spots for American Express, this time on the Web. |last=Elliott |first=Stuart |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=30 March 2004 |accessdate=19 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===My life. My card. / Are You a Cardmember?===\nIn late 2004, American Express launched the \"My life. My card.\" brand campaign, and later the \"Are You a Cardmember?\" brand campaign in 2007, (both by Ogilvy & Mather), featuring famous American Express cardmembers talking about their lives.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.adweek.com/brand-marketing/ogilvy-changes-amex-tagline-88553/ |title=Ogilvy Changes AmEx Tagline |last=McMains |first=Andrew |magazine=Adweek |date=April 6, 2007 |accessdate=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507090307/http://www.adweek.com/brand-marketing/ogilvy-changes-amex-tagline-88553/ |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The ads have featured actors/actresses [[Kate Winslet]],<ref name=\"amex-adsoftheworld-04/2009\">{{cite web |url=https://www.adsoftheworld.com/campaign/american-express-ogilvy-04-2009 |title=American Express Campaign by Ogilvy - 04/2009 |publisher=Ads of the World |accessdate=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507085750/https://www.adsoftheworld.com/campaign/american-express-ogilvy-04-2009 |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Robert De Niro]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.splendad.com/ads/show/1109-American-Express-Robert-De-Niro.html |title=American Express - Robert De Niro |publisher=splendAd |accessdate=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507085532/http://www.splendad.com/ads/show/1109-American-Express-Robert-De-Niro.html |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Ken Watanabe]],<ref name=\"amex-adsoftheworld-04/2009\"/> and [[Tina Fey]];<ref>{{cite video|publisher=[[YouTube]]|title=Tina Fey American Express Commercial|date=July 1, 2010|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=I7m-iAX3POU|access-date=May 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323090253/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=I7m-iAX3POU|archive-date=March 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Duke University]] basketball coach [[Mike Krzyzewski]];<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.adforum.com/creative-work/ad/player/34474558/coach-k/american-express |title=American Express - \"Coach K\" |publisher=adforum |accessdate=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507085734/https://www.adforum.com/creative-work/ad/player/34474558/coach-k/american-express |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> fashion designers [[Collette Dinnigan]] and [[Diane von F\u00fcrstenberg]];<ref>{{cite video|publisher=[[YouTube]]|title=American Express Collette Dinnigan|date=October 28, 2008| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hG7OMCem_Lc}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.splendad.com/ads/show/1991-American-Express-Diane-von-Furstenberg.html |title=American Express - Diane von Furstenberg |publisher=splendAd |accessdate=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507085451/http://www.splendad.com/ads/show/1991-American-Express-Diane-von-Furstenberg.html |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> comedian and talk show hostess [[Ellen DeGeneres]];<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.splendad.com/ads/show/1120-American-Express-Ellens-Dance.html |title=American Express - Ellen's Dance |publisher=splendAd |accessdate=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507085720/http://www.splendad.com/ads/show/1120-American-Express-Ellens-Dance.html |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> golfer [[Tiger Woods]];<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.adforum.com/creative-work/ad/player/34474557/tiger-woods/american-express |title=American Express - \"Tiger Woods\" |publisher=adforum |accessdate=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507085422/https://www.adforum.com/creative-work/ad/player/34474557/tiger-woods/american-express |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> professional snowboarder [[Shaun White]];<ref>{{cite video|publisher=[[YouTube]]|title=Shaun White American Express Commercial|date=June 3, 2007| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yr4515xEEPM}}</ref> tennis pros [[Venus Williams]], [[Andy Roddick]], and [[Andre Agassi]];<ref>{{cite video|publisher=[[YouTube]]|title=Venus Williams (2004 American Express ad)|date=February 15, 2010| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RhhmCeF1kZw}}</ref><ref>{{cite video|publisher=[[YouTube]]|title=Roddick vs Pong|date=May 28, 2006|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7UfGpt-0ncc|access-date=May 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228010737/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7UfGpt-0ncc|archive-date=February 28, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"MembersProjectAd\">{{cite web |url=https://www.adforum.com/talent/42675-sheryl-crow/work/6698113 |title=American Express - \"The Members Project\" |publisher=adforum |accessdate=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507085313/https://www.adforum.com/talent/42675-sheryl-crow/work/6698113 |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> surfer [[Laird Hamilton]]<ref name=\"amex-adsoftheworld-04/2009\"/> Manchester United manager [[Jos\u00e9 Mourinho]];<ref>{{cite video|publisher=[[YouTube]]|title=American Express Card by Jos\u00e9 Mourinho|date=May 13, 2008| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2HtsaHFAbas}}</ref> film directors [[Martin Scorsese]],<ref>{{cite video|publisher=[[YouTube]]|title=Martin Scorsese American Express|date=September 23, 2007|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=45iZP6AWT3c|access-date=May 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180327013708/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=45iZP6AWT3c|archive-date=March 27, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Wes Anderson]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.splendad.com/ads/show/1500-American-Express-Wes-Anderson.html |title=American Express - Wes Anderson |publisher=splendAd |accessdate=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507085734/http://www.splendad.com/ads/show/1500-American-Express-Wes-Anderson.html |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[M. Night Shyamalan]];<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.splendad.com/ads/show/1111-American-Express-M-Night-Shyamalan.html |title=American Express - M. Night Shyamalan |publisher=splendAd |accessdate=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507085925/http://www.splendad.com/ads/show/1111-American-Express-M-Night-Shyamalan.html |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> singers [[Sheryl Crow]], [[Alicia Keys]] and [[Beyonc\u00e9]].<ref name=\"MembersProjectAd\"/><ref>{{cite video|publisher=[[YouTube]]|title=Beyonce's American express commercial|date=October 4, 2007|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xH0t4Fwx_o8|access-date=May 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419192232/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xH0t4Fwx_o8|archive-date=April 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Animals====\nIn 2007, a two-minute black-and-white ad, entitled \"Animals\" and starring [[Ellen DeGeneres]], won the [[Emmy Award]] for Outstanding Commercial.<ref>{{cite web| title=59th Emmy Awards Nominees and Winners: Outstanding Commercial - 2007| url=http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2007/outstanding-commercial| publisher=Academy of Television Arts & Sciences| accessdate=February 4, 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205190131/http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2007/outstanding-commercial| archive-date=February 5, 2018| url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| url=http://adage.com/article/creativity-news/american-express-animals-earns-emmy-outstanding-commercial/120503/| journal=Advertising Age| title=American Express \"Animals\" earns the Emmy for Outstanding Commercial| date=September 17, 2007| last=Diaz| first=Ann-Christine| accessdate=February 4, 2018| url-access=subscription| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205184437/http://adage.com/article/creativity-news/american-express-animals-earns-emmy-outstanding-commercial/120503/| archive-date=February 5, 2018| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===C F. Frost===\nMany American Express credit card ads feature a sample American Express Card with the name \"C. F. Frost\" on the front. This is not a fabricated name; Charles F. Frost was an advertising executive at Ogilvy & Mather.<ref>{{cite web |first=Cecil |last=Adams |url=http://www.straightdope.com/classics/a1_180.html |title=Who is C. F. Frost, whose name appears on sample American Express cards? |work=[[The Straight Dope]] |date=December 16, 1983 |accessdate=February 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080531010042/http://www.straightdope.com/classics/a1_180.html |archive-date=May 31, 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Cause marketing===\nAmerican Express was one of the earliest users of [[cause marketing]], to great success.<ref name=\"forbescause\">{{cite journal |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/davidhessekiel/2012/01/31/cause-marketing-leaders-of-the-pack/ |title=Cause Marketing Leaders of the Pack |journal=[[Forbes]] |date=January 31, 2012 |accessdate=August 18, 2013 |last=Hessekiel |first=David |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130818053749/http://www.forbes.com/sites/davidhessekiel/2012/01/31/cause-marketing-leaders-of-the-pack/ |archive-date=August 18, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> A 1983 promotion advertised that for each purchase made with an American Express Card, American Express would contribute one penny to the renovation of the [[Statue of Liberty]]. The campaign generated contributions of $1.7&nbsp;million to the Statue of Liberty restoration project. What would soon capture the attention of marketing departments of major corporations was that the promotion generated approximately a 28% increase in American Express card usage by consumers.\n\nIn May 2007, American Express launched an initiative called the Members Project.<ref>[http://www.membersproject.com \"Members Project from American Express\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090405122736/http://www.membersproject.com/ |date=April 5, 2009 }}. Facebook. Retrieved January 9, 2012.</ref><ref name=\"American Express Rewards\">{{cite web |author=Peetu |url=http://americanexpressrewards.net/ |title=American Express Rewards |publisher=American Express Rewards |accessdate=December 18, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111219120103/http://americanexpressrewards.net/ |archivedate=December 19, 2011}}</ref> Cardholders were invited to submit ideas for projects, and were told American Express was funding the winning project.\n\n==Cultural projects==\n\nAmerican Express supports initiatives to enhance the architectural and cultural heritage, with the aim of raising awareness on the importance of historical and environmental conservation, through the restoration of historical monuments. American Express is a founder sponsor of the global program \"World Monuments Watch\",  launched in 1995, by [[World Monuments Fund]]. During the first edition of [[Corporate Art Awards]], in 2016, American Express received by [[pptArt]] the Corporate Art Award for its international restoration program.<ref>{{cite web| title=Winner of the 2016 edition of the Corporate Art Awards| url=https://www.pptart.net/winners| access-date=March 1, 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180213080154/https://www.pptart.net/winners| archive-date=February 13, 2018| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Workplace==\n\n===Offices===\n[[File:American Express Tower 9-11.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Two [[Rescue and recovery effort after the September 11 attacks|rescue workers]] entering the American Express Tower following [[September 11 attacks|September 11]] terrorist attack on [[World Trade Center (1973-2001)|World Trade Center]].]]\n[[File:Amex House, Edward Street, Brighton (from southeast).jpg|thumb|150px|[[Amex House]] in [[Brighton]], England, was built in 1977.]]\n[[File:AmEx Rome 2.jpg|thumb|150px|American Express [[Italy]] HQ in Rome]]\n[[File:AmExSouthFlorida.jpg|thumb|An American Express regional HQ in Sunrise, Florida.]]\nIn April 1986, American Express moved its headquarters to the 51-story [[Three World Financial Center]] in New York City. After [[September 11 attacks|the events of September 11, 2001]], American Express had to leave its headquarters temporarily because it was located directly opposite the [[World Trade Center (1973-2001)|World Trade Center]] and was damaged during the fall of the towers. The company began gradually moving back into its rehabilitated building in 2002.\n\nThe company maintains major offices in [[Sunrise, Florida]], [[Salt Lake City]], and [[Phoenix, Arizona]], with its main [[data center]]s in [[North Carolina]] and Phoenix.\n\nAMEX Bank of Canada was founded in 1853, in Toronto. It currently{{when|date=August 2019}} has 3,000 employees in its head office at Sheppard, east of Highway 404 in [[Toronto]] (relocated from [[Markham, Ontario]], a northern suburb of Toronto where it resided from 1985 to 2015), as well as an office in [[Hamilton, Ontario]]. The company began operations as a bank on July 1, 1990, following an [[order-in-council]] made by the [[Brian Mulroney]] government on November 21, 1988. This decision was not without controversy as federal banking policy at the time would not ordinarily have permitted American Express to operate as a bank.<ref>{{cite journal| last=Newman| first=Peter C.| date=July 30, 1990| title=The brash new kid on the block| journal=[[Maclean's]]| volume=103| number=31| page=33}}</ref>  It is a member of the [[Canadian Bankers Association]] (CBA) and a registered member of the [[Canada Deposit Insurance Corporation]] (CDIC), the federal agency insuring deposits at all of Canada's chartered banks.\n\nAmerican Express has several offices in the UK, including a European Service Center in the [[Carlton Hill, Brighton|Carlton Hill]] area of [[Brighton]], England. The building was completed in 2012. It replaced American Express's former building, Amex House, a large white tower block built in 1977 and surrounded by several other smaller offices around the city.<ref name=\"Collis9\">{{cite book| last=Collis| first=Rose| others=(based on the original by Tim Carder)| title=The New Encyclopaedia of Brighton| edition=1st| year=2010| publisher=Brighton & Hove Libraries| location=Brighton| isbn=978-0-9564664-0-2| page=9}}</ref>  The American Express European Service Center deals with card servicing, sales, fraud and merchant servicing. The official Europe, Middle East, and Africa HQ is located in the [[Belgravia]] district of Westminster, in [[central London]], at Belgrave House on Buckingham Palace Road, SW1; other UK offices are based in [[Sussex]] at [[Burgess Hill]]. In November 2009, [[Brighton and Hove]] City Council granted planning permission for American Express to redevelop the Amex House site.\n\nThe Japan, Asia-Pacific, and Australian Headquarters is co-located in Singapore, at [[Collyer Quay|16 Collyer Quay]], and in [[Sydney]]'s [[King Street Wharf]] area.\n\nThe headquarters of the Latin America and [[Caribbean]] division is in [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida]].\n\nAmerican Express also has a significant presence in India. Its two centres are located at [[Gurgaon]], [[Haryana]] and on Mathura Road in [[New Delhi]]. The Indian operations of American Express revolves around the [[back office]] customer services operations apart from the credit card business for the domestic Indian Economy, arguably the American Express campus in Gurgaon is the largest employee location by head count for Amex and supports business continuity objectives of Amex including during Hurricane Sandy, the center works 24/7 and includes a co-located second building which was recently{{when|date=September 2019}} transferred to a third party service provider but does much work for Amex.\n\n===Job satisfaction===\nIn 2008, American Express was named the 62nd best company to work for in the United States by ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'', ranking it number one for bank card companies.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/bestcompanies/2008/full_list/index.html| title=100 Best Companies to Work For| work=[[CNN Business|CNN Money]]| accessdate=October 9, 2008| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100723223729/http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/bestcompanies/2008/full_list/index.html| archive-date=July 23, 2010| url-status=live}}</ref> In October 2008, Amex Canada Inc. was named one of [[Greater Toronto's Top Employers]] by Mediacorp Canada Inc., which was announced by the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' newspaper.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.eluta.ca/top-employer-amex-canada| title=Reasons for Selection, 2009 Greater Toronto's Top Employers Competition| publisher=Eluta.ca| access-date=January 27, 2009| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091016192436/http://www.eluta.ca/top-employer-amex-canada| archive-date=October 16, 2009| url-status=live}}</ref> In 2018, ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' ranked it the 23rd best company to work for.<ref name=\"fortune100best\">{{Cite web |url=http://fortune.com/best-companies/american-express/ |title=Fortune Best Companies to Work For : American Express |access-date=May 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507085732/http://fortune.com/best-companies/american-express/ |archive-date=May 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2019, ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' ranked it the 9th best company to work for.<ref name=\"fortune100best\"/>\n\n==Management and corporate governance==\nThe officers of the company are listed on the company's website as follows:<ref name=officersanddirectors>{{Cite web |url=http://ir.americanexpress.com/Officers-and-Directors |title=American Express: Officers & Directors |access-date=April 16, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416074126/http://ir.americanexpress.com/Officers-and-Directors |archive-date=April 16, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* Stephen J. Squeri: chairman and chief executive officer\n* Douglas E. Buckminster: group president, global consumer services\n* Jeffrey C. Campbell: executive vice president and [[chief financial officer]]\n* L. Kevin Cox: chief human resources officer\n* Paul D. Fabara: president, Global Services Group\n* Marc D. Gordon: executive vice president and chief information officer\n* Michael J. O'Neill: executive vice president, corporate affairs and communications\n* Denise Pickett: president, global risk, banking and compliance and chief risk officer\n* Elizabeth Rutledge: executive vice president and [[chief marketing officer]]\n* Laureen E. Seeger: executive vice president and [[general counsel]]\n* Anr\u00e9 Williams: group president, global merchant and network services\n\nThe members of the company's board of directors are listed on the company's website as follows:<ref name=officersanddirectors/>\n* Stephen J. Squeri: chairman and CEO of American Express Company\n* Charlene Barshefsky: senior international partner at WilmerHale\n* John J. Brennan: chairman emeritus and senior advisor of The Vanguard Group\n* Ursula Burns: chairman, VEON supervisory board\n* Peter Chernin: founder and CEO of The Chernin Group, LLC\n* Ralph de la Vega: chairman and founder of the De La Vega Group\n* Anne L. Lauvergeon: founder and CEO of A.L.P.\n* Michael O. Leavitt: founder, Leavitt Partners, LLC\n* Theodore J. Leonsis: chairman and CEO, Monumental Sports & Entertainment, LLC\n* Richard C. Levin: senior advisor and former CEO, Coursera\n* Samuel J. Palmisano: former chairman, president and CEO, IBM\n* Daniel L. Vasella: honorary chairman and former chairman and CEO, Novartis AG\n* Robert D. Walter: founder and former chairman and chief executive officer, Cardinal Health, Inc.\n* Ronald A. Williams: former chairman and CEO of Aetna, Inc.\n\n== Ownership ==\n{{as of|2017||}}, American Express shares are mainly held by institutional investors ([[Berkshire Hathaway]], [[Vanguard group]], [[BlackRock]], [[State Street Corporation]] and others.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.nasdaq.com/symbol/axp/ownership-summary| title=American Express Company Ownership Summary| publisher=[[NASDAQ]]| accessdate=April 30, 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316023518/https://www.nasdaq.com/symbol/axp/ownership-summary| archive-date=March 16, 2018| url-status=live}}</ref>)\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Banks}} \n* [[Falmer Stadium]] in [[East Sussex]], [[England]]\n* [[American Express Gold card dress of Lizzy Gardiner]]\n* [[Small Business Saturday]], a registered trademark of American Express\n* [[Damage waiver#Credit card coverage of damage waiver|Credit card coverage of rental car damage waiver]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|American Express}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.americanexpress.com/}}\n{{Finance links\n| name = American Express\n| symbol = AXP\n| sec_cik = AXP\n| yahoo = AXP\n| google = AXP\n}}\n\n{{American Express}}\n{{Credit cards}}\n{{Dow Jones Industrial Average companies}}\n{{Use American English|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:American Express| ]]\n[[Category:1850 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Banks based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Banks of the United States]]\n[[Category:Berkshire Hathaway]]\n[[Category:Butterfield Overland Mail]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Companies in the Dow Jones Industrial Average]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the New York Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Contactless smart cards]]\n[[Category:Credit card issuer associations]]\n[[Category:Credit cards]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 1850]]\n[[Category:Foreign exchange companies]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies based in New 