eoflife.org/col/details/species/id/373d6e007d913ef0e629bf0a6e4f1719\n| website=Catalogue of Life\n| accessdate=2018-04-22\n}}</ref>\n<ref name=gbif>\n{{Cite web| title=''Ochthera anatolikos''\n| url=https://www.gbif.org/species/5086280\n| website=GBIF\n| accessdate=2018-04-22\n}}</ref>\n<ref name=bugref>\n{{Cite web| title=''Ochthera anatolikos'' Species Information\n| url=https://bugguide.net/node/view/1124932\n| website=BugGuide.net\n| accessdate=2018-04-22\n}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q14010852}}\n\n[[Category:Ephydridae]]\n[[Category:Articles created by Qbugbot]]\n[[Category:Insects described in 1977]]\n\n{{Ephydroidea-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Shyamal", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ochthera_anatolikos"}
{"title_page": "Budyonny horse", "text_new": "<!-- Begin Infobox horse.  The text of the article should go AFTER this section.-->\n{{Infobox horse\n|name= Budyonny\n|image= two_year_old_budjonny_stallions_in_russia.jpg\n|image_caption= Young Budyonny stallions in Russia\n|features =\n|altname= Budenny<br>Budjonny<br>Budonny<br>Budennovsky\n|nickname=\n|country= Southern [[Russia]]\n|group1=\n|std1= }}\n<!-- End Infobox horse info. Article Begins Here -->\n\nThe '''Budyonny''' is a breed of [[horse]] from [[Russia]].  They were developed for use as a military horse following the [[Russian Revolution (1917)|Russian Revolution]] and are currently used as an all-purpose competition horse and for driving.\n\n==Breed Characteristics==\n\n===Conformation===\n\nBudonny stallions stand on average {{convert|165|cm|hand in|abbr=on}}, mares {{hands|16}}.<ref name=\"Troyka\">{{cite web | title=Troyka | url=http://www.horses.ru/budenny.htm | accessdate=2009-08-24 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228100213/http://horses.ru/budenny.htm | archivedate=2009-02-28 }}</ref> The coat is generally [[chestnut (coat)|chestnut]] with a golden sheen, although they may also be [[bay (horse)|bay]], [[gray (horse)|gray]] or [[black (horse)|black]].  They have a well-proportioned head with a straight profile, a long neck, pronounced withers, sloping shoulders, a wide, deep chest, a long, straight back, and a slightly sloping croup.    | publisher = Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n  | year = 1988\n  | isbn = 0-671-66068-3\n  | page = [https://archive.org/details/lish00maur/page/52 52]\n  | url-access = registration\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/lish00maur/page/52\n  }}</ref>  The modern horse has a strong build, good bone, and are quite similar to the [[Thoroughbred]].  Conformation problems include occasional offset cannon bones in the forelegs and overly straight hind legs.<ref name=\"Budenny\">{{cite web\n | title = Budenny\n | url = http://www.mypets.net.au/flex/budenny_horse/581/1\n | work =  My Pets\n | accessdate=December 28, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===Sub-categories===\n\nIn the beginning, \u201cMassive,\u201d \u201cEastern,\u201d and \u201cMiddle\u201d types of the breed were recognized.\n\n* The Massive type was large and somewhat rough.  They were sturdy, with a well-developed bone structure, and those with an oriental typiness were especially prized.  Their robust constitution made them specially suitable for herd keeping.  They were used mainly for carriage driving.\n* The Oriental type was lighter and more elegant.  Generally chestnut with a gold sheen or bay, they were more demanding in the feed and management conditions they required.\n* The Medium type was fairly large and well-muscled, but also rangy and athletic.  They were faster than the other two types, and looked more like the Thoroughbred type.<ref name=\"The Budenny\">{{cite web\n | title = The Budenny\n | url = http://www.equiworld.net/horses/horsecare/Breeds/budenny/index.htm | work =  Equiworld\n | accessdate=2011-01-04 }}</ref>\n\nLater, demand for competition horses led to the creation of a single type with a larger proportion of Thoroughbred blood.  This breed is of interest because it is the result of the complex state-sponsored cross-breeding programs that were implemented after the Russian Revolution and are still in place today.  The Budyonny is bred today in the [[Ukraine]] and in the Kazakh and Kirghiz republics in the southern part of the former [[USSR]].<ref name=\"Budenny\"/>\n\n==History==\n\nThe Budyonny was named after Marshall [[Semyon Budyonny]], a [[Bolshevik]] cavalry commander who became famous during the Russian Revolution.  The breed was created by Budyonny, a well-known horse breeder himself, in the early 1920s in the [[Rostov-on-Don|Rostov]] region of Russia with the intent of producing cavalry horses to replace those lost during and after [[World War I]].  The resulting horses were used in Russian cavalry divisions during World War II and after.\n\nBudyonnys were bred from a cross of local [[Russian Don|Don]] and Chernomor mares and Thoroughbred stallions.  The Chernomor (also known as the Tchernomor or the Cherkassky) is a type of Cossack horse similar to the Don, although smaller.  They are descendants of the horses raised by [[Zaporozhian Cossacks]], and were first bred around Krasnodar, north of the [[Caucasus Mountains]].  During the first round of breeding for the Budyonny horse, blood from Kirghiz and Kazakh horses was also used, but the progeny was found to be not as hardy or conformationally sound, and later the Budyonny was used to improve these two breeds.\n\nThe first Budyonny horses were known as Anglo-Dons, and the best were inter-bred, with the foundation stock for the Budyonny selected from their offspring.  The foundation stock consisted of 657 mares of Anglo-Don, Anglo-Chernomor, and Anglo-Don/Chernomor crosses.  These mares were crossed with Anglo-Don and Thoroughbred stallions.  The broodmares were given the best of care with feed and management.  The young stock, when between two and four years old, were tested for performance on the racecourse and in cavalry equitation courses.  In 1949 the breed was officially recognized.<ref name=\"Budenny\"/>\n\nIn the 1950s an experiment was performed to gauge the ability of the Budyonny breed to adapt to harsh conditions without human help.  A number of horses were turned loose on a large island in Manych Lake in the Rostov district.  The horses have since survived and thrived, proving that they are capable of living in the wild for extended periods without human assistance.<ref name=\"Budyonny\">{{cite web\n | title = Budyonny\n | url = http://www.ansi.okstate.edu/breeds/horses/budyonny/\n | work =  Oklahoma State University\n | accessdate=December 28, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Uses==\nThe Budyonny is used as an all-round competition horse, competing in dressage, steeplechasing, three-day eventing, and endurance.  The breed is fast, agile, and enduring, which allows them to be used for many different events.<ref name=\"Budenny\"/>  They are also used as light carriage horses.<ref name=\"Budyonny\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Budyonny}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060215040724/http://www.equiworld.org/breeds/budenny/index.htm Equiworld]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071023021327/http://imh.org/museum/breeds.php?pageid=8&breed=18&alpha=One International Museum of the Horse - Budenny]\n\n{{Horse breeds of the Russian Federation}}\n{{Equine|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Budyonny (Horse)}}\n[[Category:Horse breeds]]\n[[Category:Horse breeds originating in Russia]]\n[[Category:Animal breeds originating in the Soviet Union]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Begin Infobox horse.  The text of the article should go AFTER this section.-->\n{{Infobox horse\n|name= Budyonny\n|image= two_year_old_budjonny_stallions_in_russia.jpg\n|image_caption= Young Budyonny stallions in Russia\n|features =\n|altname= Budenny<br>Budjonny<br>Budonny<br>Budennovsky\n|nickname=\n|country= Southern [[Russia]]\n|group1=\n|std1= }}\n<!-- End Infobox horse info. Article Begins Here -->\n\nThe '''Budyonny''' is a breed of [[horse]] from [[Russia]].  They were developed for use as a military horse following the [[Russian Revolution (1917)|Russian Revolution]] and are currently used as an all-purpose competition horse and for driving.\n\n==Breed Characteristics==\n\n===Conformation===\n\nBudonny stallions stand on average {{convert|165|cm|hand in|abbr=on}}, mares {{hands|16}}.<ref name=\"Troyka\">{{cite web | title=Troyka | url=http://www.horses.ru/budenny.htm | accessdate=2009-08-24 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228100213/http://horses.ru/budenny.htm | archivedate=2009-02-28 }}</ref> The coat is generally [[chestnut (coat)|chestnut]] with a golden sheen, although they may also be [[bay (horse)|bay]], [[gray (horse)|gray]] or [[black (horse)|black]].  They have a well-proportioned head with a straight profile, a long neck, pronounced withers, sloping shoulders, a wide, deep chest, a long, straight back, and a slightly sloping croup.  Their legs are long and strong with good joints and well-formed hooves.<ref name=\"Bongianni\">{{cite book\n  | last = Bongianni\n  | first = Maurizio\n  | title = Simon & Schuster's Guide to Horses and Ponies\n  | publisher = Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n  | year = 1988\n  | isbn = 0-671-66068-3\n  | page = [https://archive.org/details/lish00maur/page/52 52]\n  | url-access = registration\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/lish00maur/page/52\n  }}</ref>  The modern horse has a strong build, good bone, and are quite similar to the [[Thoroughbred]].  Conformation problems include occasional offset cannon bones in the forelegs and overly straight hind legs.<ref name=\"Budenny\">{{cite web\n | title = Budenny\n | url = http://www.mypets.net.au/flex/budenny_horse/581/1\n | work =  My Pets\n | accessdate=December 28, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===Sub-categories===\n\nIn the beginning, \u201cMassive,\u201d \u201cEastern,\u201d and \u201cMiddle\u201d types of the breed were recognized.\n\n* The Massive type was large and somewhat rough.  They were sturdy, with a well-developed bone structure, and those with an oriental typiness were especially prized.  Their robust constitution made them specially suitable for herd keeping.  They were used mainly for carriage driving.\n* The Oriental type was lighter and more elegant.  Generally chestnut with a gold sheen or bay, they were more demanding in the feed and management conditions they required.\n* The Medium type was fairly large and well-muscled, but also rangy and athletic.  They were faster than the other two types, and looked more like the Thoroughbred type.<ref name=\"The Budenny\">{{cite web\n | title = The Budenny\n | url = http://www.equiworld.net/horses/horsecare/Breeds/budenny/index.htm | work =  Equiworld\n | accessdate=2011-01-04 }}</ref>\n\nLater, demand for competition horses led to the creation of a single type with a larger proportion of Thoroughbred blood.  This breed is of interest because it is the result of the complex state-sponsored cross-breeding programs that were implemented after the Russian Revolution and are still in place today.  The Budyonny is bred today in the [[Ukraine]] and in the Kazakh and Kirghiz republics in the southern part of the former [[USSR]].<ref name=\"Budenny\"/>\n\n==History==\n\nThe Budyonny was named after Marshall [[Semyon Budyonny]], a [[Bolshevik]] cavalry commander who became famous during the Russian Revolution.  The breed was created by Budyonny, a well-known horse breeder himself, in the early 1920s in the [[Rostov-on-Don|Rostov]] region of Russia with the intent of producing cavalry horses to replace those lost during and after [[World War I]].  The resulting horses were used in Russian cavalry divisions during World War II and after.\n\nBudyonnys were bred from a cross of local [[Russian Don|Don]] and Chernomor mares and Thoroughbred stallions.  The Chernomor (also known as the Tchernomor or the Cherkassky) is a type of Cossack horse similar to the Don, although smaller.  They are descendants of the horses raised by [[Zaporozhian Cossacks]], and were first bred around Krasnodar, north of the [[Caucasus Mountains]].  During the first round of breeding for the Budyonny horse, blood from Kirghiz and Kazakh horses was also used, but the progeny was found to be not as hardy or conformationally sound, and later the Budyonny was used to improve these two breeds.\n\nThe first Budyonny horses were known as Anglo-Dons, and the best were inter-bred, with the foundation stock for the Budyonny selected from their offspring.  The foundation stock consisted of 657 mares of Anglo-Don, Anglo-Chernomor, and Anglo-Don/Chernomor crosses.  These mares were crossed with Anglo-Don and Thoroughbred stallions.  The broodmares were given the best of care with feed and management.  The young stock, when between two and four years old, were tested for performance on the racecourse and in cavalry equitation courses.  In 1949 the breed was officially recognized.<ref name=\"Budenny\"/>\n\nIn the 1950s an experiment was performed to gauge the ability of the Budyonny breed to adapt to harsh conditions without human help.  A number of horses were turned loose on a large island in Manych Lake in the Rostov district.  The horses have since survived and thrived, proving that they are capable of living in the wild for extended periods without human assistance.<ref name=\"Budyonny\">{{cite web\n | title = Budyonny\n | url = http://www.ansi.okstate.edu/breeds/horses/budyonny/\n | work =  Oklahoma State University\n | accessdate=December 28, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Uses==\nThe Budyonny is used as an all-round competition horse, competing in dressage, steeplechasing, three-day eventing, and endurance.  The breed is fast, agile, and enduring, which allows them to be used for many different events.<ref name=\"Budenny\"/>  They are also used as light carriage horses.<ref name=\"Budyonny\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Budyonny}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060215040724/http://www.equiworld.org/breeds/budenny/index.htm Equiworld]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071023021327/http://imh.org/museum/breeds.php?pageid=8&breed=18&alpha=One International Museum of the Horse - Budenny]\n\n{{Horse breeds of the Russian Federation}}\n{{Equine|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Budyonny (Horse)}}\n[[Category:Horse breeds]]\n[[Category:Horse breeds originating in Russia]]\n[[Category:Animal breeds originating in the Soviet Union]]\n", "name_user": "216.74.200.226", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eConformation)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Budyonny_horse"}
{"title_page": "Panic Movement (album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Panic Movement\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[The Hiss]]\n| cover      = Panicmovement.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date and age|2003|08|11}}\n| recorded   = {{Start date and age|2002|02}}\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Garage rock]]\n| length     =\n| label      = Loog Records, Sanctuary Records\n| producer   = [[Owen Morris]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = Chocolate Hearts\n| next_year  = 2007\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating| 3|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/r652463 |title=Panic Movement &#91;Loog&#93; - The Hiss &#124; AllMusic |first=Heather |last=Phares |work=allmusic.com |year=2011 |accessdate=8 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n'''''Panic Movement''''' is the first release by [[Indie (music)|indie]]/[[garage rock]] band [[The Hiss]]. It was released in August 2003 on Loog records and is distributed throughout America by Sanctuary Records. The song \"Back On the Radio\" was featured in Tony Hawk's Underground 2, and the first single \"Triumph\" entered the UK top 20. Some enhanced copies on the Sanctuary Records release have 2 bonus videos.\n\n== Track listing ==\n#\"Clever Kicks\" 2:23\n#\"Triumph\" 4:08\n#\"Listen to Me\" 4:15\n#\"Back on the Radio\" 4:12\n#\"Not for Hire\" 5:10\n#\"Riverbed\" 2:29\n#\"Ghost's Gold\" 6:27\n#\"Lord's Prayer\" 2:42\n#\"Hard to Lose\" 4:03\n#\"Step Aside\" 3:49\n#\"Brass Tacks\" 3:11\n#\"City People\" 3:03\n\n==Misc.==\nOn the video for '''Back on the Radio''' (found on the enhanced copies) it reads: \"Loog Records Presents: The Hiss in '''Shame the Devil'''\". Even though it says Loog Records, the CD case has Sanctuary Records printed on the back.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r652463|pure_url=yes}} Panic Movement at AMG]\n\n[[Category:2003 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Owen Morris]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Panic Movement\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[The Hiss]]\n| cover      = Panicmovement.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date and age|2003|08|11}}\n| recorded   = {{Start date and age|2002|02}}\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Garage rock]]\n| length     =\n| label      = Loog Records, Sanctuary Records\n| producer   = [[Owen Morris]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = Chocolate Hearts\n| next_year  = 2007\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating| 3|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/r652463 |title=Panic Movement &#91;Loog&#93; - The Hiss &#124; AllMusic |first=Heather |last=Phares |work=allmusic.com |year=2011 |accessdate=8 August 2011}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Larkin|first=Colin|authorlink=Colin Larkin|title=Encyclopedia of Popular Music|year=2007|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|edition=4th|isbn=978-0195313734|title-link=Encyclopedia of Popular Music}}</ref>\n\n'''''Panic Movement''''' is the first release by [[Indie (music)|indie]]/[[garage rock]] band [[The Hiss]]. It was released in August 2003 on Loog records and is distributed throughout America by Sanctuary Records. The song \"Back On the Radio\" was featured in Tony Hawk's Underground 2, and the first single \"Triumph\" entered the UK top 20. Some enhanced copies on the Sanctuary Records release have 2 bonus videos.\n\n== Track listing ==\n#\"Clever Kicks\" 2:23\n#\"Triumph\" 4:08\n#\"Listen to Me\" 4:15\n#\"Back on the Radio\" 4:12\n#\"Not for Hire\" 5:10\n#\"Riverbed\" 2:29\n#\"Ghost's Gold\" 6:27\n#\"Lord's Prayer\" 2:42\n#\"Hard to Lose\" 4:03\n#\"Step Aside\" 3:49\n#\"Brass Tacks\" 3:11\n#\"City People\" 3:03\n\n==Misc.==\nOn the video for '''Back on the Radio''' (found on the enhanced copies) it reads: \"Loog Records Presents: The Hiss in '''Shame the Devil'''\". Even though it says Loog Records, the CD case has Sanctuary Records printed on the back.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r652463|pure_url=yes}} Panic Movement at AMG]\n\n[[Category:2003 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Owen Morris]]\n", "name_user": "Muso805", "label": "safe", "comment": "further correction to fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Panic_Movement_(album)"}
{"title_page": "Puliyankulam", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name = Puliyankulam\n| native_name = \n| settlement_type = [[Town]]\n| pushpin_map = Sri Lanka Northern Province\n| subdivision_type = [[List of countries|Country]]\n| subdivision_name = [[Sri Lanka]]\n| subdivision_type2 = [[Provinces of Sri Lanka|Province]]\n| subdivision_name2 = [[Northern Province, Sri Lanka|Northern]]\n| subdivision_type3 = [[Districts of Sri Lanka|District]]\n| subdivision_name3 = [[Vavuniya District|Vavuniya]] \n| subdivision_type4 = [[Divisional Secretariats of Sri Lanka|DS Division]]\n| subdivision_name4 = Vavuniya North \n| coordinates = {{coord|8|57|0|N|80|31|0|E|region:LK|display=inline}}\n}}\n\n'''Puliyankulam''' is a town in [[Vavuniya District]], [[Sri Lanka]]. A road going through this town connects [[Mankulam (Sri Lanka)|Mankulam]] to [[Vavuniya]]. Another road going through Puliyankulam connects [[Nedunkeni]], [[Oddusuddan]] and [[Mullaitivu]] to [[Vavuniya]].\n\n==See also peoples who lived: Purchi@Veernathevar,paitdipillaithevar, ayya,nallukongar==\n*[[Thandikulam\u2013Omanthai offensive]]\n*[[Operation Jayasikurui]]\n\n{{coord|8|57|N|80|31|E|region:LK_type:city|display=title}}\n\n\n\n{{NorthernLK-geo-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Vavuniya North DS Division]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name = Puliyankulam\n| native_name = \n| settlement_type = [[Town]]\n| pushpin_map = Sri Lanka Northern Province\n| subdivision_type = [[List of countries|Country]]\n| subdivision_name = [[Sri Lanka]]\n| subdivision_type2 = [[Provinces of Sri Lanka|Province]]\n| subdivision_name2 = [[Northern Province, Sri Lanka|Northern]]\n| subdivision_type3 = [[Districts of Sri Lanka|District]]\n| subdivision_name3 = [[Vavuniya District|Vavuniya]] \n| subdivision_type4 = [[Divisional Secretariats of Sri Lanka|DS Division]]\n| subdivision_name4 = Vavuniya North \n| coordinates = {{coord|8|57|0|N|80|31|0|E|region:LK|display=inline}}\n}}\n\n'''Puliyankulam''' is a town in [[Vavuniya District]], [[Sri Lanka]]. A road going through this town connects [[Mankulam (Sri Lanka)|Mankulam]] to [[Vavuniya]]. Another road going through Puliyankulam connects [[Nedunkeni]], [[Oddusuddan]] and [[Mullaitivu]] to [[Vavuniya]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Thandikulam\u2013Omanthai offensive]]\n*[[Operation Jayasikurui]]\n\n{{coord|8|57|N|80|31|E|region:LK_type:city|display=title}}\n\n\n\n{{NorthernLK-geo-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Vavuniya North DS Division]]\n", "name_user": "Velladurai T", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Puliyankulam"}
{"title_page": "Gaga (dance vocabulary)", "text_new": "'''Gaga''' is a movement language and pedagogy developed by [[Batsheva Dance Company]] director and teacher [[Ohad Naharin]]. Used in some Israeli contemporary dance<ref name=\"spine\">[https://fr.scribd.com/document/324808946/building-bodies-with-a-soft-spine-gaga], Retrieved December 15, 2015.</ref> Gaga has two educational tracks which are taught in Israel as well as several other countries: Gaga/Dancers is intended for trained dancers and comprises the daily training of the Batsheva Dance Company; Gaga/People is designed for the general public and requires no dance training.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://batsheva.co.il/en/gaga|title=Batsheva Dance Company: Gaga|access-date=2017-03-18}}</ref>  Many dancers have stated that after taking Gaga classes, their passion for dance has been re-ignited; they have found new ways to connect to their inner beast without being self-conscious about how the movement looks while at the same time discovering how to listen to their bodies/self.<ref name=\"spine\" />\n\nGaga students improvise their movements based on [[somatic experiencing|somatic experience]] and imagery described by the teacher, which provides a framework that promotes unconventional movement.<ref name=\"ohadyoutube\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OGPG1QL1vJc&list=PLNc5MrHJi6tzihfXf dE_uWz1hH1ZMkZlj \"Ohad Naharin Discusses Gaga Movement\"], Retrieved December 15, 2015.</ref> The imagery is intended to guide the performer's movement  expressivity by focusing attention on specific body regions. For example, \"Luna\", \"Lena\", \"Biba\", \"Tama\" and many more words are used to experiment in a performers body while dancing.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Galili|first1=Deborah|title=Gaga for Dancers: From the Gaga Intensive to New Open Classes|url=https://www.danceinisrael.com/2009/08/gaga-for-dancers-from-the-gaga-intensive-to-new-open-classes/|website=Dance in Israel|accessdate=October 30, 2017}}</ref> Mirrors are avoided in Gaga training to facilitate movement guided by sensing and imagining rather than sight. <ref name=\"spine\" />\n\n==About==\nThe Gaga movement language was created by [[Ohad Naharin]], former Martha Graham dancer and artistic director of [[Batsheva Dance Company]] as of 1990. The movement language has developed over time in relation to Naharin\u2019s research in dance and choreography. Naharin created Gaga as a reaction to a back injury he was experiencing. The language is intended to facilitate communication with the dancers and help them to take care of the body while testing their physical limitations.<ref>Martha Schabas, [https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/theatre-and-performance/choreographer-ohad-naharin-on-developing-the-dance-language-gaga/article33531396/ ''Choreographer Ohad Naharin on developing the dance language Gaga''] ''The Globe and Mail''</ref> The terminology within the language often emphasizes pleasure and freedom.<ref>Batsheva.co.il, [https://batsheva.co.il/en/gaga ''Gaga''] ''Batsheva Dance Company Website''</ref> The idea is that the mind can undergo many tasks and the body can still explore its power, so long as it adheres to pleasure. The movement can be uninhibited, as pleasure prevents injury.<ref>Batsheva.co.il, [https://batsheva.co.il/en/gaga ''Gaga''] ''Batsheva Dance Company Website''</ref> The language allows for the breaking of movement habits and the experience of effort and exaggeration, with an emphasis on sensation.<ref>Ohad Interview, [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bje66VbeJGM ''Interview''] ''Ohad Naharin on the Language of Gaga''</ref>\n\n==Methodology==\n\nA Gaga class is given as a procession of instructions that give access to bodily sensations. Each instruction is meant to help the dancer use mental approaches to create physical research. Because of the dependence of Gaga on the actual setting and people involved, there is no uniform class structure, though specific methodologies are employed. \n\n=== Float ===\nA floating sensation (referred to as 'float') is cultivated throughout. Float does not ignore the existence of gravity. However rather than giving into gravity and adhering to heaviness, the body uses gravity as a force of energy and even elevation of the limbs.<ref>KATAN-SCHMID, EINAV. EMBODIED PHILOSOPHY IN DANCE: Gaga and Ohad Naharin's Movement Research. PALGRAVE MACMILLAN, 2018.</ref> Naharin states, \u201cwe sense the weight of our body parts, yet, our form is not shaped by gravity.\u201d <ref>Gaga People, [http://gagapeople.com/english/about-gaga/ ''Gaga''] ''Gaga People website''</ref> Additionally, float is intended to facilitate a constant awareness and activeness in which dancers are never completely released, even when they are doing nothing, leaving them 'available' for movement.<ref>KATAN-SCHMID, EINAV. EMBODIED PHILOSOPHY IN DANCE: Gaga and Ohad Naharin's Movement Research. PALGRAVE MACMILLAN, 2018. Page 123.</ref>\n\n=== Vocabulary ===\nNaharin created Gaga terminology specific to bodily functions that activated throughout a dancer\u2019s Gaga practice. \u201cBiba\u201d means to pull the body away from the seat bones. It is meant to create more space and freedom in the lower spine. \u201cTashi\u201d means to move with feet glued to the floor. \u201cPika\u201d is the activation of the spot right beneath the pubic bone.<ref>KATAN-SCHMID, EINAV. EMBODIED PHILOSOPHY IN DANCE: Gaga and Ohad Naharin's Movement Research. PALGRAVE MACMILLAN, 2018.</ref> \n\n=== Focus on pleasure ===\nNaharin emphasizes the return to pleasure, especially within moments of exaggeration and bodily effort. His belief is that pleasure is always good for the body. Gaga often requests demanding actions, such as running and shaking, but the effort of \u201cburning muscles\u201d must be tied to pleasure in order to keep it healthy.<ref>KATAN-SCHMID, EINAV. EMBODIED PHILOSOPHY IN DANCE: Gaga and Ohad Naharin's Movement Research. PALGRAVE MACMILLAN, 2018.</ref> Gaga has been taught in centers for people affected by Parkinson\u2019s disease.<ref> [http://www.abcdance.eu/dance-with-parkinson-joining-science-and-art-through-beauty/ 'Dancing with Parkinson's '] </ref>\n\n=== Release of aesthetic ambitions ===\nThe Gaga language focuses on the internal sensations. Due to this, classes are run without mirrors. Naharin emphasizes the release of ambitions or inhibitions. He states \u201cwe might be silly, we can laugh at ourselves\u201d<ref>Gaga People, [http://gagapeople.com/english/about-gaga/ ''Gaga''] ''Gaga People website''</ref> This kind of instruction is an effort for exploratory research without limits or tensions. \n\n=== Connection to groove ===\nWith or without music, dancers are asked to connect to the musicality of their movement.<ref>KATAN-SCHMID, EINAV. EMBODIED PHILOSOPHY IN DANCE: Gaga and Ohad Naharin's Movement Research. PALGRAVE MACMILLAN, 2018. Page 156.</ref> Naharin emphasizes attention to [[Groove (music)|groove]], as groove is a universal experience regardless of technique levels.<ref>Gaga People, [http://gagapeople.com/english/about-gaga/ ''Gaga''] ''Gaga People website''</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Dance in Israel]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Dance in Israel]]\n[[Category:Israeli inventions]]\n\n\n{{dance-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Gaga''' is a movement language and pedagogy developed by [[Batsheva Dance Company]] director and teacher [[Ohad Naharin]]. Used in some Israeli contemporary dance<ref name=\"spine\">[https://www.academia.edu/6458350/Building_Bodies_with_a_Soft_Spine._Gaga_Ohad_Naharins_invention_in_practice_its_roots_in_Feldenkrais_and_the_vision_of_a_pedagogy \"Building Bodies with a Soft Spine\"], Retrieved December 15, 2015.</ref> Gaga has two educational tracks which are taught in Israel as well as several other countries: Gaga/Dancers is intended for trained dancers and comprises the daily training of the Batsheva Dance Company; Gaga/People is designed for the general public and requires no dance training.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://batsheva.co.il/en/gaga|title=Batsheva Dance Company: Gaga|access-date=2017-03-18}}</ref>  Many dancers have stated that after taking Gaga classes, their passion for dance has been re-ignited; they have found new ways to connect to their inner beast without being self-conscious about how the movement looks while at the same time discovering how to listen to their bodies/self.<ref name=\"spine\" />\n\nGaga students improvise their movements based on [[somatic experiencing|somatic experience]] and imagery described by the teacher, which provides a framework that promotes unconventional movement.<ref name=\"ohadyoutube\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OGPG1QL1vJc&list=PLNc5MrHJi6tzihfXf dE_uWz1hH1ZMkZlj \"Ohad Naharin Discusses Gaga Movement\"], Retrieved December 15, 2015.</ref> The imagery is intended to guide the performer's movement  expressivity by focusing attention on specific body regions. For example, \"Luna\", \"Lena\", \"Biba\", \"Tama\" and many more words are used to experiment in a performers body while dancing.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Galili|first1=Deborah|title=Gaga for Dancers: From the Gaga Intensive to New Open Classes|url=https://www.danceinisrael.com/2009/08/gaga-for-dancers-from-the-gaga-intensive-to-new-open-classes/|website=Dance in Israel|accessdate=October 30, 2017}}</ref> Mirrors are avoided in Gaga training to facilitate movement guided by sensing and imagining rather than sight. <ref name=\"spine\" />\n\n==About==\nThe Gaga movement language was created by [[Ohad Naharin]], former Martha Graham dancer and artistic director of [[Batsheva Dance Company]] as of 1990. The movement language has developed over time in relation to Naharin\u2019s research in dance and choreography. Naharin created Gaga as a reaction to a back injury he was experiencing. The language is intended to facilitate communication with the dancers and help them to take care of the body while testing their physical limitations.<ref>Martha Schabas, [https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/theatre-and-performance/choreographer-ohad-naharin-on-developing-the-dance-language-gaga/article33531396/ ''Choreographer Ohad Naharin on developing the dance language Gaga''] ''The Globe and Mail''</ref> The terminology within the language often emphasizes pleasure and freedom.<ref>Batsheva.co.il, [https://batsheva.co.il/en/gaga ''Gaga''] ''Batsheva Dance Company Website''</ref> The idea is that the mind can undergo many tasks and the body can still explore its power, so long as it adheres to pleasure. The movement can be uninhibited, as pleasure prevents injury.<ref>Batsheva.co.il, [https://batsheva.co.il/en/gaga ''Gaga''] ''Batsheva Dance Company Website''</ref> The language allows for the breaking of movement habits and the experience of effort and exaggeration, with an emphasis on sensation.<ref>Ohad Interview, [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bje66VbeJGM ''Interview''] ''Ohad Naharin on the Language of Gaga''</ref>\n\n==Methodology==\n\nA Gaga class is given as a procession of instructions that give access to bodily sensations. Each instruction is meant to help the dancer use mental approaches to create physical research. Because of the dependence of Gaga on the actual setting and people involved, there is no uniform class structure, though specific methodologies are employed. \n\n=== Float ===\nA floating sensation (referred to as 'float') is cultivated throughout. Float does not ignore the existence of gravity. However rather than giving into gravity and adhering to heaviness, the body uses gravity as a force of energy and even elevation of the limbs.<ref>KATAN-SCHMID, EINAV. EMBODIED PHILOSOPHY IN DANCE: Gaga and Ohad Naharin's Movement Research. PALGRAVE MACMILLAN, 2018.</ref> Naharin states, \u201cwe sense the weight of our body parts, yet, our form is not shaped by gravity.\u201d <ref>Gaga People, [http://gagapeople.com/english/about-gaga/ ''Gaga''] ''Gaga People website''</ref> Additionally, float is intended to facilitate a constant awareness and activeness in which dancers are never completely released, even when they are doing nothing, leaving them 'available' for movement.<ref>KATAN-SCHMID, EINAV. EMBODIED PHILOSOPHY IN DANCE: Gaga and Ohad Naharin's Movement Research. PALGRAVE MACMILLAN, 2018. Page 123.</ref>\n\n=== Vocabulary ===\nNaharin created Gaga terminology specific to bodily functions that activated throughout a dancer\u2019s Gaga practice. \u201cBiba\u201d means to pull the body away from the seat bones. It is meant to create more space and freedom in the lower spine. \u201cTashi\u201d means to move with feet glued to the floor. \u201cPika\u201d is the activation of the spot right beneath the pubic bone.<ref>KATAN-SCHMID, EINAV. EMBODIED PHILOSOPHY IN DANCE: Gaga and Ohad Naharin's Movement Research. PALGRAVE MACMILLAN, 2018.</ref> \n\n=== Focus on pleasure ===\nNaharin emphasizes the return to pleasure, especially within moments of exaggeration and bodily effort. His belief is that pleasure is always good for the body. Gaga often requests demanding actions, such as running and shaking, but the effort of \u201cburning muscles\u201d must be tied to pleasure in order to keep it healthy.<ref>KATAN-SCHMID, EINAV. EMBODIED PHILOSOPHY IN DANCE: Gaga and Ohad Naharin's Movement Research. PALGRAVE MACMILLAN, 2018.</ref> Gaga has been taught in centers for people affected by Parkinson\u2019s disease.<ref> [http://www.abcdance.eu/dance-with-parkinson-joining-science-and-art-through-beauty/ 'Dancing with Parkinson's '] </ref>\n\n=== Release of aesthetic ambitions ===\nThe Gaga language focuses on the internal sensations. Due to this, classes are run without mirrors. Naharin emphasizes the release of ambitions or inhibitions. He states \u201cwe might be silly, we can laugh at ourselves\u201d<ref>Gaga People, [http://gagapeople.com/english/about-gaga/ ''Gaga''] ''Gaga People website''</ref> This kind of instruction is an effort for exploratory research without limits or tensions. \n\n=== Connection to groove ===\nWith or without music, dancers are asked to connect to the musicality of their movement.<ref>KATAN-SCHMID, EINAV. EMBODIED PHILOSOPHY IN DANCE: Gaga and Ohad Naharin's Movement Research. PALGRAVE MACMILLAN, 2018. Page 156.</ref> Naharin emphasizes attention to [[Groove (music)|groove]], as groove is a universal experience regardless of technique levels.<ref>Gaga People, [http://gagapeople.com/english/about-gaga/ ''Gaga''] ''Gaga People website''</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Dance in Israel]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Dance in Israel]]\n[[Category:Israeli inventions]]\n\n\n{{dance-stub}}\n", "name_user": "FlynnChester", "label": "safe", "comment": "sourcce 1 was dead, found the document elsewhere", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaga_(dance_vocabulary)"}
{"title_page": "Matthew Formston", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson|\n| name = Matthew Formston\n| image =File:XXXX15 - Matt Formston - 3b - 2016 Team processing.jpg\n| caption = 2016 Australian Paralympic Team Portrait\n| headercolor = green\n| textcolor = yellow\n| nationality = {{AUS}}\n| club = [[Central Coast (cycling team)|Central Coast]]\n| nickname = Formo\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1978|07|21|df=yes}} <ref name=one>{{cite web|title=Rider Profiles|url=http://www.cycling.org.au/High-Performance/Rider-Profiles/Male/ProfileId/49/Matthew-Formston|publisher=Cycling Australia|accessdate=20 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923212331/http://www.cycling.org.au/High-Performance/Rider-Profiles/Male/ProfileId/49/Matthew-Formston|archive-date=23 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Sydney]] <ref name=one/>\n| <!-- Sport -->\n| disability = [[Visual Impairment]]\n| coach = \n| height =\n| weight =\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[para-cycling]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{AUS}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UCI Para-cycling Track World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold |Aguascalientes 2014 | Tandem B Pursuit}}\n{{MedalSilver |Appledoon 2015 | Tandem B Pursuit}}\n}}\n\n'''Matthew Formston''' (born 21 July 1978) is a legally blind<ref name=\"two\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oztandem.com|title=OzTandem|publisher=OzTandem|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150811065102/http://www.oztandem.com/|archive-date=11 August 2015|accessdate=20 August 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Australian Professional Para Surfer and former professional Para Cyclist. Formston won gold and silver medals at the 2014 and 2015 [[UCI Para-cycling Track World Championships]] and represented Australia with pilot [[Nick Yallouris]], at the [[2016 Rio Paralympics]].<sup>[3]</sup> Formston also holds three consecutive world titles for [[Surfing]] (2017, 2018 and 2020) at the ISA Para Surfing World Championships (VI Division) as the 2016 to 2019 Australian Champion, 2018 and 2019 US Adaptive Open (Gold) and 2017, 2018, 2019 Dukes Ocean Fest Hawaii Gold medallist.\n\n==Personal==\nFormston was born on 21 July 1978 in Sydney, New South Wales.<sup>[1]</sup> At the age of five, Formston was diagnosed with [[Macular dystrophy, vitelliform|Macular Dystrophy]] eventually reducing his sight to 0% central vision and 5% [[peripheral vision]].<sup>[4]</sup> He is legally blind.<sup>[2]</sup> With a Diploma of Health Science and extensive business and competitive sport experience, Matt holds a national executive role as Head of Sustainability and [[Corporate social responsibility|Corporate Social Responsibility]]. He is also a sought after [[Keynote Speaker|keynote speaker]], [[Business coaching|business coach]] and offers strategic training workshops to promote high performing teams and resilient leadership. <sup>[1]</sup> Matt Formston and his wife Rebecca have three children and live on the [[Central Coast (New South Wales)|Central Coast of New South Wales]].\n\n==Career==\n\n==== Competitive Sports ====\nFormston's cycling career began in 2009 while on a charity ride for the Macular Disease Foundation. The ride took Formston from [[Sydney]] to [[Melbourne]] and he successfully completed it on a single bike. In 2012, Formston was named the Central Coast Cyclist of the Year. Formston originally rode competitively with [[Phillip Thuaux]] in 2010 before pairing with Mick Curran in 2012 as a tandem partner and the pair were known as OzTandem.<sup>[2]</sup> Curran, a fully sighted competitor, held the role of pilot for the duo. They went on to win gold in both track and road cycling on most continents around the globe and amassed 12 Australian National Titles between 2012 and 2016.\n\nIn 2013, the pair won gold in the Tandem Road Race at the UCI Para-cycling Road World Cup in Canada. <sup>[1]</sup> In 2014, Formston and Curran set a new world record in the Tandem Pursuit event clocking a time of 4:11.213. <sup>[6]</sup> In the same year, they took home the gold medal at the 2014 UCI Para-cycling Track World Championships in [[Aguascalientes|Aguascalientes, Mexico]].<sup>[6]</sup> Formston and Curran competed in the 2015 UCI Para-cycling Track World Championships in [[Apeldoorn]], [[Netherlands]] and finished second in the Tandem Pursuit.\n\nFormston and Curran's bond went beyond the tandem bike with the pair starting their own business known as Champion Vision.\n\nAt the 2016 Rio Paralympics, Formston's new cycling pilot was [[Nick Yallouris]] from [[Chittaway Point, New South Wales]]<sup>[9]</sup> \u00a0eventually announcing his retirement from competitive cycling the same year.\n\nIn 2016, Formston was awarded the [[New South Wales Institute of Sport]] Scholarship to continue his pursuit of competitive cycling and surfing.<sup>[11]</sup>\n\nIn 2017, Formston appeared alongside [[Ron McCallum]] on the Season 2 premiere episode of ABC's ''[[You Can't Ask That]]'' entitled \"Blind People\".<sup>[12]</sup>\n\nAs a professional surfer, Formston is the current Para Surfing World Champion, winning the 2017, 2018 and 2020 ISA World Para Surfing Championships (VI Division). He won the 2016, 2017, 2018 and 2019 \u00a0Australian Championships as well as the 2018 and 2020 US Adaptive Open (Gold). In addition, Formston achieved the 2017, 2018 and 2019 Dukes Ocean Fest Hawaii (Gold) and took home the 2018 Huntington Adaptive Pro (Gold). \n\nFormston has a range of surfing sponsors including Firewire, Slater Designs and [[Billabong (clothing)|Billabong]].\n\n==== Executive and Professional Coaching ====\nMatt Formston is a sought after [[Keynote Speaker|keynote speaker]] in [[strategic leadership]], offering executive [[business coaching]] and professional workshop facilitation. As a Gold medallist, world title holder and [[Paralympian]], Formston uses his extensive experience in [[sport psychology]], visualisation, goal setting as well as corporate experience as a successful business executive to deliver tactics to turn challenges into strengths. \n\nFormston has delivered individual and group coaching to a range of corporate executives across companies such as [[Hewlett-Packard|Hewlett Packard]], [[Tesla, Inc.|Tesla]], [[PepsiCo|Pepsi Co]], [[Optus]], Lend Lease, [[Institution of Civil Engineers]], [[Deloitte]], Orthoptics Australia, [[Vision Australia]] and [[Macquarie University]].\n\nAs Chair of the Macquarie Business Park Partnership, Formston has led corporate executives to deliver a modern approach to overcoming community disadvantage.\n\n==Recognition==\n*2012 - Central Coast Cyclist of the Year <ref name=\"one\">{{cite web|title=Rider Profiles|url=http://www.cycling.org.au/High-Performance/Rider-Profiles/Male/ProfileId/49/Matthew-Formston|publisher=Cycling Australia|accessdate=20 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923212331/http://www.cycling.org.au/High-Performance/Rider-Profiles/Male/ProfileId/49/Matthew-Formston|archive-date=23 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.paralympic.org.au/athlete/matt-formston/ Australian Paralympic Committee profile]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150923212331/http://www.cycling.org.au/High-Performance/Rider-Profiles/Male/ProfileId/49/Matthew-Formston Cycling Australia profile]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6u6yBBY3B3Q We Believe - Matt Formston and Nick Yallouris]\n*[http://mattformston.com/about/ Personal Website]\n\n{{2016 Australian Paralympic Team}}\n{{Portal bar|Australia|Biography|Sports}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Formston, Matthew}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australia at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic cyclists of Australia]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic cyclists with a vision impairment]]\n[[Category:Blind people from Australia]]\n[[Category:Sportsmen from New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Australian male cyclists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson|\n| name = Matthew Formston\n| image =File:XXXX15 - Matt Formston - 3b - 2016 Team processing.jpg\n| caption = 2016 Australian Paralympic Team Portrait\n| headercolor = green\n| textcolor = yellow\n| nationality = {{AUS}}\n| club = [[Central Coast (cycling team)|Central Coast]]\n| nickname = Formo\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1978|07|21|df=yes}} <ref name=one>{{cite web|title=Rider Profiles|url=http://www.cycling.org.au/High-Performance/Rider-Profiles/Male/ProfileId/49/Matthew-Formston|publisher=Cycling Australia|accessdate=20 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923212331/http://www.cycling.org.au/High-Performance/Rider-Profiles/Male/ProfileId/49/Matthew-Formston|archive-date=23 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Sydney]] <ref name=one/>\n| <!-- Sport -->\n| disability = [[Visual Impairment]]\n| coach = \n| height =\n| weight =\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[para-cycling]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{AUS}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UCI Para-cycling Track World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold |Aguascalientes 2014 | Tandem B Pursuit}}\n{{MedalSilver |Appledoon 2015 | Tandem B Pursuit}}\n}}\n\n'''Matthew Formston'''  (born 21 July 1978) is a legally blind<ref name=two>{{cite web|title=OzTandem|url=http://www.oztandem.com|publisher=OzTandem|accessdate=20 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150811065102/http://www.oztandem.com/|archive-date=11 August 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Australian [[Para-cycling|para-cyclist]] who won gold and silver medals at the 2014 and 2015 at the [[UCI Para-cycling Track World Championships]]. With his pilot [[Nick Yallouris]], he represented Australia at the [[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio Paralympics]].<ref name=\"rio2016\">{{cite news|last1=Walsh|first1=Scott|title=Five-time gold medallist Kieran Modra facing unusual \u2018first\u2019 in storied Paralympics career|url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/sport/olympics-2016/fivetime-gold-medallist-kieran-modra-facing-unusual-first-in-storied-paralympics-career/news-story/7e1e7a1af995bbefdb638a562fbac6c3|accessdate=31 May 2016|work=Adelaide Advertiser|date=30 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal==\nFormston was born on 21 July 1978 in [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]].<ref name=one>{{cite web|title=Rider Profiles|url=http://www.cycling.org.au/High-Performance/Rider-Profiles/Male/ProfileId/49/Matthew-Formston|publisher=Cycling Australia|accessdate=20 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923212331/http://www.cycling.org.au/High-Performance/Rider-Profiles/Male/ProfileId/49/Matthew-Formston|archive-date=23 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> At age of five, Formston was diagnosed with Macular Dystrophy resulting in 0% central vision and 5% [[peripheral vision]].<ref name= four/> He is legally blind.<ref name=\"two\"/> He has completed a Diploma of Health Science and works as an Accounts Executive.<ref name=one/>\n\n==Career==\nFormston's cycling journey began on a charity ride from Sydney to Melbourne on a single bike for the Macular Degeneration Foundation in 2009.<ref name=\"apc\">{{cite web|title=Matthew Formston|url=https://www.paralympic.org.au/athlete/matt-formston/|website=Australian Paralympic Committee website|accessdate=2 June 2016}}</ref> Formston originally rode with Mick Curran as a [[tandem (UCI)|tandem]] partner; the pair were known as OzTandem.<ref name=two/> Curran is known as the pilot because he is the person who is fully sighted and steers the bike. Formston and Curran trained out of the [[Central Coast, New South Wales]] riding every morning for two hours and a few gym sessions on top of that throughout the week.<ref name=four>{{cite web|last1=Connellan|first1=Matthew|title=Perfect pair: Blind cyclist and his co-pilot prepare for World Championships ahead of Rio Games|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/newslocal/news/perfect-pair-blind-cyclist-and-his-co-pilot-prepare-for-world-championships-ahead-of-rio-games/story-fngr8gwi-1227209084730|publisher=News Local|accessdate=20 August 2015}}</ref>  In 2013, the pair also finished 1st in the Tandem Road Race [[Para-cycling]] Road World Cup.<ref name=one/>  In 2014, Formston and Curran set a new [[world record]] in the Tandem Pursuit Para-cycling event clocking in a time of 4:11.213 <ref name=five/> and won the gold medal at the 2014 [[UCI Para-cycling Track World Championships]] in [[Aguascalientes]], [[Mexico]].<ref name=five/> Formston and Curran competed in the 2015 [[UCI Para-cycling Track World Championships]]in [[Appledoon]], [[Netherlands]] and finished second in the Tandem B 4&nbsp;km pursuit.\n\nFormston and Curran's bond went beyond the tandem bike with the pair running their own business known as Champion Vision.<ref name=three>{{cite web|title=About|url=http://www.championvision.com.au/about|publisher=Champion Vision|access-date=20 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150916105812/http://www.championvision.com.au/about#|archive-date=16 September 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=thre>{{cite web|title=Matt Formston|url=https://www.linkedin.com/pub/matt-formston/83/309/44|publisher=LinkedIn|accessdate=20 August 2015}}</ref> He is coached by Tom Skulander <ref name=five>{{cite web|last1=Moran|first1=Matt|title=The \u2018Impossible\u2019 in the morning, becomes \u2018Possible\u2019 by the afternoon|url=https://wattbike.com/uk/blog/post/the_impossible_in_the_morning_becomes_possible_by_the_afternoon|publisher=Wattbike|accessdate=20 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio Paralympics]], Formston's new pilot was [[Nick Yallouris]] who lived in [[Chittaway Point, New South Wales]] close to where Formston lives.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nick Yallouris|url=https://www.paralympic.org.au/athlete/nick-yallouris/|website=Australian Paralympic Committee website|accessdate=2 June 2016}}</ref> At the Rio Games, Formston competed in four events and his best results were fifth in the Men's Individual Pursuit B and sixth in the Men's 1&nbsp;km Time Trial B.<ref>{{cite web|title=Matthew Formston|url=https://www.rio2016.com/en/paralympics/athlete/matthew-formston|website=Rio Paralympics Official site|accessdate=15 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, he is a [[New South Wales Institute of Sport]] scholarship holder.<ref name=\"nswis\">{{cite web|title=Five NSWIS Para-cyclists pedalling towards Rio|url=http://www.nswis.com.au/media/nswis-news/may-2016/five-nswis-para-cyclists-pedalling-towards-rio.aspx|website=New South Wales Institute of Sport website|date=31 May 2016|accessdate=2 June 2016}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Formston appeared alongside [[Ron McCallum]] on the Season 2 premiere episode of ''[[You Can't Ask That]]'' entitled \"Blind People\".<ref>{{cite web|title=ABC\u2019s You Can\u2019t Ask That returns with more awkward questions|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/review/abcs-you-cant-ask-that-returns-with-more-awkward-questions/news-story/e2b41b9952186f12ccc4de1916c79f09|website=The Australian|accessdate=7 April 2017|date=1 April 2017|author=Graeme Blundell}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\n*2012 - Central Coast Cyclist of the Year <ref name=one/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.paralympic.org.au/athlete/matt-formston/ Australian Paralympic Committee profile]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150923212331/http://www.cycling.org.au/High-Performance/Rider-Profiles/Male/ProfileId/49/Matthew-Formston Cycling Australia profile]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6u6yBBY3B3Q We Believe - Matt Formston and Nick Yallouris]\n*[http://mattformston.com/about/ Personal Website]\n\n{{2016 Australian Paralympic Team}}\n{{Portal bar|Australia|Biography|Sports}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Formston, Matthew}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australia at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic cyclists of Australia]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic cyclists with a vision impairment]]\n[[Category:Blind people from Australia]]\n[[Category:Sportsmen from New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Australian male cyclists]]\n", "name_user": "EmmaWiki01", "label": "safe", "comment": "Review and update content and recent achievements.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matthew_Formston"}
{"title_page": "Thomas Partey", "text_new": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Thomas Partey\n| image = Thomas Partey 2019.jpg\n| caption = Thomas with [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] in 2019\n| fullname = Thomas Teye Partey<ref>{{cite web |url=http://actas.rfef.es/actas/RFEF_CmpActa1?cod_primaria=1000144&CodActa=57319 |title=Acta del Partido celebrado el 18 de mayo de 2019, en Valencia |trans-title=Minutes of the Match held on 18 May 2019, in Valencia |publisher=Royal Spanish Football Federation |accessdate=17 June 2019 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1993|6|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Krobo Odumase]], Ghana\n| height = 1.85 m\n| position = [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|Defensive midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]\n| clubnumber = 5\n| youthyears1 = 2011\u20132012\n| youthclubs1 = Odometah FC<ref>[http://sportsworldghana.com/feature-from-odumase-to-madrid-thomas-partey-has-arrived/ FEATURE: From Odumase to Madrid: Thomas Partey has arrived]; [http://sportsworldghana.com], November 17, 2017</ref>\n| youthyears2 = 2012\u20132013\n| youthclubs2 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]\n| years1 = 2013\u20132015\n| clubs1 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid B]]\n| caps1 = 28\n| goals1 = 3\n| years2 = 2013\u20132014\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] (loan)\n| caps2 = 37\n| goals2 = 5\n| years3 = 2014\u20132015\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[UD Almer\u00eda|Almer\u00eda]] (loan)\n| caps3 = 31\n| goals3 = 4\n| years4 = 2015\u2013\n| clubs4 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]\n| caps4 = 118\n| goals4 = 11\n| nationalyears1 = 2016\u2013\n| nationalteam1 = [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 27\n| nationalgoals1 = 10\n| pcupdate = 23:01, 7 March 2020 (UTC)\n| ntupdate = 23:43, 14 November 2019 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Thomas Teye Partey''' (born 13 June 1993), often simply known as '''Thomas''', is a Ghanaian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]] for English club [[Arsenal]] and the [[Ghana national football team|Ghana national team]].\n\nHe spent most of his career with [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]], making over 150 competitive appearances. A full [[Ghana national football team|Ghana international]] since 2016, he represented the nation at two [[Africa Cup of Nations]] tournaments.\n\n==Club career==\n===Atl\u00e9tico Madrid===\n[[File:Thomas Partey.jpg|150px|thumb|Thomas with [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] in 2018]]\nBorn in [[Krobo Odumase]], Thomas was a product of local Odometah FC's youth ranks.<ref>[http://sportsworldghana.com/feature-from-odumase-to-madrid-thomas-partey-has-arrived/ FEATURE: From Odumase to Madrid: Thomas Partey has arrived]; [http://sportsworldghana.com], November 17, 2017</ref> He signed a contract with [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] in 2011, and was subsequently moved to [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid B|the reserves]] a year later. On 10 March 2013, Thomas was called up to the main squad for the match against [[Real Sociedad]].<ref>[http://www.marca.com/2013/03/09/futbol/equipos/atletico/1362835894.html Oliver Torres y Thomas, novedades en la lista del Atl\u00e9tico (Oliver Torres and Thomas, news in Atl\u00e9tico's list)]; [[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]], 9 March 2013 {{in lang|es}}</ref> However, he remained unused in the eventual 0\u20131 home defeat.<ref>[http://espnfc.com/en/report/348268/report.html?soccernet=true&cc=3888 Prieto ends Atletico's perfect home form] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130824040156/http://espnfc.com/en/report/348268/report.html?soccernet=true&cc=3888 |date=2013-08-24 }}; [[ESPN FC]], 10 March 2013</ref>\n\n====Loans to Mallorca and Almer\u00eda====\nOn 12 July, Thomas was loaned to [[RCD Mallorca]], [[2012\u201313 La Liga|freshly relegated to the second level]].<ref>[http://www.rcdmallorca.es/principal_new.php?nombreModulo=noticiasDetalle&idnoticia=32773&idmenu=3 Thomas Teye Partey, nuevo jugador del RCD Mallorca (Thomas Teye Partey, new player of RCD Mallorca)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130715010146/http://www.rcdmallorca.es/principal_new.php?nombreModulo=noticiasDetalle&idnoticia=32773&idmenu=3 |date=2013-07-15 }}; Mallorca's official website, 12 July 2013 {{in lang|es}}</ref> On 18 August, he made his professional debut, in a 0\u20134 away defeat against [[CE Sabadell FC]].<ref>[http://www.marca.com/2013/08/18/futbol/2adivision/1376858932.html El Sabadell golea y es el primer l\u00edder de la temporada (Sabadell thrashes and is the season's first leader)]; Marca, 18 August 2013 {{in lang|es}}</ref> Thomas scored his first professional goal on 15 September, netting his side's second of a 2\u20132 draw at [[H\u00e9rcules CF]].<ref>[http://www.marca.com/2013/09/15/futbol/2adivision/1379271208.html El Mallorca dej\u00f3 escapar la victoria en apenas diez minutos (Mallorca lets victory slip away in only ten minutes)]; Marca, 15 September 2013 {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 July 2014, Thomas joined [[La Liga]] side [[UD Almer\u00eda]] also in a temporary deal.<ref>[http://www.udalmeriasad.com/-/el-almeria-ficha-al-ghanes-thomas-un-centrocampista-de-largo-recorrido-y-poderio-fisico El Almer\u00eda ficha al ghan\u00e9s Thomas, un centrocampista de largo recorrido y poder\u00edo f\u00edsico (Almer\u00eda signs Ghanaian Thomas, a central midfielder with long-haul and physical strength)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729012152/http://www.udalmeriasad.com/-/el-almeria-ficha-al-ghanes-thomas-un-centrocampista-de-largo-recorrido-y-poderio-fisico |date=2014-07-29 }}; Almer\u00eda's official profile, 27 July 2014 {{in lang|es}}</ref> He made his debut in the competition on 23 August, starting in a 1\u20131 home draw against [[RCD Espanyol]].<ref>[http://www.marca.com/eventos/marcador/futbol/2014_15/primera/jornada_1/alm_esp/ Sergio Garc\u00eda amarga la Feria de madrugada (Sergio Garc\u00eda bitters the dawn fair)]; Marca, 23 August 2014 {{in lang|es}}</ref> Thomas scored his first goals in [[Spanish football league system|the main category of Spanish football]] on 11 April 2015, netting a brace in a 3\u20130 home win against [[Granada CF]].<ref>[http://www.marca.com/eventos/marcador/futbol/2014_15/la-liga/jornada_31/alm_gda/ El Almer\u00eda pide turno por la salvaci\u00f3n (Almer\u00eda calls turn for the salvation)]; Marca, 11 April 2015 {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n\n====Return to Atl\u00e9tico Madrid====\nHe made his first team debut for ''Atleti'' on 28 November 2015, replacing [[Luciano Vietto]] in a 1\u20130 home win against Espanyol.<ref>[http://www.marca.com/eventos/marcador/futbol/2015_16/la-liga/jornada_13/atm_esp/ Una m\u00e1quina de rentabilizar goles (A goal-rentable machine)]; Marca, 28 November 2015 {{in lang|es}}</ref> On 2 January of the following year he scored his first league goal for the club, netting the game's only in a home success over [[Levante UD]].<ref>[http://www.marca.com/eventos/marcador/futbol/2015_16/la-liga/jornada_18/atm_lev/ Thomas fue el l\u00edder (Thomas was the leader)]; Marca, 2 January 2016 {{in lang|es}}</ref> On 28 May, Thomas played in the [[2016 UEFA Champions League Final|UEFA Champions League Final]] against [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]], replacing [[Koke (footballer, born 1992)|Koke]] in the 116th minute as his side lost on penalties.<ref name=final>{{cite news|title=Spot-on Real Madrid defeat Atl\u00e9tico in final again|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2016/matches/round=2000638/match=2015789/postmatch/report/index.html#madrid+crowned+11th+time|accessdate=30 May 2016|publisher=UEFA|date=28 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nThomas signed a contract extension with ''Atleti'' through 2022 on 14 February 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.in/football/soccer-transfers/story/3060582/thomas-partey-signs-long-term-atletico-madrid-contract|title=Partey signs new Atletico Madrid contract|date=14 February 2017|website=ESPN|language=en|access-date=29 September 2019}}</ref> On 31 October he scored his first European goal with a long-range strike to equalise at home to [[FK Qarabag]] in a 1\u20131 draw in the Champions League group game; he became the first African to score in the competition for Atl\u00e9tico.<ref>{{cite news |title=Thomas Partey scores stunning goal in UEFA Champions League against Qarabag |url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/thomas-partey-scores-stunning-goal-in-uefa-champions-league-against-qarabag |accessdate=10 March 2020 |publisher=Ghana Soccer Net |date=31 October 2017}}</ref> Following his impressive performances for the club, he was rewarded with another contract on 1 March 2018, this time until 2023.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.as.com/en/2018/03/01/football/1519906233_784546.html|title=Partey on! Thomas renews with Atletico until 2023|date=1 March 2018|website=Diario AS|access-date=29 September 2019}}</ref> That 16 May, he came on for the final two minutes in a 3\u20130 win over [[Olympique de Marseille]] in the [[2018 UEFA Europa League Final]].<ref name=europa/>\n\nOn 1 September 2019, Thomas came on as a late substitute and netted the match's winner in the last minute of the game, as Atl\u00e9tico came back from 2\u20130 down to win the game by 3\u20132 against [[SD Eibar|Eibar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-tza/news/thomas-partey-scores-late-winner-in-epic-atletico-madrid/1vzyzqq14e35616hcy00wconza|title=Partey scores late winner in epic Atletico Madrid comeback against Eibar|date=2 September 2019|website=Goal|access-date=29 September 2019}}</ref> Four weeks later, he marked his 100th [[La Liga]] appearance for ''Los Rojiblancos'' with a [[Player of the match|man-of-the-match]] performance in a 0\u20130 draw against [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] in [[Madrid Derby]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/thomas-partey-puts-in-masterclass-performance-in-madrid/1glcz6zyglbx411dxxoukt5zfj|title=Thomas Partey puts in masterclass performance in Madrid Derby|date=29 September 2019|website=Goal|access-date=29 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nIn May 2016, Thomas was called up for the first time to the [[Ghana national football team|Ghana national team]] by manager [[Avram Grant]], ahead of a [[2017 Africa Cup of Nations qualification]] match against [[Mauritius national football team|Mauritius]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Feature: Thomas Partey's perfect week|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gh/news/4366/uefa-champions-league/2016/05/27/23992162/feature-thomas-parteys-perfect-week|accessdate=3 January 2017|publisher=Goal.com|date=27 May 2016}}</ref> He made his debut on 5 June, replacing [[Frank Acheampong]] for the final 11 minutes of a 2\u20130 away win that booked the Black Stars' position in the [[2017 Africa Cup of Nations|finals]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Atletico Madrid midfielder makes Ghana debut in Mauritius victory|url=http://pulse.com.gh/sports/thomas-teye-partey-atletico-madrid-midfielder-makes-ghana-debut-in-mauritius-victory-id5114891.html|accessdate=3 January 2017|publisher=Pulse|date=5 June 2016}}</ref> On 5 September 2017, Thomas scored his first international hat-trick in a 5\u20131 win against [[Congo national football team|Congo]] in [[2018 FIFA World Cup Qualification]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Congo 1 - 5 Ghana|url=http://www.espnfc.com/match?gameId=464064|accessdate=5 September 2017|publisher=ESPNFC|date=5 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nThomas was chosen in [[Kwesi Appiah]]'s 23-man squad for the [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations]] in Egypt.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McPartlin |first1=Patrick |title=Thomas Agyepong named in Ghana squad for 2019 Africa Cup of Nations |url=https://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/sport/football/hibs/latest-hibs-news/thomas-agyepong-named-ghana-squad-2019-africa-cup-nations-545628 |accessdate=10 March 2020 |work=Edinburgh Evening News |date=11 June 2019}}</ref> In their last group game, he scored in a 2\u20130 win over [[Guinea-Bissau national football team|Guinea-Bissau]] at the [[Suez Stadium]] as the Black Stars topped their group.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Da Silva |first1=Michael |title=Africa Cup of Nations 2019: Ghana top group, Cameroon to face Nigeria |url=https://www.dw.com/en/africa-cup-of-nations-2019-ghana-top-group-cameroon-to-face-nigeria/a-49448560-0 |accessdate=10 March 2020 |publisher=Deutsche Welle |date=2 July 2019}}</ref> He netted in the penalty shootout at the end of the last-16 game against [[Tunisia national football team|Tunisia]] on 8 July, though his team was eliminated.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ghana 1&ndash;1 Tunisia |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48821467 |accessdate=10 March 2020 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=8 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThomas won the [[Ghana Player of the Year]] award in 2018 and 2019.<ref name=ghana18/><ref name=ghana19/>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|11 March 2020}}<ref>{{Soccerway|250434|accessdate=22 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[UEFA#Club|Europe]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals\n|-\n|[[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] (loan)\n|[[2013\u201314 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|2013\u201314]]\n|[[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]]\n|37||5||1||0||colspan=4|\u2014||38||5\n|-\n|[[UD Almer\u00eda|Almer\u00eda]] (loan)\n|[[2014\u201315 UD Almer\u00eda season|2014\u201315]]\n| rowspan=\"6\" |[[La Liga]]\n|31||4||1||0||colspan=4|\u2014||32||4\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" |[[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]\n|[[2015\u201316 Atl\u00e9tico Madrid season|2015\u201316]]\n|13||2||5||1||5||0||colspan=2|\u2014||23||3\n|-\n|[[2016\u201317 Atl\u00e9tico Madrid season|2016\u201317]]\n|16||1||2||0||6||0||colspan=2|\u2014||24||1\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 Atl\u00e9tico Madrid season|2017\u201318]]\n|33||3||3||1||14||1||colspan=2|\u2014||50||5\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Atl\u00e9tico Madrid season|2018\u201319]]\n|32||3||3||0||6||0||1||0||42||3\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 Atl\u00e9tico Madrid season|2019\u201320]]\n|24||2||1||0||8||1||2||0||35||3\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Total\n!118!!11!!14!!2!!39!!2!!3!!0!!174!!15\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" |Career total\n!186!!20!!16!!2!!39!!2!!3!!0!!244!!24\n|}\n\n===International===\n{{Updated|matches played on 14 November 2019}}<ref name=\"nft\">{{NFT|64684|accessdate=4 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|[[Ghana national football team|Ghana]]\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|2016||5||0\n|-\n|2017||10||5\n|-\n|2018||4||2\n|-\n|2019||8||3\n|-\n!Total||27||10\n|}\n\n===International goals===\n:''Scores and results list Ghana's goal tally first.''<ref name=\"nft\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! No !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1. || 1 September 2017 || [[Baba Yara Stadium]], [[Kumasi]], Ghana || rowspan=4 | {{fb|CGO}} || align=center | '''1'''\u20131 || align=center | 1\u20131 || rowspan=\"4\"| [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 CAF Third Round|2018 FIFA World Cup qualification]]\n|-\n| 2. || rowspan=\"3\"| 5 September 2017 || rowspan=\"3\"| [[Stade Municipal de Kint\u00e9l\u00e9]], [[Brazzaville]], Congo || align=center | '''2'''\u20130 ||rowspan=\"3\"| <center>5\u20131</center>\n|-\n| 3. || align=center | '''3'''\u20131\n|-\n| 4. || align=center | '''4'''\u20131\n|-\n| 5. || 10 October 2017 || [[King Abdullah Sports City]], [[Jeddah]], Saudi Arabia || {{fb|KSA}} || align=center | '''3'''\u20130 || align=center | 3\u20130 ||rowspan=\"4\"| [[Exhibition game#Association football|Friendly]]\n|-\n| 6. || 30 May 2018 || [[Nissan Stadium (Yokohama)|International Stadium]], [[Yokohama]], Japan || {{fb|JPN}} || align=center | '''2'''\u20130 || align=center | 2\u20130 \n|-\n| 7. || 7 June 2018 || [[Laugardalsv\u00f6llur]], [[Reykjav\u00edk]], Iceland || {{fb|ISL}} || align=center | '''2'''\u20132 || align=center | 2\u20132\n|-\n| 8. || 26 March 2019 || [[Accra Sports Stadium]], [[Accra]], Ghana || {{fb|MTN}} || align=center | '''3'''\u20131 || align=center | 3\u20131\n|-\n| 9. || 2 July 2019 || [[Suez Stadium]], [[Suez]], Egypt || {{fb|GNB}} || align=center | '''2'''\u20130 || align=center | 2\u20130 || [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations Group F|2019 Africa Cup of Nations]]\n|-\n| 10. || 14 November 2019 || [[Cape Coast Sports Stadium]], [[Cape Coast]], Ghana || {{fb|RSA}} || align=center | '''1'''\u20130 || align=center | 2\u20130 || [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations qualification Group C|2021 Africa Cup of Nations qualification]]\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n'''Atl\u00e9tico Madrid'''\n*[[UEFA Champions League]] runner-up: [[2015\u201316 UEFA Champions League|2015\u201316]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/36254652|title=Real Madrid 1-1 Atletico Madrid (5-3 pens)|date=2016-05-28|access-date=2019-12-31|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n*[[UEFA Europa League]]: [[2017\u201318 UEFA Europa League|2017\u201318]]<ref name=europa>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2018/may/16/marseille-v-atletico-madrid-europa-league-final-live|title=Marseille 0-3 Atl\u00e9tico Madrid: 2018 Europa League final \u2013 as it happened|last=Murray|first=Scott|date=2018-05-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-31|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n*[[UEFA Super Cup]]: [[2018 UEFA Super Cup|2018]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global/2018/aug/15/real-madrid-atletico-madrid-european-super-cup-match-report|title=Diego Costa double helps Atl\u00e9tico beat Real Madrid 4-2 in Uefa Super Cup|last=sport|first=Guardian|date=2018-08-15|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-31|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[CAF Team of the Year]]: 2018<ref>{{cite news|title=Salah and Mane Picked in First Africa Best 11 |url=https://fifpro.org/news/salah-mahrez-and-mane-in-first-africa-best-11/en/|publisher=FIFPro |date=8 January 2019|accessdate=8 January 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Ghana Player of the Year]]: 2018,<ref name=ghana18>{{cite news |last1=Zurek |first1=Kweku |title=Ghana Football Awards: Partey named Footballer of the Year |url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/sports/sports-news/ghana-football-awards-partey-named-footballer-of-the-year.html |accessdate=10 March 2020 |publisher=Graphic |date=8 July 2018}}</ref> 2019<ref name=ghana19>{{cite news |last1=Douihech |first1=Mayssa |title=2019 Ghana Football Awards: Full list of winners |url=https://orangefootballclub.com/en/articles/2019-ghana-football-awards-winners/ |accessdate=10 March 2020 |publisher=Orange Football Club |date=22 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{BDFutbol}}\n*{{Futbolme profile|15062}}\n\n{{Atl\u00e9tico Madrid squad}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Ghana squads\n| bg        = #CA1118\n| fg        = #FBE816\n| bordercolor = black\n| list1 = \n{{Ghana squad 2017 Africa Cup of Nations}}\n{{Ghana squad 2019 Africa Cup of Nations}}\n}}\n{{Ghanaian Footballer of the Year}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Partey, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Eastern Region (Ghana)]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Atl\u00e9tico Madrid B players]]\n[[Category:RCD Mallorca players]]\n[[Category:UD Almer\u00eda players]]\n[[Category:Atl\u00e9tico Madrid footballers]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Ghana international footballers]]\n[[Category:2017 Africa Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:2019 Africa Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Thomas Partey\n| image = Thomas Partey 2019.jpg\n| caption = Thomas with [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] in 2019\n| fullname = Thomas Teye Partey<ref>{{cite web |url=http://actas.rfef.es/actas/RFEF_CmpActa1?cod_primaria=1000144&CodActa=57319 |title=Acta del Partido celebrado el 18 de mayo de 2019, en Valencia |trans-title=Minutes of the Match held on 18 May 2019, in Valencia |publisher=Royal Spanish Football Federation |accessdate=17 June 2019 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1993|6|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Krobo Odumase]], Ghana\n| height = 1.85 m\n| position = [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|Defensive midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]\n| clubnumber = 5\n| youthyears1 = 2011\u20132012\n| youthclubs1 = Odometah FC<ref>[http://sportsworldghana.com/feature-from-odumase-to-madrid-thomas-partey-has-arrived/ FEATURE: From Odumase to Madrid: Thomas Partey has arrived]; [http://sportsworldghana.com], November 17, 2017</ref>\n| youthyears2 = 2012\u20132013\n| youthclubs2 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]\n| years1 = 2013\u20132015\n| clubs1 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid B]]\n| caps1 = 28\n| goals1 = 3\n| years2 = 2013\u20132014\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] (loan)\n| caps2 = 37\n| goals2 = 5\n| years3 = 2014\u20132015\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[UD Almer\u00eda|Almer\u00eda]] (loan)\n| caps3 = 31\n| goals3 = 4\n| years4 = 2015\u2013\n| clubs4 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]\n| caps4 = 118\n| goals4 = 11\n| nationalyears1 = 2016\u2013\n| nationalteam1 = [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 27\n| nationalgoals1 = 10\n| pcupdate = 23:01, 7 March 2020 (UTC)\n| ntupdate = 23:43, 14 November 2019 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Thomas Teye Partey''' (born 13 June 1993), often simply known as '''Thomas''', is a Ghanaian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]] for Spanish club [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] and the [[Ghana national football team|Ghana national team]].\n\nHe spent most of his career with [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]], making over 150 competitive appearances. A full [[Ghana national football team|Ghana international]] since 2016, he represented the nation at two [[Africa Cup of Nations]] tournaments.\n\n==Club career==\n===Atl\u00e9tico Madrid===\n[[File:Thomas Partey.jpg|150px|thumb|Thomas with [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] in 2018]]\nBorn in [[Krobo Odumase]], Thomas was a product of local Odometah FC's youth ranks.<ref>[http://sportsworldghana.com/feature-from-odumase-to-madrid-thomas-partey-has-arrived/ FEATURE: From Odumase to Madrid: Thomas Partey has arrived]; [http://sportsworldghana.com], November 17, 2017</ref> He signed a contract with [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] in 2011, and was subsequently moved to [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid B|the reserves]] a year later. On 10 March 2013, Thomas was called up to the main squad for the match against [[Real Sociedad]].<ref>[http://www.marca.com/2013/03/09/futbol/equipos/atletico/1362835894.html Oliver Torres y Thomas, novedades en la lista del Atl\u00e9tico (Oliver Torres and Thomas, news in Atl\u00e9tico's list)]; [[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]], 9 March 2013 {{in lang|es}}</ref> However, he remained unused in the eventual 0\u20131 home defeat.<ref>[http://espnfc.com/en/report/348268/report.html?soccernet=true&cc=3888 Prieto ends Atletico's perfect home form] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130824040156/http://espnfc.com/en/report/348268/report.html?soccernet=true&cc=3888 |date=2013-08-24 }}; [[ESPN FC]], 10 March 2013</ref>\n\n====Loans to Mallorca and Almer\u00eda====\nOn 12 July, Thomas was loaned to [[RCD Mallorca]], [[2012\u201313 La Liga|freshly relegated to the second level]].<ref>[http://www.rcdmallorca.es/principal_new.php?nombreModulo=noticiasDetalle&idnoticia=32773&idmenu=3 Thomas Teye Partey, nuevo jugador del RCD Mallorca (Thomas Teye Partey, new player of RCD Mallorca)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130715010146/http://www.rcdmallorca.es/principal_new.php?nombreModulo=noticiasDetalle&idnoticia=32773&idmenu=3 |date=2013-07-15 }}; Mallorca's official website, 12 July 2013 {{in lang|es}}</ref> On 18 August, he made his professional debut, in a 0\u20134 away defeat against [[CE Sabadell FC]].<ref>[http://www.marca.com/2013/08/18/futbol/2adivision/1376858932.html El Sabadell golea y es el primer l\u00edder de la temporada (Sabadell thrashes and is the season's first leader)]; Marca, 18 August 2013 {{in lang|es}}</ref> Thomas scored his first professional goal on 15 September, netting his side's second of a 2\u20132 draw at [[H\u00e9rcules CF]].<ref>[http://www.marca.com/2013/09/15/futbol/2adivision/1379271208.html El Mallorca dej\u00f3 escapar la victoria en apenas diez minutos (Mallorca lets victory slip away in only ten minutes)]; Marca, 15 September 2013 {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 July 2014, Thomas joined [[La Liga]] side [[UD Almer\u00eda]] also in a temporary deal.<ref>[http://www.udalmeriasad.com/-/el-almeria-ficha-al-ghanes-thomas-un-centrocampista-de-largo-recorrido-y-poderio-fisico El Almer\u00eda ficha al ghan\u00e9s Thomas, un centrocampista de largo recorrido y poder\u00edo f\u00edsico (Almer\u00eda signs Ghanaian Thomas, a central midfielder with long-haul and physical strength)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729012152/http://www.udalmeriasad.com/-/el-almeria-ficha-al-ghanes-thomas-un-centrocampista-de-largo-recorrido-y-poderio-fisico |date=2014-07-29 }}; Almer\u00eda's official profile, 27 July 2014 {{in lang|es}}</ref> He made his debut in the competition on 23 August, starting in a 1\u20131 home draw against [[RCD Espanyol]].<ref>[http://www.marca.com/eventos/marcador/futbol/2014_15/primera/jornada_1/alm_esp/ Sergio Garc\u00eda amarga la Feria de madrugada (Sergio Garc\u00eda bitters the dawn fair)]; Marca, 23 August 2014 {{in lang|es}}</ref> Thomas scored his first goals in [[Spanish football league system|the main category of Spanish football]] on 11 April 2015, netting a brace in a 3\u20130 home win against [[Granada CF]].<ref>[http://www.marca.com/eventos/marcador/futbol/2014_15/la-liga/jornada_31/alm_gda/ El Almer\u00eda pide turno por la salvaci\u00f3n (Almer\u00eda calls turn for the salvation)]; Marca, 11 April 2015 {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n\n====Return to Atl\u00e9tico Madrid====\nHe made his first team debut for ''Atleti'' on 28 November 2015, replacing [[Luciano Vietto]] in a 1\u20130 home win against Espanyol.<ref>[http://www.marca.com/eventos/marcador/futbol/2015_16/la-liga/jornada_13/atm_esp/ Una m\u00e1quina de rentabilizar goles (A goal-rentable machine)]; Marca, 28 November 2015 {{in lang|es}}</ref> On 2 January of the following year he scored his first league goal for the club, netting the game's only in a home success over [[Levante UD]].<ref>[http://www.marca.com/eventos/marcador/futbol/2015_16/la-liga/jornada_18/atm_lev/ Thomas fue el l\u00edder (Thomas was the leader)]; Marca, 2 January 2016 {{in lang|es}}</ref> On 28 May, Thomas played in the [[2016 UEFA Champions League Final|UEFA Champions League Final]] against [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]], replacing [[Koke (footballer, born 1992)|Koke]] in the 116th minute as his side lost on penalties.<ref name=final>{{cite news|title=Spot-on Real Madrid defeat Atl\u00e9tico in final again|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2016/matches/round=2000638/match=2015789/postmatch/report/index.html#madrid+crowned+11th+time|accessdate=30 May 2016|publisher=UEFA|date=28 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nThomas signed a contract extension with ''Atleti'' through 2022 on 14 February 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.in/football/soccer-transfers/story/3060582/thomas-partey-signs-long-term-atletico-madrid-contract|title=Partey signs new Atletico Madrid contract|date=14 February 2017|website=ESPN|language=en|access-date=29 September 2019}}</ref> On 31 October he scored his first European goal with a long-range strike to equalise at home to [[FK Qarabag]] in a 1\u20131 draw in the Champions League group game; he became the first African to score in the competition for Atl\u00e9tico.<ref>{{cite news |title=Thomas Partey scores stunning goal in UEFA Champions League against Qarabag |url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/thomas-partey-scores-stunning-goal-in-uefa-champions-league-against-qarabag |accessdate=10 March 2020 |publisher=Ghana Soccer Net |date=31 October 2017}}</ref> Following his impressive performances for the club, he was rewarded with another contract on 1 March 2018, this time until 2023.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.as.com/en/2018/03/01/football/1519906233_784546.html|title=Partey on! Thomas renews with Atletico until 2023|date=1 March 2018|website=Diario AS|access-date=29 September 2019}}</ref> That 16 May, he came on for the final two minutes in a 3\u20130 win over [[Olympique de Marseille]] in the [[2018 UEFA Europa League Final]].<ref name=europa/>\n\nOn 1 September 2019, Thomas came on as a late substitute and netted the match's winner in the last minute of the game, as Atl\u00e9tico came back from 2\u20130 down to win the game by 3\u20132 against [[SD Eibar|Eibar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-tza/news/thomas-partey-scores-late-winner-in-epic-atletico-madrid/1vzyzqq14e35616hcy00wconza|title=Partey scores late winner in epic Atletico Madrid comeback against Eibar|date=2 September 2019|website=Goal|access-date=29 September 2019}}</ref> Four weeks later, he marked his 100th [[La Liga]] appearance for ''Los Rojiblancos'' with a [[Player of the match|man-of-the-match]] performance in a 0\u20130 draw against [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] in [[Madrid Derby]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/thomas-partey-puts-in-masterclass-performance-in-madrid/1glcz6zyglbx411dxxoukt5zfj|title=Thomas Partey puts in masterclass performance in Madrid Derby|date=29 September 2019|website=Goal|access-date=29 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nIn May 2016, Thomas was called up for the first time to the [[Ghana national football team|Ghana national team]] by manager [[Avram Grant]], ahead of a [[2017 Africa Cup of Nations qualification]] match against [[Mauritius national football team|Mauritius]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Feature: Thomas Partey's perfect week|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gh/news/4366/uefa-champions-league/2016/05/27/23992162/feature-thomas-parteys-perfect-week|accessdate=3 January 2017|publisher=Goal.com|date=27 May 2016}}</ref> He made his debut on 5 June, replacing [[Frank Acheampong]] for the final 11 minutes of a 2\u20130 away win that booked the Black Stars' position in the [[2017 Africa Cup of Nations|finals]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Atletico Madrid midfielder makes Ghana debut in Mauritius victory|url=http://pulse.com.gh/sports/thomas-teye-partey-atletico-madrid-midfielder-makes-ghana-debut-in-mauritius-victory-id5114891.html|accessdate=3 January 2017|publisher=Pulse|date=5 June 2016}}</ref> On 5 September 2017, Thomas scored his first international hat-trick in a 5\u20131 win against [[Congo national football team|Congo]] in [[2018 FIFA World Cup Qualification]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Congo 1 - 5 Ghana|url=http://www.espnfc.com/match?gameId=464064|accessdate=5 September 2017|publisher=ESPNFC|date=5 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nThomas was chosen in [[Kwesi Appiah]]'s 23-man squad for the [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations]] in Egypt.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McPartlin |first1=Patrick |title=Thomas Agyepong named in Ghana squad for 2019 Africa Cup of Nations |url=https://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/sport/football/hibs/latest-hibs-news/thomas-agyepong-named-ghana-squad-2019-africa-cup-nations-545628 |accessdate=10 March 2020 |work=Edinburgh Evening News |date=11 June 2019}}</ref> In their last group game, he scored in a 2\u20130 win over [[Guinea-Bissau national football team|Guinea-Bissau]] at the [[Suez Stadium]] as the Black Stars topped their group.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Da Silva |first1=Michael |title=Africa Cup of Nations 2019: Ghana top group, Cameroon to face Nigeria |url=https://www.dw.com/en/africa-cup-of-nations-2019-ghana-top-group-cameroon-to-face-nigeria/a-49448560-0 |accessdate=10 March 2020 |publisher=Deutsche Welle |date=2 July 2019}}</ref> He netted in the penalty shootout at the end of the last-16 game against [[Tunisia national football team|Tunisia]] on 8 July, though his team was eliminated.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ghana 1&ndash;1 Tunisia |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48821467 |accessdate=10 March 2020 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=8 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThomas won the [[Ghana Player of the Year]] award in 2018 and 2019.<ref name=ghana18/><ref name=ghana19/>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|11 March 2020}}<ref>{{Soccerway|250434|accessdate=22 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[UEFA#Club|Europe]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals\n|-\n|[[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] (loan)\n|[[2013\u201314 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|2013\u201314]]\n|[[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]]\n|37||5||1||0||colspan=4|\u2014||38||5\n|-\n|[[UD Almer\u00eda|Almer\u00eda]] (loan)\n|[[2014\u201315 UD Almer\u00eda season|2014\u201315]]\n| rowspan=\"6\" |[[La Liga]]\n|31||4||1||0||colspan=4|\u2014||32||4\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" |[[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]\n|[[2015\u201316 Atl\u00e9tico Madrid season|2015\u201316]]\n|13||2||5||1||5||0||colspan=2|\u2014||23||3\n|-\n|[[2016\u201317 Atl\u00e9tico Madrid season|2016\u201317]]\n|16||1||2||0||6||0||colspan=2|\u2014||24||1\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 Atl\u00e9tico Madrid season|2017\u201318]]\n|33||3||3||1||14||1||colspan=2|\u2014||50||5\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Atl\u00e9tico Madrid season|2018\u201319]]\n|32||3||3||0||6||0||1||0||42||3\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 Atl\u00e9tico Madrid season|2019\u201320]]\n|24||2||1||0||8||1||2||0||35||3\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Total\n!118!!11!!14!!2!!39!!2!!3!!0!!174!!15\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" |Career total\n!186!!20!!16!!2!!39!!2!!3!!0!!244!!24\n|}\n\n===International===\n{{Updated|matches played on 14 November 2019}}<ref name=\"nft\">{{NFT|64684|accessdate=4 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|[[Ghana national football team|Ghana]]\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|2016||5||0\n|-\n|2017||10||5\n|-\n|2018||4||2\n|-\n|2019||8||3\n|-\n!Total||27||10\n|}\n\n===International goals===\n:''Scores and results list Ghana's goal tally first.''<ref name=\"nft\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! No !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1. || 1 September 2017 || [[Baba Yara Stadium]], [[Kumasi]], Ghana || rowspan=4 | {{fb|CGO}} || align=center | '''1'''\u20131 || align=center | 1\u20131 || rowspan=\"4\"| [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 CAF Third Round|2018 FIFA World Cup qualification]]\n|-\n| 2. || rowspan=\"3\"| 5 September 2017 || rowspan=\"3\"| [[Stade Municipal de Kint\u00e9l\u00e9]], [[Brazzaville]], Congo || align=center | '''2'''\u20130 ||rowspan=\"3\"| <center>5\u20131</center>\n|-\n| 3. || align=center | '''3'''\u20131\n|-\n| 4. || align=center | '''4'''\u20131\n|-\n| 5. || 10 October 2017 || [[King Abdullah Sports City]], [[Jeddah]], Saudi Arabia || {{fb|KSA}} || align=center | '''3'''\u20130 || align=center | 3\u20130 ||rowspan=\"4\"| [[Exhibition game#Association football|Friendly]]\n|-\n| 6. || 30 May 2018 || [[Nissan Stadium (Yokohama)|International Stadium]], [[Yokohama]], Japan || {{fb|JPN}} || align=center | '''2'''\u20130 || align=center | 2\u20130 \n|-\n| 7. || 7 June 2018 || [[Laugardalsv\u00f6llur]], [[Reykjav\u00edk]], Iceland || {{fb|ISL}} || align=center | '''2'''\u20132 || align=center | 2\u20132\n|-\n| 8. || 26 March 2019 || [[Accra Sports Stadium]], [[Accra]], Ghana || {{fb|MTN}} || align=center | '''3'''\u20131 || align=center | 3\u20131\n|-\n| 9. || 2 July 2019 || [[Suez Stadium]], [[Suez]], Egypt || {{fb|GNB}} || align=center | '''2'''\u20130 || align=center | 2\u20130 || [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations Group F|2019 Africa Cup of Nations]]\n|-\n| 10. || 14 November 2019 || [[Cape Coast Sports Stadium]], [[Cape Coast]], Ghana || {{fb|RSA}} || align=center | '''1'''\u20130 || align=center | 2\u20130 || [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations qualification Group C|2021 Africa Cup of Nations qualification]]\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n'''Atl\u00e9tico Madrid'''\n*[[UEFA Champions League]] runner-up: [[2015\u201316 UEFA Champions League|2015\u201316]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/36254652|title=Real Madrid 1-1 Atletico Madrid (5-3 pens)|date=2016-05-28|access-date=2019-12-31|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n*[[UEFA Europa League]]: [[2017\u201318 UEFA Europa League|2017\u201318]]<ref name=europa>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2018/may/16/marseille-v-atletico-madrid-europa-league-final-live|title=Marseille 0-3 Atl\u00e9tico Madrid: 2018 Europa League final \u2013 as it happened|last=Murray|first=Scott|date=2018-05-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-31|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n*[[UEFA Super Cup]]: [[2018 UEFA Super Cup|2018]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global/2018/aug/15/real-madrid-atletico-madrid-european-super-cup-match-report|title=Diego Costa double helps Atl\u00e9tico beat Real Madrid 4-2 in Uefa Super Cup|last=sport|first=Guardian|date=2018-08-15|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-31|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[CAF Team of the Year]]: 2018<ref>{{cite news|title=Salah and Mane Picked in First Africa Best 11 |url=https://fifpro.org/news/salah-mahrez-and-mane-in-first-africa-best-11/en/|publisher=FIFPro |date=8 January 2019|accessdate=8 January 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Ghana Player of the Year]]: 2018,<ref name=ghana18>{{cite news |last1=Zurek |first1=Kweku |title=Ghana Football Awards: Partey named Footballer of the Year |url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/sports/sports-news/ghana-football-awards-partey-named-footballer-of-the-year.html |accessdate=10 March 2020 |publisher=Graphic |date=8 July 2018}}</ref> 2019<ref name=ghana19>{{cite news |last1=Douihech |first1=Mayssa |title=2019 Ghana Football Awards: Full list of winners |url=https://orangefootballclub.com/en/articles/2019-ghana-football-awards-winners/ |accessdate=10 March 2020 |publisher=Orange Football Club |date=22 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{BDFutbol}}\n*{{Futbolme profile|15062}}\n\n{{Atl\u00e9tico Madrid squad}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Ghana squads\n| bg        = #CA1118\n| fg        = #FBE816\n| bordercolor = black\n| list1 = \n{{Ghana squad 2017 Africa Cup of Nations}}\n{{Ghana squad 2019 Africa Cup of Nations}}\n}}\n{{Ghanaian Footballer of the Year}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Partey, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Eastern Region (Ghana)]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Atl\u00e9tico Madrid B players]]\n[[Category:RCD Mallorca players]]\n[[Category:UD Almer\u00eda players]]\n[[Category:Atl\u00e9tico Madrid footballers]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Ghana international footballers]]\n[[Category:2017 Africa Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:2019 Africa Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c6:1985:3400:51a:bb69:b2ce:7d7", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Partey"}
{"title_page": "Praveen Linga", "text_new": "{{short description|Chemical engineering professor (b. 1979)}}\n{{Autobiography|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Praveen Linga\n| image         = Prof Linga in his lab.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| caption       = Linga in his lab at NUS\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = \n| birth_place   = [[India]]\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| death_cause   = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence     = [[Singapore]]\n| nationality   = \n| other_names   = \n| known_for     = \n| education     = [[University of Madras]] <br> [[Indian Institute of Technology Kharagpur]]<br>[[The University of British Columbia]]\n| employer      = [[National University of Singapore]] [[Singapore]]\n| occupation    = Academic\n| title         = Dean's Chair Associate Professor at the Department of Chemical and Biomolecular Engineering\n| boards        = \n| spouse        = \n| partner       = \n| children      = \n| parents       = \n| relatives     = \n| signature     = \n| website       = {{url|gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg}}\n| footnotes     = \n}}\n\n'''Praveen Linga''' is a professor at the [[National University of Singapore]]'s Department of Chemical and Biomolecular Engineering. He is also the co-founder of NewGen Gas Pte Ltd<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newgengas.com/index.php/our-technology-4|title=About Us|website=newgengas.com}}</ref>, a spin-off company that specializes in solidified natural gas (SNG) technology via [[clathrate hydrates]] for natural gas storage and transport.\n\n==Educational background==\nLinga was born on April 21, 1979 in Chennai, India. His father was an agriculturist. During his primary years of education, up to 3rd standard, he went to [[St. Mary's Home Matriculation School]] in Kothagiri, Tamil Nadu, India. From 6th to 12th standard, he studied at Infant Jesus Matriculation Higher Secondary School in Manali New Town, Chennai, India. He obtained his Bachelor of Technology degree in Chemical Engineering from [[Sriram Engineering College]] affiliated to the [[University of Madras]] in 2000. He then went on to pursue his Master of Technology degree at [[Indian Institute of Technology Kharagpur]] and graduated in 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kgpchronicle.iitkgp.ac.in/frsc-for-kgpian-praveen-linga/|title=FRSC for Kgpian Praveen Linga \u2013 The KGP Chronicle}}</ref> In 2004, he joined the Department of Chemical and Biological Engineering at [[The University of British Columbia]] to pursue his doctoral studies. Under the supervision of Professor Peter Englezos, he obtained his doctoral degree in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grad.ubc.ca/prospective-students/graduate-student-research/convocation-may-2009|title=Convocation May 2009|website=UBC Graduate and Postdoctoral Studies}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://academictree.org/etree/tree.php?pid=100963|title=E-Tree - Praveen Linga Family Tree|website=academictree.org}}</ref> He did his Postdoctoral fellowship in the Department of Chemical and Biological Engineering at [[The University of British Columbia]] for a year (2009-2010). He was the first in his family's lineage to pursue post graduation in education.\n\n==Career==\n\nIn 2010, he started his academic career at the National University of Singapore (NUS) as an Assistant Professor in the Department of Chemical and Biomolecular Engineering specializing in gas hydrates technology. In 2016, he was appointed as an Associate Professor with tenure and in 2019, he was appointed as the Dean's Chair Associate Professor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eng.nus.edu.sg/chbe/staff/chepl/ |title=Staff |publisher=www.eng.nus.edu.sg |date= |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref>\nHe is also a visiting professor of Guangzhou Institute of Energy Conversion<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg/Achievements/2018-2022_GIEC-CAS%20Institute%20Approval.jpeg |title=Instsute approval |publisher=gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg |date=2018 |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref> Chinese Academy of Sciences, Guangzhou, [[PR China]] and a visiting guest professor of [[Harbin Engineering University]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg/Achievements/Harbin%20Engineering%20University_Visiting%20Professor%20Appointment.jpeg |title=Visiting professors |publisher=gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg |date= |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref> [[PR China]].\n\nHe is a licensed Professional Engineer (P.Eng.) in Singapore. He also serves as a scientific editor in various engineering journals \n* Subject Editor: [[Applied Energy]] (Elsevier)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.journals.elsevier.com/applied-energy/editorial-board|title=Applied Energy Editorial Board|via=www.journals.elsevier.com}}</ref>\n* Associate Editor: Journal of Natural Gas Science and Engineering (Elsevier)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.journals.elsevier.com/journal-of-natural-gas-science-and-engineering/editorial-board|title=Journal of Natural Gas Science and Engineering Editorial Board|via=www.journals.elsevier.com}}</ref>\n* Editorial Advisory Board Member: [[Energy & Fuels]] (ACS Publisher)<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://pubs.acs.org/journal/enfuem|title=Energy & Fuels|website=pubs.acs.org|doi=10.1021/enfuem|doi-broken-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n* Editorial Advisory Board Member: [[Fluid Phase Equilibria]] (Elsevier)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.journals.elsevier.com/fluid-phase-equilibria/editorial-board/p-linga|title=P. Linga|website=www.journals.elsevier.com}}</ref>\n\n==Research areas==\n\nLinga's research interests are in the areas of [[clathrate hydrate]] or gas hydrate, energy storage, carbon dioxide capture and storage (CCS) and energy recovery. His targeted applications are seawater desalination, gas storage, data center cooling and carbon capture & storage. A part of his research is also focused on energy recovery from [[methane hydrate]], which is considered as a huge energy resource for natural gas.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S030626191401318X|title=Review of natural gas hydrates as an energy resource: Prospects and challenges|first1=Zheng Rong|last1=Chong|first2=She Hern Bryan|last2=Yang|first3=Ponnivalavan|last3=Babu|first4=Praveen|last4=Linga|first5=Xiao-Sen|last5=Li|date=January 15, 2016|journal=Applied Energy|volume=162|pages=1633\u20131652|via=ScienceDirect|doi=10.1016/j.apenergy.2014.12.061}}</ref>\n\nHis research group has been working on process innovation and process development to scale-up [[clathrate hydrate]] as a technology enabler for clean energy and sustainable applications.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/eco-friendly-ways-to-harness-natural-gas-efficiently|title=Eco-friendly ways to harness natural gas efficiently|date=June 30, 2017|website=The Straits Times}}</ref> These applications include seawater desalination<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.engineersaustralia.org.au/News/drinkable-water-cold-energy|title=Drinkable water from cold energy &#124; Engineers Australia|website=www.engineersaustralia.org.au}}</ref>, solidified natural gas (SNG) technology for gas storage<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/vision-to-make-electric-cars-popular-by-2050|title=Vision to make electric cars popular by 2050|date=June 4, 2016|website=The Straits Times}}</ref>, development of a new cooling technology for data centre with [[clathrate hydrates]] as a medium.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.nus.edu.sg/press-releases/new-cooling-technology-for-data-centres|title=NUS, Keppel and SLNG join forces to develop new energy-efficient cooling technology for data centres|website=NUS News}}</ref>.\n\n==Honours and awards==\n\nIn 2018, [[Clarivate Analytics]] named him as one of the World's Most Influential Scientific Minds<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.nus.edu.sg/press-releases/highly-cited-researchers-2018|title=30 NUS researchers among the world's most highly cited researchers|website=NUS News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref> and Highly Cited Researchers in Engineering.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apsc.ubc.ca/news/2019/01/apsc-alumni-included-global-list-of-highly-cited-researchers|title=APSC alumni included in global list of highly cited researchers &#124; UBC Applied Science|website=apsc.ubc.ca}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg/Achievements/2018_11_27_Highly%20Cited%20Researcher%20Award.tiff |title=Award lsit |publisher=gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg |date=2018 |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref> He is one of the recipients of the SCEJ Award for Outstanding Asian Researcher and Engineer in 2020.<ref>http://www.scej.org/docs/en/awards/scej-award-for-oare/winner.pdf</ref> This prestigious award is given annually to individuals who have accomplished outstanding achievements in chemical engineering in Asia by the Society of Chemical Engineers, Japan (SCEJ).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scej.org/en/awards/scej-award-for-oare.html|title=The SCEJ Award for Outstanding Asian Researcher and Engineer}}</ref> In 2017, he was awarded the Donald W. Davidson Award at the 9th International Conference on Gas Hydrates (ICGH9) held in Denver USA for his outstanding contributions to gas hydrate research.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg/Achievements/2017_06_28-Don%20Davidson%20Award%20ICGH%20Conference.jpeg |title=Award list |publisher=gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg |date=2017 |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eng.nus.edu.sg/news/nus-engineering-researchers-win-two-top-awards-at-the-9th-international-conference-on-gas-hydrates/ |title=Researchers win two awards |publisher=www.eng.nus.edu.sg |date= |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref> He was awarded the prestigious Young Researcher Award (YRA) in NUS in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nus.edu.sg/uawards/2017/praveen_linga.php |title=National University of Singapore - University Awards 2017 |publisher=NUS |date= |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref> He is an elected fellow of the Royal Society of Chemistry in United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eng.nus.edu.sg/news/dr-praveen-linga-elected-fellow-of-royal-society-of-chemistry/ |title=Info |publisher=www.eng.nus.edu.sg |date= |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg/Achievements/2019_06_FRSC%20Certificate.png |title=Achievements |publisher=gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg |date=2019 |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n\nFor his teaching, he received the Annual Teaching Excellence Award (ATEA) in 2017 from [[National University of Singapore]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nus.edu.sg/cdtl/teaching-and-learning-quality/teaching-awards/teaching-award-winners/past-annual-teaching-excellence-award-(atea)-winners|title=Past Annual Teaching Excellence Award (ATEA) Winners|website=nus.edu.sg}}</ref> ATEA is awarded to faculty members who have displayed a high level of commitment to their teaching for the year under review.\n\n==Selected publications==\nLinga has published more than 100 peer-reviewed journal articles with an h index of 46.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholar.google.com.sg/citations?hl=en&user=6NpSa1kAAAAJ&view_op=list_works&sortby=pubdate|title=Praveen Linga PhD, PEng, FRSC - Google Scholar Citations|website=scholar.google.com.sg|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> A selected list of the review papers published by his group are listed below.\n* He, T.; Chong, Z. R.; Zheng, J.; Ju, Y.; Linga, P. LNG Cold Energy Utilization: Prospects and Challenges. Energy 2019, 170, 557\u2013568. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1016/j.energy.2018.12.170 10.1016/j.energy.2018.12.170]\n* Babu, P.; Nambiar, A.; He, T.; Karimi, I.A.; Lee, J. D.; Englezos, P.; Linga, P. A review of clathrate hydrate based desalination to strengthen energy-water nexus. ACS Sustainable Chemistry & Engineering 2018, 6 (7), 8093\u20138107. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1021/acssuschemeng.8b01616 10.1021/acssuschemeng.8b01616]\n* Veluswamy, H. P.; Kumar, A.; Seo, Y.; Lee, J. D.; Linga, P. A review of solidified natural gas (SNG) technology for gas storage via clathrate hydrates. Applied Energy (2018), 216, 262\u2013285. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1016/j.apenergy.2018.02.059 10.1016/j.apenergy.2018.02.059]\n* Yin, Z.; Khurana, M.; Tan, H.K.; Linga, P. A review of gas hydrate growth kinetic models Chemical Engineering Journal (2018), 342, 9-29. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1016/j.cej.2018.01.120 10.1016/j.cej.2018.01.120]\n* Khurana, M.; Yin, Z.; Linga, P. A review of clathrate hydrate nucleation ACS Sustainable Chemistry and Engineering (2017), 5 (12), 11176\u201311203. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1021/acssuschemeng.7b03238 10.1021/acssuschemeng.7b03238]\n* Yin, Z.; Chong, Z. R.; Tan, H. K.; Linga, P. Review of gas hydrate dissociation kinetic models for energy recovery. Journal of Natural Gas Science and Engineering (2016), 35, 1362\u20131387. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1016/j.jngse.2016.04.050 10.1016/j.jngse.2016.04.050]\n* Chong, Z. R.; Yang, S. H. B.; Babu, P.; Linga, P.; Li, X.-S. Review of natural gas hydrates as an energy resource: Prospects and Challenges. Applied Energy (2016), 162, 1633\u20131652. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1016/j.apenergy.2014.12.061 10.1016/j.apenergy.2014.12.061]\n* Babu, P.; Linga, P.; Kumar, R.*; Englezos, P. A review of the hydrate based gas separation (HBGS) process for carbon dioxide pre-combustion capture. Energy (2015), 85, 261\u2013279. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1016/j.energy.2015.03.103 10.1016/j.energy.2015.03.103]\n* Veluswamy, H. P.; Kumar, R.; Linga, P. Hydrogen storage in clathrate hydrates: Current state of the art and future directions. Applied Energy (2014), 122, 112\u2013132. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1016/j.apenergy.2014.01.063 10.1016/j.apenergy.2014.01.063]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* {{cite web|url=http://orcid.org/0000-0002-1466-038X\n|title=Praveen Linga's ORCiD profile\n|date=\n|publisher=ORCiD\n|accessdate=}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg/ Linga lab]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Linga, Praveen}}\n[[Category:National University of Singapore faculty]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Chennai]]\n[[Category:University of British Columbia alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Madras alumni]]\n[[Category:Indian Institute of Technology Kharagpur alumni]]\n[[Category:University of the Chinese Academy of Sciences faculty]]\n[[Category:Harbin Engineering University faculty]]\n[[Category:Singaporean engineers]]\n[[Category:Indian chemical engineers]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Chemistry]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Chemical engineering professor (b. 1979)}}\n{{Autobiography|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Praveen Linga\n| image         = Prof Linga in his lab.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| caption       = Linga in his lab at NUS\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = \n| birth_place   = [[India]]\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| death_cause   = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence     = [[Singapore]]\n| nationality   = \n| other_names   = \n| known_for     = \n| education     = [[University of Madras]] <br> [[Indian Institute of Technology Kharagpur]]<br>[[The University of British Columbia]]\n| employer      = [[National University of Singapore]] [[Singapore]]\n| occupation    = Academic\n| title         = Dean's Chair Associate Professor at the Department of Chemical and Biomolecular Engineering\n| boards        = \n| spouse        = \n| partner       = \n| children      = \n| parents       = \n| relatives     = \n| signature     = \n| website       = {{url|gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg}}\n| footnotes     = \n}}\n\n'''Praveen Linga''' is a professor at the [[National University of Singapore]]'s Department of Chemical and Biomolecular Engineering. He is also the co-founder of NewGen Gas Pte Ltd<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newgengas.com/index.php/our-technology-4|title=About Us|website=newgengas.com}}</ref>, a spin-off company that specializes in solidified natural gas (SNG) technology via [[clathrate hydrates]] for natural gas storage and transport.\n\n==Educational background==\nLinga was born on April 21, 1979 in Chennai, India. His father was an agriculturist. During his primary years of education, up to 3rd standard, he went to [[St. Mary's Home Matriculation School]] in Kothagiri, Tamil Nadu, India. From 6th to 12th standard, he studied at Infant Jesus Matriculation Higher Secondary School in Manali New Town, Chennai, India. He obtained his Bachelor of Technology degree in Chemical Engineering from Sri Ram Engineering College affiliated to the [[University of Madras]] in 2000. He then went on to pursue his Master of Technology degree at [[Indian Institute of Technology Kharagpur]] and graduated in 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kgpchronicle.iitkgp.ac.in/frsc-for-kgpian-praveen-linga/|title=FRSC for Kgpian Praveen Linga \u2013 The KGP Chronicle}}</ref> In 2004, he joined the Department of Chemical and Biological Engineering at [[The University of British Columbia]] to pursue his doctoral studies. Under the supervision of Professor Peter Englezos, he obtained his doctoral degree in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grad.ubc.ca/prospective-students/graduate-student-research/convocation-may-2009|title=Convocation May 2009|website=UBC Graduate and Postdoctoral Studies}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://academictree.org/etree/tree.php?pid=100963|title=E-Tree - Praveen Linga Family Tree|website=academictree.org}}</ref> He did his Postdoctoral fellowship in the Department of Chemical and Biological Engineering at [[The University of British Columbia]] for a year (2009-2010). He was the first in his family's lineage to pursue post graduation in education.\n\n==Career==\n\nIn 2010, he started his academic career at the National University of Singapore (NUS) as an Assistant Professor in the Department of Chemical and Biomolecular Engineering specializing in gas hydrates technology. In 2016, he was appointed as an Associate Professor with tenure and in 2019, he was appointed as the Dean's Chair Associate Professor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eng.nus.edu.sg/chbe/staff/chepl/ |title=Staff |publisher=www.eng.nus.edu.sg |date= |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref>\nHe is also a visiting professor of Guangzhou Institute of Energy Conversion<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg/Achievements/2018-2022_GIEC-CAS%20Institute%20Approval.jpeg |title=Instsute approval |publisher=gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg |date=2018 |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref> Chinese Academy of Sciences, Guangzhou, [[PR China]] and a visiting guest professor of [[Harbin Engineering University]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg/Achievements/Harbin%20Engineering%20University_Visiting%20Professor%20Appointment.jpeg |title=Visiting professors |publisher=gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg |date= |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref> [[PR China]].\n\nHe is a licensed Professional Engineer (P.Eng.) in Singapore. He also serves as a scientific editor in various engineering journals \n* Subject Editor: [[Applied Energy]] (Elsevier)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.journals.elsevier.com/applied-energy/editorial-board|title=Applied Energy Editorial Board|via=www.journals.elsevier.com}}</ref>\n* Associate Editor: Journal of Natural Gas Science and Engineering (Elsevier)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.journals.elsevier.com/journal-of-natural-gas-science-and-engineering/editorial-board|title=Journal of Natural Gas Science and Engineering Editorial Board|via=www.journals.elsevier.com}}</ref>\n* Editorial Advisory Board Member: [[Energy & Fuels]] (ACS Publisher)<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://pubs.acs.org/journal/enfuem|title=Energy & Fuels|website=pubs.acs.org|doi=10.1021/enfuem|doi-broken-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n* Editorial Advisory Board Member: [[Fluid Phase Equilibria]] (Elsevier)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.journals.elsevier.com/fluid-phase-equilibria/editorial-board/p-linga|title=P. Linga|website=www.journals.elsevier.com}}</ref>\n\n==Research areas==\n\nLinga's research interests are in the areas of [[clathrate hydrate]] or gas hydrate, energy storage, carbon dioxide capture and storage (CCS) and energy recovery. His targeted applications are seawater desalination, gas storage, data center cooling and carbon capture & storage. A part of his research is also focused on energy recovery from [[methane hydrate]], which is considered as a huge energy resource for natural gas.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S030626191401318X|title=Review of natural gas hydrates as an energy resource: Prospects and challenges|first1=Zheng Rong|last1=Chong|first2=She Hern Bryan|last2=Yang|first3=Ponnivalavan|last3=Babu|first4=Praveen|last4=Linga|first5=Xiao-Sen|last5=Li|date=January 15, 2016|journal=Applied Energy|volume=162|pages=1633\u20131652|via=ScienceDirect|doi=10.1016/j.apenergy.2014.12.061}}</ref>\n\nHis research group has been working on process innovation and process development to scale-up [[clathrate hydrate]] as a technology enabler for clean energy and sustainable applications.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/eco-friendly-ways-to-harness-natural-gas-efficiently|title=Eco-friendly ways to harness natural gas efficiently|date=June 30, 2017|website=The Straits Times}}</ref> These applications include seawater desalination<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.engineersaustralia.org.au/News/drinkable-water-cold-energy|title=Drinkable water from cold energy &#124; Engineers Australia|website=www.engineersaustralia.org.au}}</ref>, solidified natural gas (SNG) technology for gas storage<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/vision-to-make-electric-cars-popular-by-2050|title=Vision to make electric cars popular by 2050|date=June 4, 2016|website=The Straits Times}}</ref>, development of a new cooling technology for data centre with [[clathrate hydrates]] as a medium.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.nus.edu.sg/press-releases/new-cooling-technology-for-data-centres|title=NUS, Keppel and SLNG join forces to develop new energy-efficient cooling technology for data centres|website=NUS News}}</ref>.\n\n==Honours and awards==\n\nIn 2018, [[Clarivate Analytics]] named him as one of the World's Most Influential Scientific Minds<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.nus.edu.sg/press-releases/highly-cited-researchers-2018|title=30 NUS researchers among the world's most highly cited researchers|website=NUS News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref> and Highly Cited Researchers in Engineering.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apsc.ubc.ca/news/2019/01/apsc-alumni-included-global-list-of-highly-cited-researchers|title=APSC alumni included in global list of highly cited researchers &#124; UBC Applied Science|website=apsc.ubc.ca}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg/Achievements/2018_11_27_Highly%20Cited%20Researcher%20Award.tiff |title=Award lsit |publisher=gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg |date=2018 |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref> He is one of the recipients of the SCEJ Award for Outstanding Asian Researcher and Engineer in 2020.<ref>http://www.scej.org/docs/en/awards/scej-award-for-oare/winner.pdf</ref> This prestigious award is given annually to individuals who have accomplished outstanding achievements in chemical engineering in Asia by the Society of Chemical Engineers, Japan (SCEJ).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scej.org/en/awards/scej-award-for-oare.html|title=The SCEJ Award for Outstanding Asian Researcher and Engineer}}</ref> In 2017, he was awarded the Donald W. Davidson Award at the 9th International Conference on Gas Hydrates (ICGH9) held in Denver USA for his outstanding contributions to gas hydrate research.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg/Achievements/2017_06_28-Don%20Davidson%20Award%20ICGH%20Conference.jpeg |title=Award list |publisher=gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg |date=2017 |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eng.nus.edu.sg/news/nus-engineering-researchers-win-two-top-awards-at-the-9th-international-conference-on-gas-hydrates/ |title=Researchers win two awards |publisher=www.eng.nus.edu.sg |date= |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref> He was awarded the prestigious Young Researcher Award (YRA) in NUS in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nus.edu.sg/uawards/2017/praveen_linga.php |title=National University of Singapore - University Awards 2017 |publisher=NUS |date= |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref> He is an elected fellow of the Royal Society of Chemistry in United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eng.nus.edu.sg/news/dr-praveen-linga-elected-fellow-of-royal-society-of-chemistry/ |title=Info |publisher=www.eng.nus.edu.sg |date= |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg/Achievements/2019_06_FRSC%20Certificate.png |title=Achievements |publisher=gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg |date=2019 |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n\nFor his teaching, he received the Annual Teaching Excellence Award (ATEA) in 2017 from [[National University of Singapore]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nus.edu.sg/cdtl/teaching-and-learning-quality/teaching-awards/teaching-award-winners/past-annual-teaching-excellence-award-(atea)-winners|title=Past Annual Teaching Excellence Award (ATEA) Winners|website=nus.edu.sg}}</ref> ATEA is awarded to faculty members who have displayed a high level of commitment to their teaching for the year under review.\n\n==Selected publications==\nLinga has published more than 100 peer-reviewed journal articles with an h index of 46.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholar.google.com.sg/citations?hl=en&user=6NpSa1kAAAAJ&view_op=list_works&sortby=pubdate|title=Praveen Linga PhD, PEng, FRSC - Google Scholar Citations|website=scholar.google.com.sg|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> A selected list of the review papers published by his group are listed below.\n* He, T.; Chong, Z. R.; Zheng, J.; Ju, Y.; Linga, P. LNG Cold Energy Utilization: Prospects and Challenges. Energy 2019, 170, 557\u2013568. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1016/j.energy.2018.12.170 10.1016/j.energy.2018.12.170]\n* Babu, P.; Nambiar, A.; He, T.; Karimi, I.A.; Lee, J. D.; Englezos, P.; Linga, P. A review of clathrate hydrate based desalination to strengthen energy-water nexus. ACS Sustainable Chemistry & Engineering 2018, 6 (7), 8093\u20138107. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1021/acssuschemeng.8b01616 10.1021/acssuschemeng.8b01616]\n* Veluswamy, H. P.; Kumar, A.; Seo, Y.; Lee, J. D.; Linga, P. A review of solidified natural gas (SNG) technology for gas storage via clathrate hydrates. Applied Energy (2018), 216, 262\u2013285. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1016/j.apenergy.2018.02.059 10.1016/j.apenergy.2018.02.059]\n* Yin, Z.; Khurana, M.; Tan, H.K.; Linga, P. A review of gas hydrate growth kinetic models Chemical Engineering Journal (2018), 342, 9-29. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1016/j.cej.2018.01.120 10.1016/j.cej.2018.01.120]\n* Khurana, M.; Yin, Z.; Linga, P. A review of clathrate hydrate nucleation ACS Sustainable Chemistry and Engineering (2017), 5 (12), 11176\u201311203. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1021/acssuschemeng.7b03238 10.1021/acssuschemeng.7b03238]\n* Yin, Z.; Chong, Z. R.; Tan, H. K.; Linga, P. Review of gas hydrate dissociation kinetic models for energy recovery. Journal of Natural Gas Science and Engineering (2016), 35, 1362\u20131387. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1016/j.jngse.2016.04.050 10.1016/j.jngse.2016.04.050]\n* Chong, Z. R.; Yang, S. H. B.; Babu, P.; Linga, P.; Li, X.-S. Review of natural gas hydrates as an energy resource: Prospects and Challenges. Applied Energy (2016), 162, 1633\u20131652. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1016/j.apenergy.2014.12.061 10.1016/j.apenergy.2014.12.061]\n* Babu, P.; Linga, P.; Kumar, R.*; Englezos, P. A review of the hydrate based gas separation (HBGS) process for carbon dioxide pre-combustion capture. Energy (2015), 85, 261\u2013279. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1016/j.energy.2015.03.103 10.1016/j.energy.2015.03.103]\n* Veluswamy, H. P.; Kumar, R.; Linga, P. Hydrogen storage in clathrate hydrates: Current state of the art and future directions. Applied Energy (2014), 122, 112\u2013132. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1016/j.apenergy.2014.01.063 10.1016/j.apenergy.2014.01.063]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* {{cite web|url=http://orcid.org/0000-0002-1466-038X\n|title=Praveen Linga's ORCiD profile\n|date=\n|publisher=ORCiD\n|accessdate=}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg/ Linga lab]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Linga, Praveen}}\n[[Category:National University of Singapore faculty]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Chennai]]\n[[Category:University of British Columbia alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Madras alumni]]\n[[Category:Indian Institute of Technology Kharagpur alumni]]\n[[Category:University of the Chinese Academy of Sciences faculty]]\n[[Category:Harbin Engineering University faculty]]\n[[Category:Singaporean engineers]]\n[[Category:Indian chemical engineers]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Chemistry]]\n", "name_user": "Sandpidu2", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEducational background", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Praveen_Linga"}
