{"title_page": "The Problem (album)", "text_new": "{{unreferenced|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Problem\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[Mathematics (producer)|DJ Mathematics]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = June 28, 2005\n| recorded   = 2004-2005\n| venue      =\n| studio     = \n| genre      = [[Hip hop music|Rap]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Nature Sounds]]\n| producer   = [[Mathematics (producer)|DJ Mathematics]]\n| prev_title = [[Love, Hell or Right]]\n| prev_year  = 2003\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n'''''The Problem''''' is an album by [[Wu-Tang Clan]] DJ [[Mathematics (producer)|Mathematics]], released on June 28, 2005 by [[Nature Sounds]]. Most tracks have cameos by members of the Wu-Tang Clan. ''The Problem'' is Mathematics' second solo album. It Feat The young upcoming Hot Flamez who's now know as Hahflamez. Track 4 \"can i rise\" is one of the most prolific songs of its generation. Wu-Tang Forever\n\n==Track listing==\n#\"Intro\"\n#\"C What I C\" (T-Slugz and Eyeslow)\n#\"Strawberries & Cream\" ([[Allah Real]], [[Inspectah Deck]], [[The RZA]] and [[Ghostface Killah]])\n#\"Can I Rise\" (Hot Flamez)\n#\"John  \u2013 3:16\" ([[Method Man]] and Panama P.I.)\n#\"Winta Sno\" (Eyeslow, L.S., and Ali Vegas)\n#\"Two Shots Of Henny\" (Buddah Bless, Angie Neil, Hot Flamez, Eyeslow, Panama P.I. and Allah Real)\n#\"Bullet Scar\" (T-Slugz)\n#\"Real Nillaz\" (Ghostface Killah, Buddah Bless, Eyeslow, and [[Raekwon]])\n#\"Coach Talk\" (Bald Head)\n#\"Rush\" (Method Man and [[GZA]])\n#\"U.S.A.\" (Ghostface Killah, [[Masta Killa]], Todd, Panama P.I., Eyeslow and Hot Flamez)\n#\"Tommy\" (Allah Real, Eyeslow, Angie Neil and Bald Head)\n#\"Break That\" ([[Ol Dirty Bastard]], Masta Killa and [[U-God]])\n#\"Spot Lite\" (Method Man, U-God, [[Inspectah Deck]] and [[Cappadonna]]) [bonus track]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Problem}}\n[[Category:Mathematics (producer) albums]]\n[[Category:2005 albums]]\n[[Category:Nature Sounds albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Mathematics]]\n", "text_old": "{{unreferenced|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Problem\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[Mathematics (producer)|DJ Mathematics]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = June 28, 2005\n| recorded   = 2004-2005\n| venue      =\n| studio     = \n| genre      = [[Hip hop music|Rap]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Nature Sounds]]\n| producer   = [[Mathematics (producer)|DJ Mathematics]]\n| prev_title = [[Love, Hell or Right]]\n| prev_year  = 2003\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n'''''The Problem''''' is an album by [[Wu-Tang Clan]] DJ [[Mathematics (producer)|Mathematics]], released on June 28, 2005 by [[Nature Sounds]]. Most tracks have cameos by members of the Wu-Tang Clan. ''The Problem'' is Mathematics' second solo album. \n\n==Track listing==\n#\"Intro\"\n#\"C What I C\" (T-Slugz and Eyeslow)\n#\"Strawberries & Cream\" ([[Allah Real]], [[Inspectah Deck]], [[The RZA]] and [[Ghostface Killah]])\n#\"Can I Rise\" (Hot Flamez)\n#\"John  \u2013 3:16\" ([[Method Man]] and Panama P.I.)\n#\"Winta Sno\" (Eyeslow, L.S., and Ali Vegas)\n#\"Two Shots Of Henny\" (Buddah Bless, Angie Neil, Hot Flamez, Eyeslow, Panama P.I. and Allah Real)\n#\"Bullet Scar\" (T-Slugz)\n#\"Real Nillaz\" (Ghostface Killah, Buddah Bless, Eyeslow, and [[Raekwon]])\n#\"Coach Talk\" (Bald Head)\n#\"Rush\" (Method Man and [[GZA]])\n#\"U.S.A.\" (Ghostface Killah, [[Masta Killa]], Todd, Panama P.I., Eyeslow and Hot Flamez)\n#\"Tommy\" (Allah Real, Eyeslow, Angie Neil and Bald Head)\n#\"Break That\" ([[Ol Dirty Bastard]], Masta Killa and [[U-God]])\n#\"Spot Lite\" (Method Man, U-God, [[Inspectah Deck]] and [[Cappadonna]]) [bonus track]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Problem}}\n[[Category:Mathematics (producer) albums]]\n[[Category:2005 albums]]\n[[Category:Nature Sounds albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Mathematics]]\n", "name_user": "2604:2000:1201:8806:e156:bb8c:fa21:a563", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fixed typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Problem_(album)"}
{"title_page": "Nick Cross", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian independent animator|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n'''Nick Cross''' is a [[Canada|Canadian]] independent animator. His works include ''The Waif of Persephone'', ''Yellow Cake'', ''Pig Farmer'', and ''Black Sunrise'',<ref name=\"pig\">{{cite journal|author=Ritika Bhandari|journal=Animation Reporter Magazine|title=Pig Farmer|issue=May 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"ASIFA\">{{citation|people=Danny Young, Michael Woodside|title=Nick Cross interview|publisher=ASIFA-Hollywood Animation Archive|date=March 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"king\">{{cite journal|title=King of Videos|journal=Ottawa Magazine|issue=October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{citation|work=Catsuka|publisher=NOLIFE|url=http://www.catsuka.com/player.php?id=catsuka_emission_30|title=Nick Cross|year=2011}}</ref> which he wrote, directed, animated and produced. He is friends with [[graphic novel]] artist [[Troy Little]]<ref name=\"fulle\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fullecirclemagazine.com/2008/06/conversation-with-nick-cross.html|title=Conversation with Nick Cross|author=Jason Anders|work=Fulle Circle Magazine|date=2008|accessdate=June 29, 2015}}</ref> and they collaborated on the development of the animated series ''Angora Napkin''. He directed the pilot for the [[Nickelodeon]] series ''[[Pig Goat Banana Cricket]]'' created by graphic novel creator [[Dave Cooper]] and [[alternative comics]] creator [[Johnny Ryan]]. He was the art director for the [[Cartoon Network]] acclaimed miniseries ''[[Over the Garden Wall]]'' as well as the [[Cartoon Network Shorts Department|network's shorts development program]]. He is currently supervising producer on the upcoming Cartoon Network series ''Tig n' Seek''.\n\nHe is married to cartoonist [[Marlo Meekins]].\n\n==Black Sunrise==\n''Black Sunrise'' is a planned feature-film, produced and animated entirely by Nick Cross. Cross began the film before the rise in popularity of the internet, at which time he considered notions like [[the Illuminati]] and secret societies more mysterious and interesting to the general public than they are today. After completing 15 minutes of animation, time constraints prevented Cross from continuing his work on the film. Cross believes that the film, if completed, will not be received favorably because the topic of secret societies is overexposed, but he might still release segments of the film.<ref>{{cite|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LmiLxmAOJIk|title=Startoon Cartoon Podcast - Episode 19 - The One With Nick Cross Part 2|date=December 13, 2017|time=the start of the video and later from 20 minutes onward|accessdate=June 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{{BLP sources section|date=April 2016}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" width=100%\n|-style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n! width=50px| Year\n! width=300px | Title\n! Credit\n! Notes\n! width=30px | Ref.\n|-\n| 1997 || ''[[Rupert (TV series)|Rupert]]'' || layout artist || 13 episodes ||\n|-\n| 2001\u20132003 || ''[[Untalkative Bunny]]'' || storyboard artist ||  ||  \n|-\n| 2001 || ''The Red Scarf'' || producer, writer, animator, director ||  || <ref>{{cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/40332276|title=The Red Scarf|author=Nick Cross|date=April 13, 2012|accessdate=May 3, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2001\u20132002 || ''[[The Ripping Friends]]'' || model clean-up ||  || \n|-\n| 2003 || ''[[Ren & Stimpy Adult Party Cartoon]]'' || art director, background designer, storyboard artist || || \n|- \n| \"align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\"|2006 || ''[[Tenacious D]]'' - \"Classico\" || background artist ||  || <ref name=\"fulle\" />\n|- \n| ''The Waif of Persephone'' || producer, writer, animator, director ||  || <ref name=\"ASIFA\" />\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[Wayside (TV series)|Wayside]]'' || storyboard artist || 2 episodes || \n|-\n| 2008 || [[Danko Jones]] - \"King of Magazines\" || animator, co-director || Collaboration with [[Dave Cooper]] and Steve Stefanelli. || <ref name=\"king\" />\n|-\n| \"align=\"center\" rowspan=\"3\"|2009 || ''Angora Napkin'' || co-creator, designer, animator, storyboard artist, background artist, layout artist, director || Collaboration with [[Troy Little]]. ||\n|-\n| ''[[Jimmy Two-Shoes]]'' || storyboard artist || \"Meet the Gnomans\" || \n|-\n| ''Yellow Cake'' || producer, writer, animator, director  ||  || <ref name=\"ASIFA\" />\n|-\n| 2010 || ''[[Scaredy Squirrel (TV series)|Scaredy Squirrel]]'' || \"align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\"|storyboard artist || \"Captain Nuts\" || \n|- \n| 2010\u20132011 || ''[[Babar and the Adventures of Badou]]'' || 15 episodes || \n|-\n| 2011 || ''The Pig Farmer'' || producer, writer, animator, director ||  || <ref name=\"pig\" />\n|-\n| 2012 || ''Pig Goat Banana Mantis!'' || \"align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\"|animator, director ||  || <ref name=\"Andreeva 2013\">{{cite web|author=Andreeva, Nellie|date=September 26, 2013|url=http://deadline.com/2013/09/nickelodeon-orders-two-animated-series-four-live-action-pilots-597541/|title=Nickelodeon Orders Two Animated Series, Four Live-Action Pilots|work=Deadline Hollywood|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|accessdate=November 6, 2014|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6TsLDjaPI|archivedate=November 6, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| \"align=\"center\" rowspan=\"3\"|2013 || ''Perihelion'' || || <ref>{{cite|url=https://vimeo.com/62456806|title=Perihelion|author=Nick Cross|date=March 22, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[The Day My Butt Went Psycho!]] || storyboard artist ||  || <ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305114819/https:/twitter.com/ncrossanimation/status/606575643204067328|archive-date=March 5, 2016|url=https://twitter.com/ncrossanimation/status/606575643204067328|title=Nick Cross @BrandonMurphyy i feel like i should warn you...............|accessdate=June 23, 2016|date=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Tome of the Unknown]]'' || background painter || Nick Cross awarded Emmy for Outstanding Individual Achievement in Animation. || <ref name=\"Emmy2015\">{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/sites/default/files/Downloads/2015-creative-arts-winners-v1.pdf|title=2015 Creative Arts Emmy Awards Winners|publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]]|date=September 12, 2015|accessdate=September 15, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| \"align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\"|2014 || ''[[Over the Garden Wall]]'' || \"align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\"|art director || Nick Cross awarded Emmy for Outstanding Individual Achievement in Animation. || <ref name=\"Emmy2015\" />\n|-\n| ''[[Back to Backspace]]'' ||  ||\n|- \n| \"align=\"center\" rowspan=\"10\"|2015 || ''[[The SpongeBob Movie: Sponge Out of Water]]'' || storyboard artist || Time travel sequence || <ref>{{cite web|url=http://ncrossanimation.tumblr.com/post/110368879547/i-storyboarded-a-few-sequences-for-spongebob-movie|title=Spongebob Movie 2|author=Nick Cross|date=February 7, 2015|accessdate=June 29, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Jammers (film)|Jammers]]'' || \"align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\"|art director ||  ||\n|-\n| ''Ridin' with Burgess'' ||  ||\n|-\n| ''Twelve Forever'' || art director, background designer ||  ||\n|-\n| \"align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\"|''[[Uncle Grandpa]]'' || animator, storyboard artist, director || [[Bumper (broadcasting)|Bumpers]] in \"[[Guest Directed Shorts]]\" || <ref>{{cite web|url=http://ncrossanimation.tumblr.com/post/118338293687/i-see-your-working-on-an-episode-of-uncle-grandpa#notes|author=Nick Cross|title=Uncle Grandpa|date=May 6, 2015|accessdate=June 29, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| background painter || \"The Great Spaghetti Western\" || \n|-\n| ''[[Pig Goat Banana Cricket]]'' || storyboard artist, director || \"Pig Goat Banana Cricket High Five!\" ||\n|-\n| ''[[Apple & Onion]]'' || art director ||  ||\n|-\n| ''[[Welcome To My Life (Pilot)|Welcome to My Life]]'' || art director, background painter ||  ||\n|-\n| ''[[Long Live the Royals]]'' || character design || 2 episodes ||\n|-\n| \"align=\"center\" rowspan=\"4\"|2016 || ''Bottom's Butte'' || \"align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\"|art director, prop designer ||  